a boat, Irish eathar, ship, boat, Old Irish ethar, a boat, *itro-, "journeyer"; from ethaim, I go, *itâo, go, root ei, i; Latin eo; Greek @Ge@'@nimi; Lithuanian eimi; Sanskrit émi.
betweeen them, so Irish, Old Irish etarro, *etr@.-so, *enter-sôs. For sôs, See -sa.
cry; See éigh.
the aspen, letter e, Irish eadha; also eadha, q.v.
a live coal, spark, Irish eibhleóg, Early Irish óibell, spark, fire, Welsh ufel, fire, *oibelos, fire, spark (Stokes).
joyous; See aoibhinn.
a young gelded goat; from Scottish aiver (do.), with Gaelic termination of firionnach, etc. Aiver is also aver, worthless old horse, any property, English aver, property, from Latin habere.
clothing, a suit; See aodach.

ivy, Irish eidhean, Early Irish edenn, Welsh eiddew, Cornish idhio, *(p)edenno-, root ped, fasten, hold on; Latin pedica, a fetter; English fetter, etc. For sense, cf. Latin hedera, ivy, from ghed, catch, pr@oehendo, English get.
a web; apparently a shortened form of éideadh.
effect, so Irish; from Latin effectus.
a web, eididh (on analogy of éididh, *veggiâ, root of figh.  page 154
ice; See deigh. Hence eighre, oighre, Irish oidhir, Early Irish aigred, Welsh eiry, snow.
a file, Irish oighe: *agiâ; root ag of English axe, Gothic aqizi.
a cry, Irish éigheamh, Old Irish égem, Celtic root eig; Lettic ígt. Cf. also Latin aeger (Stokes, Zim).
a cloudberry; See oighreag.
necessity, Irish éigin, Old Irish écen, Welsh angen, *enknâ (Stokes); Greek @Ga@'nágkc (= a@'n-ágkc). Allied by root (ank:enk) to thig, etc.
an elder; from the Scotch, English elder.
other, another, Irish eile, Old Irish aile, Welsh aill, all, Breton eil, all, Gaulish allo-, *aljo-, *allo-; Latin alius; Greek @Ga@'/llos; English else.
mill-race, mill-dam, embankment; from ail, stone, "stone-work".
an Island, Irish oilean, Early Irish ailén; from Norse eyland, English island.
training; See oilean.
the notch on the staves of a cask where the bottom is fixed. (In Arg. èarrach):
a deer's walk, eileirig, where deer were driven to battue them. Hence the common place-name Elrick. Book of Deer in d-elerc?
sequestered region, etc.; See eilthir.
levelling of a field for sowing, first ploughing; cf. Irish eillgheadh, burial, to which Stokes cfs. Umbrian pelsatu, Greek @Gqáptein, pelsans, sepeliundus. H.Maclean compared the Basque elge, field.
a hind, so Irish, Old Irish elit, Welsh elain, cerva, *elinti-s, *elanî, Greek @Ge@'llós, fawn, e@'/lafos (= e@'/lnfos), stag; Lithuanian élnis, stag; Armenian e @Gln; etc.
willow-herb, epilobium; from Latin helix.
a bier (H.S.D. for Heb.), Irish eletrom, eleathrain, Middle Irish eilitrum; from Latin feretrum (Stokes).
a foreign land, eilthireach, a pilgrim, Irish oilithreach, Old Irish ailithre, pilgrimage; from eile and tìr, q.v.
rejoice:
bounty, Irish oineach. Cf. Old Irish ainech, protectio, root nak, attain, as in tiodhlac. Hence the H.S.D. eineachlann, protection (from Irish).
dyke or wall between crop-land and hill-land (M`F.):
moving, stirring; Early Irish airbert, use, airbiur, dego, fruor: air and beir, q.v.
asking indirectly: "side-say"; air+ beir; cf. abair.  page 155
slack-jointed or crippled person; cf. Scottish hirplock, lame creature, hirple. The possibility of air-ablach (cf. conablach) should be kept in view.
portcullis (M`D.):
a burden, Irish eire, Early Irish ere, Old Irish aire: *pario, root of air. Cf. Latin porto.

an assembly, Irish óireachdus, Early Irish airecht, Old Irish airect, *air-echt, echt being from the root of thig. Stokes refers it to the same origin as Welsh araeth, speech, root req, as in Old Slavonic reka, speak, Latin raccare, cry as a lion.
handsome, Old Irish airegde, præstans, from aire(ch), primas. See airidh.
a pullet, young hen, Irish eireog ( Fol., O'R.), Middle Irish eirin, Welsh iaren, Cornish yar, gallina, Breton iarik, *jari-, hen; Lithuanian jerube@?, heathcock, N.Slavonic jertu@u, nuthatch (Bez.).
a monster, clumsy old carle (Dial., H.S.D.); from eire.
heresy, so Irish, Early Irish éres, Old Irish heretic, hereticus; from the Old Irish form somehow, which itself is from Latin h@oereticus.

rise, éirigh, rising, Irish éirighim, éirghe, Early Irish érigim, éirgim, inf. Old Irish éirge, érge, *eks-regô; Latin e@-rigo, erect, English erect, rego, I govern; Greek o@'régw, extend; English right; Indo-European root reg. See rach.
attendance, patience, Old Irish airitiu, g. airiten, reception, airema, suscipiat, *ari-em-tin-, root em, grasp, take; Latin emo, buy; Lithuanian imù, hold.
ransom, Irish éiric, Early Irish éric, éiricc: *es-recc, "buying or selling out", from reic. Vb. as-renim, reddo, enclitic érnim, impendo.
hit, find out, Old Irish ermaissiu, attaining, irmadatar, intelligunt, irmissid, intelligatis, *air-mess-, *air-med-; root, med, as in meas, judgement, q.v.
delay, impediment; founded on déis?

listen, hear, Irish éisdim, Old Irish étsim. Ascoli analyses it into *étiss, *aith-do-iss, animum instare; the iss he doubtless means as from the reduplicated form of the root sta (cf. Old Irish air-issim, I stand). an-tus-, great silence! Cf. Irish éist do bhéal = hush! Root of tosd.
satirist, Irish eigeas, pl. eigse, a learned man, Early Irish écess: *ád-gen-s-to? See eagna.
dependence, obligation, Middle Irish esimol, an esimul, *ex-em-mo-lo, root em of eudail. Cf. Latin exemplum.
example, Irish eisiompláir, Middle Irish esimplair; from Latin exemplar.  page 156
oyster, Irish eisir, oisre; from Middle English oistre, from Latin ostrea.
the withe that ties the tail-beam to the pack-saddle, crupper:
grief: *an-slàn; cf. Irish eislinn, weak, Early Irish eslinn (do.): *ex-slàn; See slàn.
boards on which the corpse is laid, a shroud (H.S.D., from MSS.; M`E.):
unhusked ear of corn (M`E.):
stretching, extending:
burnt roots of heath:
white pebble, precious stone; from English hectic, lapis hecticus, the white hectic stone, used as a remedy against dysentery and diarrh@oea (Martin, West Isles, 134). See eitig.
a kernel, grain, Irish eitne eithne, Early Irish eitne (n.).

false, perjured, Irish eitheach, a lie, perjury, Old Irish ethech, perjurium; root pet, fall? Cf. Irish di-thech, denial on oath, for-tach, admission on oath, di-tongar i. séntar, fortoing, proved by oath: *tongô, swear. See freiteach for root.
refuse, Irish eitighim. For root, etc., See under freiteach.

fierce, dismal, Old Irish étig, turpe, adétche, abomination. Scarcely *an-teg-, "un-wonted, un-house-like" (Zim.), for Gaelic would be éidigh. This Stokes (Bez. Beit @+21) makes *an-teki-s, not fair, Welsh têg, fair, Greek @Gtíktw, produce, @Gtéknon, child, English thing. Still Gaelic should be éidigh.
go (Sutherland), dh'eithinn, would go, Irish eathaim, Early Irish ethaim, *itâô; root ei, i; Latin ire, itum; Greek @Gei@'@nmi, etc.
consumption; from Scottish etick, from French étique, hectique, English hectic.
storm, sorrow: *aith-ter-? See tuirse.
a charm; a metathesis of eòlas.
knowledge, Irish eól, eolas, Early Irish eólas, Old Irish heulas, d-eulus: *ivo-lestu?
barley, Irish eórna, Early Irish eorna, *jevo-rnio-, *jevo-; Greek @Gzeiá, spelt; Sanskrit yáva, corn, barley; Lithuanian jawai, corn.
languishing ( H.S.D. gives it as Dial.; M`E.); See feodhaich.
negative prefix, Irish ea-, éu-, Old Irish é-. It stands for an- before c, t, p, and s. See an-.
disease: an+ cáil, q.v.
a feat, exploit, Irish éachd, feat, covenant, condition; Early Irish écht, murder, slaughter, from éc (St.).
a fair maid, a charmer: "featsome one", from euchd.

jealousy, zeal, Irish éad, Old Irish ét, Welsh addiant (= add-iant), longing, regret, Gaulish iantu- in Iantumarus, *jantu-; Sanskrit  page 157  yatná, zeal; Greek @Gzctéw, seek, @Gzc@nlos, zeal, English zeal; root jâ, jat, strive.

treasure, cattle, Irish éadáil, eudáil, profit, prey, Early Irish étail, treasure, booty, Early Irish ét, herds, riches: *em-tâli-, root em, hold, as in Latin emo (see eiridinn). Also feudail. éd = áirneis no spréidh, O'Cl.
death, Irish eug, Old Irish éc, Welsh angeu, Cornish and Old Breton ancou, *enku-s, *enkevo-; Latin nex, death; Greek @Gnékus, corpse; Sanskrit nac@?, perish.
as eugais, without, Irish égmhuis, want, dispensation, Early Irish écmais: *an-comas, "non-power"?
negative prefix, as in eugsamhuil = an-con-samuil: See cosmhail.
creeping away; See èaladh.
a pearl (H.S.D. from MSS.), Old Irish ném, g. némann, pearl, níam, sheen, níamda, bright, Welsh nwyf, vigour, nwyfiant, brightness, vigour: *neim. Cf. neamhnuid.

a bird, Irish eun, Old Irish én, Old Welsh etn, Welsh edn, Cornish hethen, Breton ezn, *etno-s, *petno-, root pet, fly; Greek @Gpétomai, fly, @Gpetcná, fowls; Latin penna, wing; English feather; Sanskrit pátati, fly. Hence eunlaith, birds, Early Irish énlaith.
refuse, Irish eura, refusal, Early Irish éra, eraim, *ex-rajo- (n.), root râ, give, Welsh rhoi, give, Cornish ry, Breton reiff, give; Sanskrit ráti, give, Zend râ. See rath, luck, favour. F
under, Irish fa, Early Irish fa (as in distributive numbers); a side form of fo, q.v., used in adverbial expressions.

was (past of is), Middle Gaelic fa ( Dean of Lismore), Irish fa, fa h- (Keat.), Middle Irish fa h-, Early Irish ba h-, *bât, *(e)bhu-â-t; Latin -bat, -bamus, of refe-bam, etc.; root bheu, to be. See bu, the form now used.
favour, Irish fábhar, Welsh ffafr; from Latin favor.
a fault; from Scottish faut, from French faute.

abhra, eyelid, eyebrow, Irish abhra, fabhra, eyelid, Early Irish abra, n.pl. abrait, Cornish abrans, Breton abrant, eyebrow, Mac. Greek @Ga@'brou@ntes; further @Go@'frús, brow, English brow. There is an Early Irish bra, pl. brói, dual brúad, *bruvat-. The phonetics are not clear. Stokes has suggested Latin frons, frontis, as allied, *bhront- with the prep. a(p)o (= Early Irish -a-), ab.  page 158
swirl, eddy (Carm.). Cf. Old Irish fobar (St.).
word, Irish focal, Old Irish focul, from Latin vocabulum (through *focvul, Güterbock). Stokes and Wind. take it from Latin vocula.
the puffin - a water fowl (Sh.); root va, blow? Onomatopoetic: f-ah-ah, call of bird?
strife ( Sh.; H.S.D. marks it Dialectic); cf. Irish fachain, striving.
puny (H.S.D. for N.High.):
ridicule, scoffing; from fo-cainnt, "sub-speaking". Cf. Welsh gogan, satire, Breton goge, *vo-can, root can, sing, say.
long, Irish fad, Old Irish fota, longus, fot, length, *vad-dho- or vaz-dho-, Latin vastus, vast? Hence fadal, delay, desiderium, Keat. faddáil, "long delay", from fad and dáil.

kindling, Irish fadadh, fadaghadh, fadógh (Keat.), Middle Irish fatód, Early Irish átúd, which Zimmer analyses as *ad-soud (soud of iompaidh), but unsatisfactorily; Early Irish adsúi tenid, kindles, adsúithe, kindled (Meyer). Cf. fód.
trifling, paltry, fagharsach:
cuttle-fish:
a breeze:
leave, Irish fágaim, Old Irish foacbaim, fácbaim, *fo-ad-gab-; root gab of gabh, q.v.
near, Irish fogus, Early Irish focus, ocus, Old Irish accus, Welsh agos, Breton hôgoz, *aggostu-. See agus.
see, Irish faic, Old Irish im-aci, vides-ne, *ád-cî, See chì. The f is prothetic.

a green (by the house), Irish, Early Irish faithche, the field nearest the house, Early Irish faidche, *ad-cáio-, "by the house", Celtic kaio-n, house; See ceàrdach. Ascoli refers it to Old Irish aith, area (an imaginary word), and Jubainville allies it with Welsh gwaen, plain, German weide (see bhàn for Welsh).
a crab, or lobster's, burrow (M`A.); See aice:
hiding place, den, mole's burrow; See aice.
stately, showy; cf. Irish faicheallach, luminous:
caution, guard, Early Irish accill, preparation, watch: *ád-ciall; from ciall, sense? CF. dìchioll.
a prophet, Irish fáidh, Old Irish fáith, *vâti-s; Latin vates; Norse óðr, sense, song, Middle English wood, Scottish wud (= mad), German with, rage. Welsh has gwawd, carmen: *vâto-.
a beech, Irish feagha, fagh-vile (Lh., Comp.Voc.), Welsh ffawydden, Breton fao; from Latin fagus. Gaelic adds the old word bile, a tree, which is the same in origin as bile, leaf.  page 159
a fair, Irish faidhrín; founded on English fair, faire (from Latin feria). For phonetics, cf. paidhir from pair, and staidhir from stair.
lumpish ( Sh.); faidse, lump of bread ( M`A.):
get, Irish faghaim, Early Irish fagbaim, Old Irish ní fogbai, non invenis, from fo-gabim, root gab of gabh, q.v.
begging, etc.; See faoighe.
ask: *vo-gen-, root gen, know, as in aithne. Cf. Early Irish imma foacht, asked. Windisch refers to iar-faigim, iarfacht, I asked, = iarmifoacht, root ag, say. iarmi-fo-siag (St. R.C.@+19 177).
corrupt, putrefy, parboil; root vel, bubble, boil; Norse vella, boil, English well, German wallen, bubble.

a stye, Irish fail, Old Irish foil, mucc-foil, hara, trét-foil, Welsh gwâl, couch, *vali-, root vel, cover, encircle; Greek @Gei@'lúw, envelop (*velu-), @Gei@'@?nlar, shelter; Sanskrit valá, cave, vali, projecting thatched roof. In the sense of "encircling, rolling", add Latin volvo, volumen, English volume, wallow, etc. Further allied is Gaelic olann, wool, English wool, Latin lâna, etc.

a ring, Irish fáil, Old Irish foil, g. falach, *valex; Greek @Ge@`lix, a twist, spire, vine-tendril; root vel, "circle", as above in fail. Cf. for vowel fàl, dike; Breton gwalen, "bague sans chaton". Also failbhe, Irish failge, for failghe; from the stem falach or falagh condensed to falgh.

bathe, lave, Irish folcadh, Old Irish folcaim, Welsh golchi, Breton goalc'hi, wash, *volkô; Lettic wa'lks, damp, wa'lka, flowing water, swampish place. Further allied is Gaelic fliuch, q.v. Possibly here place Volcae, the Rhine Gauls, after whom the Teutons named the Celts; whence Wales, Welsh, etc.
pot-lid (Arran), failceann ( Rob.); from fail, ring (Rob.).
smell, savour; See àile.
dog-brier berry (= mucag):
little lawns (Carm.): cf. àilean.
shadow, aileas (Dial.); from fo-leus? or allied to ail, mark?
root or hole of the ear, faillean, sucker of a tree: *al-nio-, root al, nourish?

fail, fàillinn, failing, Irish faillighim, Early Irish faill, failure, Welsh gwall, Breton goall, *valni-; root val of feall, q.v. Borrowing from English fail, from Latin fallo, is however, possible in the modern languages.
a helm; from the Norse hjálm, English helm.
kneepan (M`A.); from fail, ring ( Rob.). See falman.

welcome, hail! Irish, Old Irish fáilte, *vâletiâ, root vâl, vel, glow; Welsh gwawl, lumen; Greek a@'léa, warmth, sun's heat; Gothic  page 160  vulan, be hot, Old High German walm, heat (Bez.). Cf. Caesar's Valetiacus. Borrowing from Latin valête seems to be Zimmer's view (Zeit. @+30 28). Rhys suggests Welsh gwell; Hend., English wealth.

under consideration, Irish fa deára, remark, fé ndeár, fé ndeara (Munster). Foley gives tabhair fa d'aire = "observe". "Thoir fainear" = observe, consider. The above may be a fixed fa d'aire = fa-deara, with n from the plural an, their.

a swallow, Irish áinleóg, Old Irish fannall, Welsh gwennol, Cornish guennol, Breton gwenneli *vannello. Cf. French vanneau, lapwing, It. vannello, Medieval Latin vannellus, which is usually referred to Latin vannus, fan. *vat-n-allo-s (Holden).
a ring, Irish fáinne, áinne, Old Irish ánne, *ânniâ; Latin ânus, English annular.
fetch, bring; a curtailed form of tabhair through thabhair or (tha)bhair? Cf. thoir.

dawn, Early Irish fáir, Welsh gwawr, Breton gouere-, morning, gwereleuen, morning-star, *vâsri-, Lithuanian vasará, summer, Sanskrit vâsará, early shining, morning (adj.), Latin ver, spring, Greek @Ge@'/ar, spring (Stokes).
ridge, sky-line; from fàir, dawn? Cf., however, Irish faireóg, hillock, and fàireag, below.
bathe; See fathraig.
links, lands sometimes covered by the sea (M`A., who says that in Islay it means "hole"); from English park?
(M`D.), a mallet, Irish farcha, farcha, farca, Middle Irish farca, Early Irish forcha tened, thunderbolt; root ark as in adharc?
a cask or pot lid, Early Irish farcle: *vor-cel-, root cel, cover.
watching, Irish, Early Irish faire; See aire.

a gland, swollen gland, Irish fáireóg ( Fol., O'R.); cf. Welsh chwaren, gland, blotch, root sver, hurt, German schwer, difficult. The Welsh precludes comparison with Latin va@urus, pimple, varix, dilated vein, English varicose.

the ocean,Irish fairrge, Old Irish fairgge, Ptolemy's Vergivios, the Irish Atlantic; from the same root as fearg. In Sutherland fairge means the "ocean in storm". Usually pronounced as if fairce. Welsh Môr Werydd, the Atlantic.
hacking, sacking:
perceive, feel, Irish airighim, Old Irish airigur, sentio; same root as faire (Stokes, Beit. @+8 341).
an object on the sky-line (H.S.D. from MSS.); *f-air-leus; from leus, light.
noisy: allied to seirm. See foirm?
wide, Irish, Old Irish fairsing, Welsh eang (= *ex-ang, ehang), *f-ar-ex-ang: "un-narrow", root ang, narrow (Stokes for Welsh).  page 161
baffle; *vor-tl@.-, "over-bear", root tel, tol, bear (Latin tolero, English tolerate)?
pick off vermin: for root See caisg.
near: See fagus.

squeeze, wring, Irish fáisge, Early Irish faiscim, Welsh gwasgu. premere, Old Breton guescim, Breton goascaff, stringere, *vakshô; Sanskrit vâhate, press; English wedge; further Latin vexo. *fo-ad-sech (Asc.).
a pimple, weal (H.S.D., Dial.):
prophecy, omen, Irish fáisdineachd, fáisdine, Old Irish fáitsine; for fáith-sine, where th is deaspirated before s; from fáith, with the termination -sine (-stine?) Zeuss @+2 777.
speaking, whispering, Irish fáisnéis, rehearsal, Middle Irish faisnéis, Early Irish aisnéis, vb. aisnédim, narrate, *as-in-feid-, infíadim, root veid, vid, know; See innis.
a smile, Irish faitbe (O'R.), laugh, Old Irish faitbim, I laugh, *fo-aith-tibim, tibiu, I laugh, *stebiô; Lithuanian stebiu@os, astonish.
timorous, shy, Irish fáiteach, faitcheas, fear (Keat.), Old Irish faitech, cautus: *f-ad-tech, "home-keeping"?
a hem, Irish fáithim, fathfhuaim; fo and fuaim. See fuaigh.
turf, sods, dike, Irish fál, hedge, fold, Old Irish fál, saepes, Welsh gwawl, rampart, Pictish fahel, murus, *vâlo-; Latin vallum, English wall. See further under fail, stye.
a spade, peat spade, Manx faayl, Welsh pâl, Cornish pal; from Latin pâla. Also "scythe" (Wh.).

a hiding, covering, Irish, Early Irish folach, Welsh, Breton golo, *vo-lugô, *lugô, hide, lie; Gothic liugan, tell a lie, English lie (Stokes). Ernault refers it to the root legh, logh, lie, as in Gaelic laighe: "under-lie", in a causative sense.
spite, malice, treachery, Irish fala. See fàillig, feall for root.
orts (M`D.):
a scythe, really "man who works the scythe", a turfer, from fàl: "scythe" properly is iarunn fàladair.
bare pasture (H.S.D. for Heb.): "turf-land", from fàl.
a jest, irony, fun; See fealla-dhà.
an interment, funeral entertainment (Stew.) = farair?

an ambler, mare, Irish falaire, ambling horse; seemingly founded on English palfrey. The form àlaire, exists, in the sese of "brood-mre" (M`Dougall's Folk and Hero Tales), leaning upon àl, brood, for meaning. Irish falaradh, to amble.
heath-burning, Irish folosg (do.), Early Irish foloiscim, I burn slightly; from fo and loisg, q.v.  page 162

empty, Irish folamh, Middle Irish folum, Early Irish folom, folomm; cf. Old Welsh guollung, Middle Breton gollo, Breton goullo. Windisch derives the Gaelic from lom, bare, but the modern aspiration of folamh makes this derivation doubtful. Ernault refers the Breton to the root of Latin langueo.

go falbhan, moving about, walking, waving, Irish foluamhain, bustling, running away, Early Irish folúamain, flying; See fo and luainech. Old Irish fulumain, volubilis, allied to Latin volvo, English wallow, would suit the phonetics best, but it does not appear in the later dialects. The verb falbh is made from falbhan. Hennessey referred the Gaelic to falamh, empty. Cf. Early Irish falmaigim, empty, quit (Zim.).
the young of live stock, a follower as a calf or foal; from the Scottish follower, a foal, English follower.
common auk, falc (Heb.); from Norse álka, English auk.
dry meal put on cakes:
healthy, Irish falláin, Early Irish follán; for fo+ slàn, q.v.
false (M`D.), Irish, Middle Irish fallsa; from the Latin falsus.

a mantle, so Irish, Middle Irish fallaing, Latinised form phalingis (Geraldus), dat.pl., Welsh ffaling; from Latin palla, mantle, pallium. Cf. Old French pallion, Middle English pallioun. Middle English falding, sort of coarse cloth (Hend.).
sweat, Irish fallus, allus, Old Irish allas: *jasl, root jas, jes, seethe, yeast, Welsh jas, what pervades, Breton goell (= vo-jes-l), leaven; English yeast, zeal; Greek @Gzéw, boil.
the tiller: "helm-worker", from falm, helm, from Norse hjálm, helm. See failm.
a kind of fish (H.S.D. for Heb.), falmaire, herring hake:
kneepan:

hair, Irish folt, Old Irish folt, Welsh gwallt, Cornish gols, caesaries, Old Breton guolt, *valto-s (Stokes), root vel, cover; Latin vellus, fleece, lána, wool, Greek @Glásios, hairy (= vlatios); English wool; Lithuanian velti, hairs, threads. Stokes compares only Russ. voloti@u, thread, Lithuanian waltis, yarn, Greek @Glásios. Same root as olann, wool, *vel, *vol, *ul.
a tendon, snood; for altan, from alt.

a giant, Irish fomhor, pirate, giant, Early Irish fomór, fomórach, a Fomorian, a mythic race of invaders of Ireland; *fo-mór, "sub-magnus" (Zimmer). Stokes refers the -mor, -morach, to the same origin as mare of nightmare, German mahr, nightmare. Rhys interprets the name as "sub-marini", taking mor from the root of muir, sea. The ó of mór, if it is long (for it is rarely so marked) is against these last two derivations.
hurry, confusion (Arg.):  page 163
a mole, fadhbh (Lh.), Welsh gwadd, Cornish god, Breton goz; Middle English wont, talpa. Dialectic ath-thalmhain.

stay, Irish fanaim, Old Irish anaim; root an, breathe, exist, as in anam, anail: "gabhail anail" = taking rest. Stokes suggests an = m@.m, root men, remain, Latin maneo, Greek @Gménw, a phonetic change not yet proved for Gaelic. Welsh di-anod, without delay.
mockery, Irish fonomhad, Early Irish fonomat: *vo-nom-anto-, root nem, take, for which See nàmhad.
dog violet ( H.S.D. quoting O'R.), Irish fanaigse ( O'R.): from pansy?
a void space; from Latin vanus.
a sheep-pen, fank; from Scottish fank.
a vulture, Irish fang, raven.

faint, Irish, Early Irish fann, Welsh, Breton gwan, Cornish guan, debilis, *vanno-s, root vâ, ven, spoil, wound; Gothic wunns, affliction, winnan, to suffer, English wound, wan; Greek @Ga@'/te, infatuation, etc. Others have connected it with Latin vannus and with English want. fannan-feòir, weak breeze (M`D.).
fishing with a feathered hook (H.S.D. for Heb.):

an excrescence, knob, piece, Irish fadhb (Lh.++), Old Irish odb, obex, Welsh oddf: *ud-bhv-o-, "out-growth", root bhu, be (See bu). Stokes gives a Celtic *odbós, from eðgo-s, ozgo-s(?), allied to Greek @Go@'/shc, twig? Latin obex; or to Lithuanian u@odega, tail. Lidén equates Latin offa, a ball. Stokes now @Go@'sfús.

booty, Irish fadhbhaim, I despoil, Old Irish fodb, exuvias: *vodvo-, from Indo-European vedh, slay, thrust; Sanskrit vadh, slay; Greek @Gw@'qéw, push. The root may be vedh, pledge, Greek @Ga@'/eqlon, war prize, English wager.
the common cuttle-fish (Heb.).
edge, so Irish, Early Irish faebur, Old Irish faibur, machera, sword, *vaibro-s, Latin vibro, vibrate, brandish, Lithuanian wyburti, wag (Stokes). Cf. further Welsh gwaew, pl. gweywyr, a lance.
a periwinkle, Irish faochóg, Middle Irish faechóg; cf. Welsh gwichiad.
curve (Carm.):
a favourable crisis in sickness, relief; See faothaich.
entreat earnestly, strive, inf. faochnadh (M`A., Arg.):
knave (Carm.):
may, Irish féadaim, I can, Early Irish fétaim, can, sétar, seitir, potest, *sventô; Gothic swinþs, strong, Anglo-Saxon swíð (do.), Norse svinnr, clever, German geschwind, swift (Stokes).
goods found by chance or lost, waif: "foundling", Early Irish étaim, I find, *pentô, English find. See eudail.
ford, a narrow channel fordable at low water, a hollow in the sand retaining tide water: from Norse vaðill, a shallow, a place where straits can be crossed, Shet vaadle, English wade.  page 164
faodhailt, starting of game, hunting:
a sound; See rather foghar.
begging, asking of aid in corn, etc., Middle Irish faigde, Old Irish foigde, mendicatio, *fo-guide; from fo and guidhe, beg, q.v.
liberal, hospitable, Irish faoilidh, joyful, Old Irish fáilidh, blithe, *vâleti-s, allied to fáilt, welcome (Stokes). Hence faoilte, welcome, delight. Root, *vil, Greek @Gi@`larós, gay?
a sea-gull, Irish faoileán, Old Irish faoilenn, Welsh gwylan, Breton gwelan, whence French goëland and English gull. For root, Stokes compares English wail.

the month extending from the middle of January to the middle of February, Irish faoillidh (do.), faoilleach (do.), holidays, Carnival. The idea is "Carnival" or month of rejoicing; from faoilidh. Usually referred to faol, wolf: "wolf-month". Cf. féill. February in Irish = mí na Féile Bríghde.
vain, void, Irish faon, Middle Irish faen, weak:
unhusk, faoisgeag, a filbert, unhusked nut, Old Irish áesc, concha, aesc, classendix, Latin aesculus? (Stokes). Cf. Welsh gweisgion, husks, gweisgioni, to husk.
confession, Irish faoisdin, Old Irish fóistiu, *vo-sestamtion- (Stokes), furoissestar, confessus: fo and seasamh, q.v. Cf. Greek @Gu@`fístcmi, submit.
a wolf, so Irish, Early Irish fáel, fael-chú, Welsh gweilgi, the sea ("wild dog"), *vailo-s; Armenian gail.
a stony beach (Heb.): "the beach", vaðlinn.
learning; See fòghlum.
fainting from closeness or excitement, falling (Lewis); from aomadh.
wandering, exposure, Old Irish airndrethach, errantia = air-ind-reth-; Gaelic is for fo-ind-reth-, root ret, run, of ruith, q.v. For ind, See ionn-.
getting, Early Irish foemaim, I receive, root em, grasp, hold, Latin emo. Gaelic is for *vo-em-tin-.
relieve, be relieved from fever, etc., Irish faothamh, recovery after a crisis, alleviation: *fo-thàmh?
upon, far an (am), where, Irish mar a n-, where; from mar and rel., not from for.
with, far rium, with me, Irish a bh-farradh, with (lit. "in company of", with gen.). See farradh and mar ri.
freight (a ship), Irish faraim, faraighim, farthadh or faradh, a freight:
bring; See fair.  page 165
over; See far, upon, and air. far-ainm, nick-name; far-cluais, listening, etc.
death watch beetle: "hammerer"; from fairche, hammer, Irish farachan, a hammer (also Gaelic, Wh.). The possibility of its being from faire must not be overlooked.
a roost, Irish faradh (do.), Early Irish forud, a bench, seat, shelf: *for-sud, root sed, seat, as in suidhe, q.v. Cf. Welsh gor-sedd, a seat. Early Irish forad, platform *ver-podo-.
a cooper's wedge; See fairce.
a visit, inquiry for health; from far or for and -ell-, -eln-, go, root el, as in Latin amb-ulare, Greek @Ge@'lqei@nn. See further under tadhal.
see forair.
lykewake:
easy, gentle, Irish farasda, forasda, solid, reasonable, "staid": *for-asda; for asda, See fasdadh. farasda is confused with furasda, q.v.
a lid; from far-bheul, "super-os", from beul, mouth.
a stranger; from falbhalach, from falbh?
a surmise; *far-meas, from meas, judge. Cf. eirmis.
noise:
a mansion, hearth, home; cf. dachaidh.
alder bark for dyeing black (H.S.D., Dial.), lye, or any colour in liquid (M`A.); from far and dath?
delay, Middle Irish fordall, staying, Early Irish fordul:
a farthing, Irish fardín; from the English
lintel, Irish fárdorus, Early Irish fordorus, porch, Welsh gwarddrws, lintel; from for, far and dorus.
a warning (H.S.D.); See root in fathunn: *vor-svon.
a report: *vor-gar, root gar as in goir.
chimney or roof-light, Early Irish forlés; from for- and leus, q.v. Cf. àrlas.
a sand lark (H.S.D., Dial.):
envy, Irish formad, Old Irish format: *for-mad, the mad being for mento- (*ver-mento-, Stokes), root men, Latin mens, English mind. See dearmad.
a large pitcher (Heb.):
refuse of straw or hay ( H.S.D., M`E.); cf. rapas.
strife, co-fharpuis:
off! be off!
violence, Irish farrach, forrach; See farran.

company, vicinity, Middle Gaelic na warri (Dean of Lismore), Irish farradh, Early Irish farrad, i fharrad, near, Old Irish in arrad; from ar-sod-, "by-seat", root sod, sed, sit, as in suidhe. Hence Irish compound prep. a bh-farradh; and from the same source comes the Gaelic mar ri, q.v.  page 166
litter in a boat:
a ledge (Arran), = faradh, dh hardened.
ask, inquire; faghairt (Perth), which suggests fo-gar-t, root gar, speak. Cf. iarr.

anger, force, Irish farrán, vexation, anger, forrán, oppression, Middle Irish forrán, destruction, Early Irish forranach, destructive. Hence Gaelic farrant, great, stout, Irish farránta (O'Br.). Also farrach. The root seems to mean "superiority"; root vers, vors, as in feàrr, q.v.?
a peeling, inner rind; Middle Irish forrusc; from for- and rùsg, q.v.
pinnacle; from far and rinn.
wide; better fairsing, q.v.
arspag, a seagull:
noise, Irish fothrum, Early Irish fothrom, fothrond, Welsh godornn, tumultuous nois (Hend.); for fo-thorm, from toirm. Stokes suggest fo-thrond, from torann. The roots are allied in either case.

grow, Irish fásaim, Old Irish ásaim, fásaim, root aux, au@g, increase, Latin augeo, Greek @Gau@'/xw, English eke, wax. Stokes and Strachan refer fás to a stem (p)ât-to-, pát, pat, eat, feed, Greek @Gpatéomai, eat, English feed, food. Latin pasco, pastum.

empty, waste, fàsach, a desert, Irish fás, fásach, Old Irish fás, fáas, vanus, fásach, desert: *vâsto-s, a waste; Latin vastus, vastare; English waste, German wüste. Hence fàsan, refuse of grain: "waste". fásach, desert, is neuter, See M`A. pref. VIII.
harness, girth-saddle; See asair.
fashion; from the English
hiring, binding, Irish fastogh, hiring, See foisteadh.

a dwelling, Early Irish fastud, holding fast, vb. astaim, fastaim, Old Irish asstai, moratur, adsaitis, residentes, *ad-sod-, root sed, sod of suidhe (Thurneysen). Welsh eistedd, sitting, is for *ex-sod-ijo. It is possible to refer astaim to *ad-stâ-, root sta, stand, Latin sto; the -asda of farasda, "staid", seems from it (cf. tairis).
shelter, Irish fosgadh, Old Irish foscad, umbra: *fo-scáth, "sub-umbra"; See sgàth, shade.
a picking or cleansing off of vermin. See faisg. fasgnadh?
winnowing, fasgnag, asgnag, corn-fan, Irish fasgnaim, I purge.
difficulty, embarrassment:
a mole; See famh.
vista (Carm.):  page 167
a cause, reason, Irish fath, fáth, Early Irish fáth, *vât-u-; root vât as in fàith? See fathamas.
a degree of fear, awe, a warning; also fothamas: *fo-ted-mess-, root of meas, tomhas, etc.
occasion, opportunity: *fo-tad-mess-, See amas.
coltsfoot, Irish fathán (O'R.):
trifling, silly:

bathe, Irish fothrugaim, Old Irish fothraicim, fothaircthe, balnearum, fothrucud, a bath, *vo-tronkatu- (Stokes), Welsh trochi, mergere, balneare, Breton go-zronquet; Lithuanian trinkti, wash, bathe (Bez.).

yet, Middle Irish, Early Irish fodesta, fodechtsa, for fo-fect-sa, the d being otiose and caused by analogy (Zim., Zeit.@+30 21). Atkinson suggests with a query fo'nd(fh)echt-sa. The root word is fecht, time: "under this time, sub hoc tempus". See feachd, time. Hence also feasd (= i fecht-sa).
news, floating rumour, fabhunn (Dial.): *vo-svon, root sven, sound (see tabhann), or root bon, ban, English ban, Old Irish atboind, proclaims?

(fèith, fiath), a calm, Middle Irish feith, Early Irish féth, Old Irish féth, Gadelic root vei, *ve-jo-, root ve, vê, blow, Greek @Ga@'c/r, air, (whence English air), German wehen, to blow, English wind, especially weather (root vet) for the Gaelic sense.

goodness, "betterness", Irish feabhus, Old Irish febas, superiority, feib, distincion, *visus, g. vesv-iás (Thurneysen, Zeit.@+28 149, and Brug.), from vesu- or vesv-, as in fiù, q.v. Stokes doubtfully compares Latin vigeo, English vigour (Bez. Beit.@+19 75).

an army, host, expedition, Irish feachd, an expedition, Early Irish fecht (ar fecht agus sluagad), Welsh gwaith, action, work. This Zimmer refers to Old Irish fichim, I fight (Latin vinco, Gothic veihan, root viq), as well as ++feachd time, Irish feachd, Early Irish fecht, oenfhecht, once, Welsh gwaith, turn, vicem. Stokes separates the latter (feachd, time, Early Irish fecht, journey), giving as stem vektâ, root vegh (Latin veho, English waggon); for fecht, campaign, hosting, he gives the Celtic viktâ, root viq, as Zimmer does. The words seem, as Stokes has it, from two roots, but now they are indistinguishably mixed. Osthoff regards feachd, time, as allied to Latin vices; See fiach.
a whistle, Irish fead, Middle Irish fet-, fetán, a flute, a whistle, Welsh chwythell, a whistle, chwyth, a blast, breath, *wviddo-, *svizdo-, Latin sibilus, English sibilant. See further under séid.
lenght, extent, so Irish; See eadh.

people, some people, troop, Irish feadhainn, Early Irish fedain, company, cobeden conjugatio, Welsh gwedd, team, yoke, root ved, Indo-European vedh, English wed, Latin vas, vadis, surety, Sanskrit vi-vadhá, shoulder-yoke.  page 168
(M`A. feallan), itch, hives; it also means "worm" (See fiolan), Middle Irish filún, glandular disease, fiolún saith, anthrax, malignant struma, all which Stokes takes from Late Latin fello, strumae.

treachery, Irish feall, Early Irish fell (*velno-, Welsh gwall, defect, Breton goall (do.), Cornish gal, malus, malum, Breton gwall (do.), root vel, cheat; Lithuanian ap-vilti, vilióti, cheat, Lettic wilát, deceitful; Norse vél, a deceit, wile, English wile; Zend vareta, error. Stokes hesitates between the above and vel from u(p)el, Gothic ubils, English evil.
joking, irony: *feall+dhà, "double-dealing".
philosopher, Irish feallsamhnach, feallsamh, philosopher, Old Irish felsub; from Latin philosophus.
groos, dirty ( Sh., O'R.): from feam, tail, as in feaman.

sea-weed, Irish feamuin, Early Irish femnach, Welsh gwymon, French goëmon, *vit-s-máni-, root vi, vei, wind, as in fèith, vein? Stokes gives the stem as vemmâni- (vembani-?), which suggests *ve@gvo-, root ve@g, as in feur.
a tail, Irish feam, Middle Irish feam, mentula, Manx famman; also Gaelic eaman, *engvo-, Latin inguen, groin.
flay:
skinning, excessive cold; See fionnadh. The idea of "cold" is metaphorical. Early Irish fennaim, I skin, is referred by Stokes to the root of English wound: he gives the stem as *venvo-.
hooded crow, Irish feannóg, fionnóg: cf. fionna, pile, for root: "piled crow"?
a lazy-bed; older fennoc, trench: from feann, flay.

a man, Irish fear, Old Irish fer, Welsh gwr, Old Welsh gur, Cornish gur, Breton gour, *viro-s (Rhys thinks the Celtic start was ver: cf. Welsh gwr = ver, super, and Gaelic eadh, Old Irish ed = Latin id, etc.): Latin vir; Anglo-Saxon wer, Norse verr, English werwolf; Lithuanian wy/ras; Sanskrit vîra.

land, so Irish, Early Irish ferand, also ferenn, a girdle, garter, root vera, enclose, look after; Sanskrit varan@.á, well, dam, vr@.n@.oti, cover, enclose; Greek @Ge@'rusqai, draw, keep; Church Slavonic vrêti, claudere: further Latin vereor, English ware.
wrath, so Irish, Early Irish ferg, Old Irish ferc, ferg, *vergâ; Greek @Go@'rgc/; root vergo, swell, be puffed up. Hence feargnadh, provocation.
alder tree, Irish fearn, fearnóg, Early Irish fern, fernog, Welsh gwern, Cornish gwernen, Gaulish verno-, French verne, *verno-; Greek @Ge@'rnia, wild figs (? Bez.).

better, Irish feárr, Old Irish ferr, *vers, *ver(i)s, a comparative in -is from the prep. ver (= Gaelic far, for, super); now comparative  page 169  for math, but evidently once for fern, good, *verno-s, Latin supernus (cf. -no- of magnus disappearing in major, and -ro- of Celtic mâros in Gaelic mò). Stokes refers ferr to vers, raise, *uersos-, height, top; Latin verruca, steep place, Lithuanian wirzùs, top, Sanskrit varshman-, height, várshîyas, higher. Cf. Welsh goreu, best (= Latin supremus).

a spindle, Irish fearrsaid, Middle Irish fersaid, *versatti-, *verttati-, Welsh gwerthyd, Cornish gurthit, Old Breton guirtilon, fusis, Middle Breton guerzit, root vert, turn; Latin vertô, vortex; German werden, to be, English worth, be, Middle High German wirtel, spindle ring. Sanskrit vártate, turn, roll, vartulâ, spindle ball.
thrift or sea gilly-flower; from ovs. fearsad, estuary, sand-bank, passage across at ebb-tide, whence place-name Fersit, and in Ireland Belfast; for root see feart.
attention, notice; Breton gortos, to attend, root vert, vort; German warten, attend, English ward, from ware, Nor. varða, ward. An extension of root ver, watch, Latin vereor, etc.
a virtue, efficiency, deed, Irish feart, Old Irish firt, pl. ferta, Welsh gwyrth; from Latin virtus (Windisch, Stokes).
a grave, Irish feart, Old Irish fert, tumulus, *verto-; root ver, cover, enclose, which See under fearann. Cf. Sanskrit vr@.ti, enclosure, hedge.

rain, Irish fearthuinn, Early Irish ferthain, inf. to feraim, I pour, give, *veraô, rain: Latin ûrína, urine, Greek @Gou@`@nron (do.): Norse úr, a drizzle, Anglo-Saxon wär, sea; Sanskrit va@-/ri, water, Zend, vâra, rain. See dòirt.
shrivelling, so Irish (O'R.):
for ever, Irish feasda, henceforward, Early Irish festa, ifesta, now, from this point forward, i fecht-sa; from feachd by metathesis of the s. See fathast.
evening, Irish feascar, Old Irish fescor, *vesqero-, Welsh ucher, *eksero- for *esqero-; Latin vesper; Greek @Ge@`spéros.
slight breeze; See feothachan.
generosity, hospitality, Irish féile, Early Irish féle; from fial, q.v.

charm, incantation, Early Irish éle, héle, mo fhele; from Norse heill, auspice, omen, English hale, etc.; allied to Old Irish cél, augurium, Welsh coel, omen, Old Welsh coil (Zim., Zeit.@+33 147). For Gaelic féile, See Inv. Gaelic Soc. Tr. @+17 243. Stokes regards Zimmer's derivation from Norse a failure, and compares Welsh wylo, wail, weep, as Irish amor, music = Welsh afar, grief, and Gaelic ceòl = German heulen, howl. Rhys cfs. Welsh eli, oil, ointment.

a kilt, Early Irish, Old Irish fíal, velum: Old Irish ronfeladar, he might clothe us; from Latin vêlum, a covering, vêlare, English veil. In Islay, Jura, etc., it is an t-sibhleadh. McL. and D.  page 170  also give éibhleadh. Hend. questions if Latin See uanfebli in Fled Breton 68. Root sveil as in fill, spaoil, etc?

a fair, feast, Irish féil, festival, holiday, Old Irish féil, Welsh gwyl, festum, Breton goel, *vegli-; Latin vigilia, Greek veille, a watch, vigil, English vigil, wake. The Celtic words are borrowed from Latin (Windisch, Stokes). Hence féillire, an almanack.

self, Irish, Old Irish féin, *sve-j-sin, "self there", *sve-j, *sve, Prussian swaiss, Church Slavonic svoji@u; Latin suus, se@-; Greek @Ge@`/, @Go@`/s. Zeuss explains féin, as bé-shin, "quod sit hoc", bé being the verb to be. This explanation is due to the divers forms of the Old Irish word for "self, selves": fésine (= bé-sin-é, sit id hoc), fésin, fadesin (= bad-é-sin), fodén, etc.

g. Féinne, the Fingalians, Irish Féinne, Fiann, Early Irish fíann, *veinnâ, also Early Irish fían, a hero, *veino-s, root vein, strive; Latin vênari, hunt; Sanskrit vénati, go, move, desire. Zimmer takes the word from Norse fjándi, an enemy (English fiend, which he supposes the Irish troops called themselves after the Norsemen.
a farm, Irish feilm; from m.English ferme, English farm.
a feast; better feusd, q.v.
wait, Irish feithim, Early Irish fethim, inf. fethem (= Gaelic feitheamh), *vetô, root vet; Latin vetus, old, English veteran; Greek @Ge@'/tos, year; English wether ("yearling").

a sinew, a vein, Irish, Old Irish féith, fibra, *veiti-s, root vei, vi, wind, bend; Latin vînem, with, vîtis, a vine; Greek @Gi@'téa (long @G i), willow; English withe; Lithuanian vy/tis, willow-wand, Church Slavonic viti, res torta; Sanskrit vayati, weave, flecto. The Welsh shows a stem *vittâ, vein, Welsh gwythen, Breton gwazen, Cornish guid-; cf. Latin vitta, fillet. Hence féith, a bog channel (Irish féth, a marsh, bog-stream), and feithleag, honeysuckle, Middle Irish feithlend, woodbine, Welsh gwyddfid (do.).
a bird or beast of prey (M`A.), Irish feithide, Irish feithide, a beast:
corn-thistle, thistle (Arms., H.S.D.), Irish feochadan (O'R.), feóthadán (O'Br.), and feóthán. Cf. fobhannan.
the pole-cat, Irish feochullan (Fol., O'R. has feocullan like Sh.). Cf. Scottish fethok, fithowe, pole-cat, Middle English ficheu, now fitchew.
pith, puff (feo'ran) - Dial.; feodharan, root, *vet, vetu-?
goodness; See feabhas.
pewter, Irish péatar, Welsh ffeutar; from the English pewter.
decay, Irish feodhaim, Middle Irish feodaigim, wither: "senesco"; *vetu-, root vet, as in Latin vetus, Gaelic feith? Old Irish feugud, Welsh gwyw, Latin vietus; *vivagatu?
flesh, Irish feoil, Early Irish feóil, Old Irish feúil, *vepoli-s; Sanskrit vapâ, fat, vápus, body, form?  page 171
a farthing land, feòirling; from Anglo-Saxon feorþling, English farthing.
chess, Irish feoirne (Sh., O'R., Fol.):
a squirrel, Irish feoróg ( Sh., O'R., Fol.), Welsh gwiwer, Breton gwiber; Lithuanian vovere@?, Lettic wâweris, Prussian weware; Latin viverra, ferret (Pliny).

inquire, fiafraigh (Kintyre Dial.), Irish fiafruighim, Old Irish iarfaigim: *iar-fach, prep. iar and fach, Early Irish faig, dixit, *vakô, say; Latin vocô, call, vox, voice; Sanskrit vac, say. The r of Gaelic and modern Irish has shifted to behind the f, while a prothetic f is added.
a firlot; See feòirling.
(Arran), a little breeze; root vet, as in onfhadh.
behold, see, try, Irish feuch, féach, Early Irish féchaim, fégaim, *veikô; Greek ei@'kw/n, image (English iconoclastic), @Geo@'/ika, I seem, @Gei@'kazw, conjecture; Sanskrit vic@?, appear, arrive.
may, can; See faod.
cattle; usual spelling of eudail, q.v.

it is necessary, Middle Irish is eidir, it is possible, for is ed fhétir, it is what is possible. feudar is the pres. pass. of feud, may. In Gaelic the "may" has become "must". The negative, cha 'n fheudar, is common in Early Irish as ni fhétir, ni étir, cannot be.

use, need, Irish feidhm, pl. feidhmeanna, need, use, duty, need-service of a vassal, Early Irish feidm, effort, *védes-men-, "need-service"; root ved, as in feadhainn. Hence feumannach, a steward: "a servitor".
a waggon, wain, Old Irish fén, Welsh cywain, vehere, *vegno-, root vegh, carry; Latin veho, vehiculum, vehicle; Greek @Go@'/hos, chariot; English waggon, wain; Sanskrit vahati, carry.

grass, Irish feur, Old Irish fér, Welsh gwair, Cornish gwyr, *vegro-, Indo-European root ve@g, increase, be strong; Latin vegeo, quicken, vigor, vigour, English vegetation; Anglo-Saxon wacan, nasci, English waken. Strachan and Stokes refer it to the root ve@g, u@g, be wet, moist, Latin uvidus, moist, English humour, Greek @Gu@`grós, wet, Norse vökr, moist; but judged by the Latin, the Celtic should be vebro-, which would not give Welsh gwair.
a canker, veursann, a worm in the hide of cattle:
a beard, Irish féusóg, féasóg, Early Irish fésóc, beard, fés, hair, *vanso, Old Prussian, wanso, first beard, Church Slavonic vasu@u, beard.
(féisd, féis), a feast, Irish féis, feusda, Early Irish feiss; from Latin festia, English feast.  page 172
a mussel:

found, invent, Irish fuair, Old Irish fúar, inveni, frith, inventus est, *vovora, root ver; Greek @Geu@`@nron, I found, @Geu@`/rcka (Strachan, Prellwitz). The root ver is likely that found in Greek @Go@`ráw, I see, Latin vereor, English ware.
a fever, Irish, Middle Irish fiabhrus; from Latin febris.
a tooth, Irish, Old Irish fiacail. There is an Early Irish fec for féc, a tooth, a stem *veikkâ:
value, worth; See fiach.
debt, value, Irish fiach, Old Irish fíach, *veico-, Latin vices, change, German wechsel, exchange, Sanskrit vishtí, changing, in turn (Osthoff). This is the right derivation.

a deer, Irish fiadh, Early Irish fíad, Old Irish fíadach, venatio, Welsh gwydd, Breton guez, goez, savage, *veido-s, wild; Old High German weide, a hunt, German weide, pasturage, Norse veiðr, hunting; further is Gaelic fiodh, wood, English wood. Hence fiadhaich, wild.
invite, welcome (Skye):
lay or fallow land; from the above root of fiadh. Cf. German weide, pasture. Also Gaelic fiadhain, wild, Irish fiadháin, wild, uncultivated.

generous, Irish fial, Early Irish fíal, modest, Welsh gwyl. Bez. suggests *veiplo-, Teutonic vîba-, German weib, English wife. Cf. Irish fialus, relationship. The underlying idea is "kindness, relationship".
awe, reverence, Irish fiamh, fear, reverence, ugly, horrible, Early Irish fiam, horrible:

aspect, appearance, trace, Irish fiamh, track, trace, chain, fíamh (O'Cl.) = lorg, Early Irish fiam, a chain, *veimo-, root vei, wind, as in féith. fiamh ghàire, fèath ghaire (Arg.), a slight smile, is in Irish fáetheadh an gháire, appearance of a smile, Early Irish féth, aspect.
peat cart; carn-fianaidh (Ross); See feun.
the Fingalians; See Féinn. This is the real nom. case.
the black heath-berr; root vein as in Fiann.

witness, a witness, Irish fiadhnuise, fiadhan, a witness, Old Irish fiadnisse, testimony, fiadu, acc. fiadain, testem, *veidôn, Indo-European root veid, vid, know, see, as in fios, q.v.; Anglo-Saxon witta, a witness, English witness, root, wit, know.
crooked, Irish fiar, Early Irish fíar, Welsh gwyr, Greek goar, gwar, *veiro-; root vei, wind as in féith; English wire, Anglo-Saxon wîr, wire.
wild; a participial formation from fiadh. Also fiadhta, so Irish
quiet and sly (Skye):
calm; See fè.  page 173
an interjetion denoting "nasty"! English fie, Norse fy/, German pfui. Also Dial. fuich, fuidh, which leans on Norse fúi, rottenness ("Cha bhi fuidh ach far am bi fàile").
twenty, Irish fiche, ar fhichid, Old Irish fiche, g. fichet, Welsh ugeint, ugain, Cornish ugens, ugans, Breton ugent, *vikn@.s, uikn@.tos; Latin vîginti; Greek @Gei@'/kosi; Zend vîçaiti.
a suggestion (H.S.D.): *vid-dho-, root vid, wit.
a small pipe, reed, flute, Irish fideóg; for root, See fead. Shaw also gives the meaning "small worm". M`L. has fìdeag.
a green islet or spit uncovered at high tide, web of sea-clam (Isles); from the Norse fit, webbed foot of waterfowl, meadow land on the banks of firths or rivers, fitja, to web, English fit.
a fiddler; from fiodhull. Irish fidiléir is English fiddler directly borrowed. Hence Gaelic fidleireachd, restlessness; "fiddling" about.

know, consider, Irish fidir, knows, Old Irish fetar, scio, fitir, novit, *viddetor, *vid-dho- (the -dho- as in creid, Windisch); root vid, see, as in fios. Thurneysen explains it as *videsar (aorist stem vides-) becoming vid-shar, but d-sh does not produce t or d without an n before it.
a fig, Irish fíge; from Latin fîcus, English fig.

weave, Irish fighim, Early Irish figim, Old Welsh gueig, testrix, Welsh gweu, to weave, Cornish guiat, tela, Breton twea, Middle Breton tweaff, *vegiô; Ger wickeln, roll, wind, curl, wieche, wick, English wick, Anglo-Saxon wecca (Stokes). Usually referred to the root vei, vi, wind.

a poet, Irish file, g. filidh, Old Irish fili, g. filed, *velet-, "seer"; Welsh gwelet, to see, Breton guelet, sight, *velô. Cf. Norse völva, prophetess, sibyl. Old Germanic Veleda, a prophetess (Tacitus).

fold, Irish fillim, fold, return, Old Irish fillim, flecto, *velvô; Latin volvo, roll, volumen, English volume; Greek @Gei@'lúw, envelop; Gothic af-valvjan, roll away, English wallow. Cf. Welsh olwyn, a wheel (Stokes). Windisch (Curt. Et.) suggests vald as root, allied to Norse velta, roll, Gothic valtjan, English welter, German walze, roll, waltz. See especially till.
a collop: a "roll"; from fill.

a tribe, kindred, Irish, Old Irish fine, Old Breton coguenou, indigena, *venjâ, kinship; Norse vinr, a friend, Anglo-Saxon wine, Old High German wini (do.); Indo-European root ven, love, Latin Venus, veneror, English venerate, Sanskrit van, love.
fine, elegant, Irish fínealta; cf. Middle Irish fín- in Fínscothach, fair-flowered, Fin-shnechta, bright-snow, root svén; Greek @Gc@'noy, bright (Stokes for Middle Irish).  page 174
jet (m`D., M`A.), finichd, black as jet ( M`E.):
end; from Latin finit, the colophon of so may tales when written.
wise, so Irish ( Lh., Sh., H.S.D., which gives C.S. as authority):
a maiden ( Arms., M`A., M`E.): "fairness, beauty"; from fionn (*vindiâ).
a buzzard.
wrath, Irish fíoch, Early Irish fích, feud, Indo-European *veiqo-, fight; Gothic veihan, strive, Old High German wîgan, fight; Latin vinco. Hence fiochdha, angry.

wood, so Irish, Old Irish fid, Welsh guid, gwydd, gwydden (sing.), Cornish guiden, Breton gwezenn, tree, gwez, trees, Gaulish vidu- *vidu-; English wood, Anglo-Saxon wudu, Old High German witu. Hence ++fiodhcheall chess play, Early Irish fidchell, Welsh gwyddbwyll, "wood-sense", from fiodh and ciall. Also fiodhag, wild fig, fiodhan, cheese-vat.
an impetuous rush forward (Heb.):
a fiddle, Early Irish fidil, from Low Latin vitula, whence French viola, English viol, violin. Cf. English fiddle, from Medieval Latin fidula, Latin fidis.
a figure, Irish fíoghair, Middle Irish figur; from Latin figura.
a field-mouse (Arran.):
an earwig, nesscock, Welsh chwil, beetle, chwiler, maggot, Breton c'houil; Greek @Gsílfc, cockroach, English sylph. Cf. feallan.
a giant (Sh.); from fiamh.
wine, Irish fíon, Old Irish fín, Welsh, Cornish, Breton gwin; from Latin vinum.
a mite, insect, a miser, Irish fineóg, a mite in cheese, etc.:
white, Irish fionn, Old Irish find, Welsh gwyn, Cornish guyn, Breton gwenn, Gaulish vindo-, *vindo-, a nasalised form of root vid, veid, see, as in fios. Cf. Servian vidny/, clear.
to, against, Irish fionn-, ionn-, Old Irish ind-; See ionn-.

hair, pile, Irish fionnadh, Early Irish finda, findfad, Old Irish finnae, pilorum, *ves-niâ, root ves, clothe, Latin vestis, English vestment. Stokes has compared it to Latin villus, hair, which he takes from *vin-lus, but which is usually referred to the root vel of vellus, lana, etc. The -fad of Early Irish is for *vida, aspect, Welsh gwedd, root vid, see.
refreshment: "coolness", *ionn-fhuachd: cf. fionnar.
grasshopper, Irish finnín feoir (O'R.):
a watching: *ind-faire; See fionn-, to, and faire.
cool, Irish fionnfhuar, Middle Irish indfhuar; from fionn-, and fuar. fionnas-gàrraidh, parsley (M`L.):  page 175
randk grass, downy beard (H.S.D.):
(white) bronze, Early Irish findruine, white bronze: *find(b)ruine (Hend.), English bronze.
grandson's grandson, Irish fionnúa; from fionn-, ad-, and ogha.
a romance, Irish finnsgeul; from fionn- and sgeul: ande-sqetlon.

true, Irish fíor, Old Irish fír, Welsh gwir, Old Welsh guir, Breton gwir, *vêro-; Latin vêrus; German wahr. Root ver, vor, var, see, as in English beware, ward. Before the noun the word is fìr. Hence fìrean, righteous man, Old Irish fírian, Welsh gwirion, *vêriâno-s.

knowledge, Irish fios, Old Irish fiss, *vid-tu-, root vid, veid, know; Latin video, see; Greek @Gei@'@ndon, @Gi@'dei@nn, saw, @Goi@'@nda, know, Gothic vitan, watch, English wit; Sanskrit vid, know, vetti, to know. Hence fiosrach, knowing.
the northern lights; See fear and clis.
backgammon men:
interjection - "what a pother"; from the Scottish fiery-fary, bustle.
hill ground, mountain: cf. fearann, root *ver.
a ferret, Irish firéad; from the English
an eagle, Irish fír-én: "true-bird"; from fìor and eun. So in Early Irish fír-iasc is the salmon. So in Reay Country (Rob.).
male, so Irish; Early Irish firend; from fear.
interjection - noise of things breaking, talking secretly.
a raven, Irish, Old Irish fiach; this is a dissylable, *vivo-ko-; the phonetics being those of biadh. Stokes gives *veijako-s or *veivako-s. It is still distantly allied to German weihe.
dulse, so Irish ( Lh., O'Br., etc.):

worthy, Irish fiú, Old Irish fiú, Welsh gwiw, Cornish guiu, Old Breton uuiu, Gaulish vesu-, *vesu-, vêsu-, good; Sanskrit vásu, good; root ves, be, English was. Some give *visu (*vîsu-) as the stem, Greek @Gi@'/sos, like (= visvo-s), Sanskrit vishu, æque. Hence fiùbhaidh, a prince, valiant chief, Irish fiúbhas, dignity; also fiùghanta, generous, Irish fiughantach, fiúntach (Keat.), worthy.
expectation, Early Irish fiugrad, praedicere; from Latin figura. Irish has fíoghair, figure, fashion, sign.
a sapling, Irish fiúrán ( Sh., O'R., Fol.):
(fiùbhaidh), an arrow; See iùthaidh).
a sudden gust of wind ( Sh., O'R.):
heaven, glory, flaitheas, sovereignty, Irish flaitheamhnus, Old Irish flaithemnas, gloria; from flaithem, lord, g. flaitheman; See flath.
red, blood-red, so Irish, Early Irish fland, blood, red: vl-ando-, root vol of fuil, q.v.  page 176
a flask, Welsh fflasg; from the English

a chief, prince, Irish flaith, Old Irish flaith, chief, dominion, flaithem(an), chief (*vlatimon-), Welsh gwlad, region, Middle Welsh gulatic, rex, Cornish gulat, patria, Breton gloat, realm, Gaulish vlatos, *vlato-s, *vlati-s, root vala, vla, be strong; Latin valere, English valid; Gothic valdan, German walten, rule, English weild, Walter; Church Slavonic vlada@?, rule, Russ. vladiete, rule, Old Prussian waldnika-, king. Also *valo-s as the final element of certain personal names - Domhnall, *Dumno-valo-s (see domhan), Conall, *Kuno-valo-s (*kuno-s, high, root ku, as in curaidh, q.v., Teutonic Hûn-, Humbold, Humphrey, Hunwald, etc.), Cathal, *Katu-valo-s (see cath), etc.
flowing in ringlets (H.S.D., from MSS.); from Latin plecto, plait.

a feast, Irish fleadh, Old Irish fled, Welsh gwledd, Old Welsh guled, pompae, *vl@.dâ, root vel, wish; Greek @Gei@'lapínc, feast, @Ge@'\ldomai, wish, e@'lpís, hope; Latin voluptas; English will, well.
brandishing; English wield; See flath.

a rod, wreath, Irish fleasg, garland, wand, sheaf, Old Irish flesc, rod, linea, *vleska, from *vledska, root vl@.d; German wald, wood, English wold; Greek @Ga@'/lsos, grove; Church Slavonic vladi, hair. From the Celtic comes the French flèche, arrow, whence English Fletcher, arrow-maker. See fleisdear.
young man, bachelor, so Irish, Middle Irish flesgach: "wand-bearer". From fleasg, above. The Irish fleasgaigh ealadhna, itinerant medicine men, carried fleasgan to denote their profession.
a barge or boat hung with festoons; from fleasg.
arrow-maker; from Scottish fledgear, Middle English flecchere, now fletcher, from Old French flechier. See fleasg further.
floating (Heb.), fleodruinn, a buoy; from Norse fljóta, to float, English float.
an untidy, flabby person, a flat fish (Arms.), fleoidhte, flaccid (Sh.):
chickweed, a wen, Irish fliodh, fligh, chickweed, Welsh gwlydd, chickweed, soft stems of plants, *vl@.du-. Same root as in fleasg.

wet, Irish, Old Irish, fliuch, Welsh gwlyb, Old Welsh gulip, Cornish glibor, humor, Breton gloeb, wet, *vl@.qu-s, wet; Latin liquidus (= fliquidus); Lithuanian wa'lks, wet, wa'lka, swampy place. See failc.
hallucination (H.S.D. for N.H.):
a state of floating; from English float, Norse floti, a raft.
lukewarm; See plodadh.
flower, Irish plúr, Middle Irish plúr; from the Middle English flour, Old French flour, Latin florem, Gaelic flùr is from the Scotch.  page 177
under, Irish, Old Irish fo, Welsh go-, Old Welsh guo-, Cornish go-, Cornish, Bret. gou-, Gaulish vo-: *vo, for *u(p)o; Indo-European upo; Greek @Gu@`pó; Latin s-ub; Gothic uf; Sanskrit upa, hither.
brink (Carm.):
(fòthannan), a thistle, Irish fóbhthán, fóthannán, Early Irish omthann, *omo-tanno-, "raw or rough twig"? See amh and caorrunn. Dial. fonntan (Arran).
word; See facal.
scoffing, Irish fochmhuid, fochuidbheadh, Middle Irish fochmaid, Early Irish fochuitbiud, *fo-con-tib-, root teb, smile, Old Irish tibiu, laugh; Lithuanian stebiu@os, be astonished.
presence, am fochar, coram, Irish, Middle Irish fochair: *fo-char, car being cor, put.
young corn in the blade, Irish fochan, Middle Irish fochon; *vo-kuno? Root kun, ku, increase, Gaulish cuno-, high, etc. See curaidh.
a peat, turf, Irish fód, Old Irish fót: *vonto-?
fodder, Irish fodar; from the English fodder.
expel, banish, Irish fógair, command, proclaim, Old Irish fócairim (do.), fócre, monitio: *fo-od-gar-; root gar of goir.
quiet, careless (Stew.):
a hostile incursion, Irish foghail, Early Irish fogal; *fo-gal: root gal, valour, war. See gal.
noise, bustle, merriment; for first sense, See foghair, for second, See othail.
valorous, Irish fóghainteach, good, fit, serviceable, fóghaint, ability: "capable"; from foghainn, suffice. See fòghnadh. Irish foghaintidhe, a servant.
a sound, tone, so Irish, Old Irish fogur, sonus: *fo-gar-; root gar of goir. Strachan makes the root part fog, and refers it to fuaim, q.v.

harvest, Irish fóghmhar, Middle Irish fogamur, autumn, Early Irish fogamur, fogomur, last month of autumn: *fo-gamur, the gamur being from the root of geamhradh, winter, q.v. The idea is "sub hiemem". Cf. Welsh cynauaf, harvest, Old Welsh kynnhaeaf, from cyn, before, and gauaf, winter.
learning, Irish fóghluim, Old Irish foglaim, vb. fogliunn: *vo-glendô, *glendô, make clear; English glance, German glanz, splendour; Church Slavonic gle@?edati, show.
sufficiency, service, Irish foghnamh, Old Irish fognam, service; from fo and gnìomh, deed.
a wrapper, infant's clout:
a sprout, young corn (Arms.), faichean (Arg.), Irish foichnín; See fochann.  page 178
a peat; See fód.
a beggar; See faoighe.
naked (H.S.D., Dial.):
patience, Irish foighid, Old Irish foditiu, toleratio (*vo-dam-tin-), vb. fodamim, patior, root dam; Latin domo, I tame, subdue; Greek @Gdamáw (do.); English tame; Sanskrit dâmyati, tame.
ask; See faighnich. Also, more Dialectic, foinich.
macerate, broil; See fail. Hence foileag, a cake suddenly and imperfectly toasted.
pig-stye; See fail.
slow, stately, fòill, composure, Irish fòil, fóill, softly! a while, Middle Irish co fóill, slowly, for a while, Early Irish co foill, slowly:
slow development:
treachery, Old Irish foile, astutia. Gaelic is for *volni-, Irish for *foliâ, both side-forms to feall, treachery, q.v.
reveal, Old Irish foillsigim *svolnestikiô; See follas.
ask; See faighnich.
a wart, Irish faine, faithne, Welsh, Cornish gwenan, blister, Breton gwennhaenn, a wart; English wen, Anglo-Saxon wenn (Ern.).
handsome, genteel; cf. foinnich, also Latin vinnulus, delightful, root ven, as in Gaelic fine, etc.
temper, Irish foinnim, temper, knead, foinnighte, tempered, kneaded. Cf foinneamh.
prefix meaning "super", same as for-: See far, air(b).

help, Irish fóir (vb. and n.), Early Irish foriuth, I. help, Old Irish don-fóir, to help us: *vo-ret-; root ret of ruith, run. For force, cf. furtachd. The Welsh gwared, release, Breton goret, are of like elecents. Similarly foirbheart (an Irish word really), assistance, is from foir- and beir.
acceptable (M`D); from for and bail, good?
instruction, catechism, Irish foircheadal, Old Irish forcital, doctrina, vb. forchun, doceo: *for-can-; root can, say, sing. See can.

a band, crew, Irish fuirionn, Early Irish fairenn, Old Irish foirinn, Old Welsh querin, Welsh gwerin, people, Middle Breton gueryn, *vorênâ, *vorinni-, multitude, root ver, enclose; Anglo-Saxon vorn, multitude, caterva; Lithuanian worà, long row in Indian file; Sanskrit vra@-/, troop, company. See fearann.

perfect, Irish foirfe, complete, old, Old Irish foirbthe, pefectus, forbe, perfectio, vb. forbanar, perficitur, forfenar, consummatus: *for-ben-; root ven, va, go (Latin venio, Greek @Gbaínw, @Ge@'/bcn, practically a verb "to be" (Stokes Neo-Celtic Verb. Subst.).
assistance, Early Irish inf.dat. foirithin; See fòir.
border land (Cam.)  page 179
noise; side form of toirm?
brisk, lively ( Sh., etc.): from English formal ( Rob.).
formalists.
a band, dwellers, Irish foirne (O'Br.); an oblique form of foireann, g. foirne.
intruding; See teirinn, teàrnadh.
a furnace; See fùirneis.
conspicuously brave; See niata.

rest, Irish fois, Old Irish foss, residence, remaining, rest, Welsh ar-os; *voss-; root ves, be, rest; Greek @Ga@'/stu, city (*vastus); Sanskrit vástu, place; Latin Vesta; English was, German wessen, be, Gothic visa, remain. So all etymologists till Windisch (1892) suggested the root stâ, tat is *vo-sto-. Stokes still holds by old (1903). Hence foisdin, taciturnity, Irish foisdine.
wages, hire, Irish foistighim, I hire; Middle Irish foss, servant, Welsh gwas (English vassal); from the same root as fois. Also fasdadh.
covering, hiding; See falach.
rank grass growing on dunghills; *vog-lo-, root, vog, veg of feur.
a feud, bloodiness; See fuil.
water-parsnip ( H.S.D. quotes only O'Br.), Irish folachtain:
publicity, follaiseach, public, Irish follus, public, manifest, Old Irish follus, clear, shining, manifest, *svolnestu-s; See solus.
land, Irish fonn, Early Irish fond; from Latin fundus, which, again, is connected with Gaelic bonn, q.v.
a tune, Irish fonn, tune, desire, delight, Middle Irish adbonn, a strain; *svonno-, root sven, sound, Latin sonus, English sound. See seinn.
a trooper (M`A.):
super-, Irish, Old Irish for-; prep. for, for which See far, air(b).
projection into the sea (Carm.):
command, Irish foráilim. See earail for formation and root.
watch, Irish foraire; from for and aire.
sedate, so Irish; See farasda, in the sese of "staid".
ambush ( Sh., H.S.D., which quotes Lh. and C.S.), Irish forbhas, Early Irish forbas, siege:
a fork, Irish forc, Early Irish forc (= gobul); for Latin furca, English fork.
information, inquiry, Irish foras, Early Irish foras, forus, true knowledge: *for-fiss, from fiss or fios, knowledge, q.v. foras feasa, "basis of knowledge".
keenness, anger; from a side-form forg (*vorg) of fearg?  page 180
a furlogh; from the English
spite, hatred (H.S.D.), Irish, Middle Irish forlonn; from for and lonn, fierce.
a mould, Irish formán; from Latin forma.
gain ( H.S.D.), excrescence, shift ( M`E.); from for and rath? See rath.
a forester; from the English.
strong, hardy, (an Irish word clearly), Irish foirteamhail, fortail, brave, stout, Early Irish fortail, predominant, strong; from Latin fortis.
fortune, Irish fortún; from Latin fortuna.
litter, refuse of cattle's food, orts; from the English orts. Lh. has an Irish fortas, straw.
yet, still, Irish fós, Middle Irish fós, beos, Old Irish beus, beius. Stokes makes it a comparative in s from beo-, allied to Latin beô, gladden, be-ne, well.
the lark (Carm.):
open, so Irish, Early Irish oslaicim: *f-od-as-leic; Gaelic root leic or leig, let. See leig and cf. tuasgail.
open, frank:
porch (Carm.):
pounded bark (or anything) to stop leaks; cf. Irish fosradh, scattering, from *vo-ster-, root ster, strew.
hand feeding of cattle (Heb.):
the glanders in horses, Irish fothach, fóthach:
a flaw, refuse (M`A. says "rotten pus", and gives fòt, rotten earth): from Scottish faut, as in fabhd.
refuse, small potatoes (Arg.):
freight; from Scottish fraught, English freight.
vision, sight, Irish rádharc, Early Irish rodarc: *ro-darc; root derk, see, as in dearc, q.v.
a brisk, warlike fellow; See frogan.
wattled partition, Early Irish fraig: *vragi-, root verg; Sanskrit vraja, hurdle; Greek @Gei@'rgw, shut in.
sea-weed ( Sh., O'R.):
tansy; lus na Fraing (Cameron), the French herb; from Fraing, France. Irish lus na bhfhrancach, Middle Irish frangcan, tansy (St.).
heather, Irish fraoch, Old Irish froech, Welsh grug, Cornish grig, Middle Breton groegon, *vroiko-; Greek @Ge@'reíkc. Hence Gaelic fraoch, wrath, Irish fraoch, Early Irish fraech, furor.
toe-bit of shoe; "heather-protector", from fraoch?
flourishing:
a fringe; from the English
a flustering by liquor; Dial. sraoileadh:  page 181
a place of shelter in the mountains ( Sh., O'R.), fraoinibh (D.Bàn):
a shower, Irish fras, Early Irish frass, *vrastâ; Greek @Ge@'/rsc, dew; Sanskrit farsham, rain.
answer, Irish freagairim, Early Irish frecraim: *frith-gar-, root gar of goir.
serving, attending, Irish freasdail, Old Irish frestal, fresdel: *fris-do-el-; for root See fritheil. Dr Cameron referred it to fris and tal, which See in tuarastal.
a guard, watch: *frith-coimhead-an; from coimhead, guard, look, q.v.

a vow, interdictory resolution, Early Irish fretech, fristoing, repudiation, renunciation, Old Irish fristossam, renuntiaverimus; root tong, tog, swear, Latin tongeo, think, English think. Stokes gives the final root as tag, take, Latin tangere. Irish tong, swear, is allied to Welsh tyngu.
fury, rage:
bent-grass (Arg.):

a root, Irish fréamh, Early Irish frém, Welsh gwraidd, gwreiddyn, Cornish grueiten, Breton grisienn, *vr@.d-mâ, *vr@.djo-, *vr@.dnu-: Latin radix, root; Greek @Gr@`íza; Gothic vaurts, English wort, root.
a tetter, ring-worm, Middle Irish frigde, flesh-worm, Early Irish frigit, Welsh gwraint, Middle Breton gruech, *vr@.gn@.tiâ, root verg; English wriggle.
support, attention:
fry; from the English frying.
a second dram, a nip:
a frying pan, Irish friochtán; cf. Irish friochtalaim, I fry. From fry of the English
a bristle, pig's bristle; Middle Irish frighan i. guairech muc; root vr@.g as in fraigh? Cf. Welsh gwrych, hedge, bristles, *vr@.g-ko-. Hence frioghail, sharp, keen.
fretfulness: *friogh'n-as, "bristlines"; from frioghan.
fretful (Stew.); See frith, wour look.
an incantation to discover if far-away persons live (Heb.), fate ( Sh., O'R.); from the Nrose frétt, enquiry of the gods about the future, Scottish fret, freit.
small, trifling ( Sh., O'R.), which M`A. says antecedes the noun, is the prep. frith or ri.
a sour or angry look (A.M`D.), frithearachd, peevishness, Irish frithir, peevish: *vr@.ti-; root of ri "against"?
a forest, deer forest, Irish frith, wild, mountainous place, Welsh ffridd, forest; from Middle English frið, deer park, Anglo-Saxon frið.
freas-, prefix = prep. ri by force and derivation; which see.  page 182
attend, Irish friotholaim (Con. friothólaim, Early Irish frithailim, root -al- (Ascoli), go; root al, el, eln of tadhal, q.v.
earnest, eager (Stew.), Irish frithir, earnest, peevish; cf. frith, sour look.
a hole, fen, den, ròg (Suth.).
liveliness, a slight degree of drunkenness:
a dampness oozing through the wall; from fraigh and snighe.
a sudden tugging, rushing at (M`D.):
a fringe; See fraoidhneis.
hoarse, rough:
acclivity (Carm.):
cold, so Irish, Old Irish uacht, ócht, *aukto-; Lettic auksts, cold (adj.), Lit áuszti, cold, be cold.
drive away, Irish fuadaighim, drive away, snatch away, Early Irish fúataigm: *fo-od-tech(?); See teich. Hence fuadan, wandering.
hasty, in a hurry ( Stew., Arms. and H.S.D.), Irish fuadar, haste; from fuad- of fuadaich? Cf. Scottish foutre.
exiled; See fògair.
loose pins of warping stakes. Cf. Old Irish fuat.

stitch, fuaigheal, sewing, so Irish, Early Irish fúagaim, úagaim, Old Irish úaimm (n.): +out-s-men-; root poug, pug, stitch, stick; Latin pungo, English punch. Zimmer (in 1882), referred it to the root of òigh, the idea being "integrate", from óg, uag, "integer". Old Irish óigthidi, sartores.

noise, so Irish, Early Irish fúaimm (pl. fuamand). Neither *vog-s-men (Strachan; root vog of Sanskrit vagnú, sound, Gothic vôpjan, cry, English whoop) nor *voc-s-men (Stokes; root voq, voice, Latin voco) can give ua, only o@u or a@u.
loom posts (Uist), Irish uaithne, pillar, post, Early Irish úatne, a post (bed post). So Henderson; fùidne (Wh.):

urine, so Irish, Old Irish fúal: *voglo- or *voblo-; root vo@g, ve@g, u@g, be wet; Greek @Gu@`grós, wet, English hygrometer; Latin humidus, uveo, (for ugveo), be moist, English humour; Norse vökva, moisture.

cold, Irish fuar, Early Irish uar, Welsh oer, Cornish oir; *ogro-, root ug, aug, of fuachd, q.v. Stokes refers it to the root ve@g, u@g, discussed under fual, especially Greek @Gu@`grós, wet; a root which would rather be vob in Celtic (cf. Latin), and this would not give Welsh oer. Strachan suggests either Church Slavonic ogni@u, fire (Latin ignis), or Greek @Gpágos, frost (root pâg, fix, fit). Hence fuaradh, windward side, fuaran, a well, fuarraidh, damp, fuarralanach (Irish fuarálach, chill), cold feeling, etc.; fuar bhalla, an outside wall; fuar-shlat, the rough strong hoop used to bend in staves at the end of casks (Wh.).  page 183
loose, untie, so Irish, Early Irish fuaslaicim; See tuasgail.
hatred, so Irish, Middle Irish fúath; cf. Early Irish uath, awe, terror, terrible, and See ++uath for root.
a spectre, so Irish, Old Irish fúath, figura, forma:
fulling cloth, Middle Gaelic owkki@+t (Dean of Lismore), Irish úcaire, fuller; cf. pùc.
a shoe-strap (H.S.D. says Dial.):
mean, vile; from Scottish footy, fouty.
powder, Irish púdar; from the English
smart, in good condition:
an interjection. See fich.
remainder, Irish fuigheall, Old Irish fuidell, Welsh gweddill; also Gaelic fuidhleach, remains, Early Irish fuidlech: *vodilo-, dîl, allied to English deal, dole, German teil ( St. with query).
a fool (Carm.):
commixing, pulverising; from fùdar. Dial. fùdradh, turning hay in the sunshine to dry it.
craven; from Scottish fugie, one who flies from the fight.
a thrum, Irish fughóg; from a short vowel form of root of fuaigh.
blood, Irish, Old Irish fuil, gen. fola, folo: *voli-, root vol, vel, well; English well. Stokes agrees.
I need, must; for furail, Old Irish foráil, excessive injunction, infliction, same root as earail.

fulaing, suffer (thou), Irish fulangaim, Early Irish fulangim, Old Irish fuloing, sustinet, inf. fulang: "under-go"; from fo and *long, going, root leng, spring, go, as in leum, q.v. Further allied is German verlangen, desire, English long, Latin longus.

bake, Irish fuinim, I knead, bake, boil, Early Irish fuinim, bake, cook. Zimmer takes the word to mean "to fire, bake", from the Norse funi, flame, fire, Early Irish oc-fune = Norse við funa, a-roasting; but unlikely. Possibly *voni-, "dress", root ven, von, Latin Venus, English venerate.
a strong man, also fuirbearnach; compounds of bì and beir, with for, super.
a parching of corn; See eararadh.
stay, Irish fuirighim, Early Irish fuirigim, noun fuirech, Old Irish fuirset (s future): *vo-reg; root reg, stretch, go; Latin porrigo, rego. See rach.
stools, a form, Irish fuirm, Welsh ffurf; from English form.
a furnace, Irish furnéis; from the English
a galling, taking off the skin by riding (M`D.): fo-bian?
(vb.), fulang (n.); See fuilig.  page 184
rock; from fo+ luaisg, q.v.
gloom (Arg.); See suilbh.
a species of petrel, fulmar; from Scottish, English fulmar.
articulation, jointing ( Sh., O'R., H.S.D.); cf. alp.
benumbment by cold; See punntainn. Scottish fundy.
parching corn (Carm.), also furaradh. See fuirearadh.
incitement, command, Irish furáil, Early Irish uráil, furáil, Old Irish iráil; the same as earail, q.v.

a welcome, Irish furán, foran (Connaught); root ver, as in Early Irish feraim fáilti, I welcome. The root means in Early Irish "give rain" (see fearthuinn). The root of fhuair seems mixed with that of fearthuinn. See fearthuinn.
patience: *f-air-asta, asta (standing, staying) being for ad-sta-, ad and sta, stand.
(furas), easy, easier, Irish furas, furasda, Early Irish urusa: *air-usa, from usa, easier, q.v.
wrath ( Sh., O'R.), furban ( H.S.D., from MSS); See fuirbidh.
courtesy, kindly reception; also furmailt. For the latter Armstrong gives "ceremony" as force, which may be from English formality. The words, otherwise, seem from for-fàilte.
a stool; See fuirm.
hate, detest (Arms.), revolt against (Rob.):
relief, help, so Irish, Old Irish fortacht (gen. in -an): *for-tiacht; for Gaelic root tiagh, tigh, See tighinn.
a heather brush; cf. Scottish whisker, a bunch of feathers for sweeping, English whisk.
the dog-days; from Scottish fure-days. G
a tattling mouth; from Scottish gab (do.), Middle English gabben, to chatter, mock, Norse gabb, mockery, Old Fris gabbia, accuse.
a transport vessel (Heb.); from Scottish gabert, a lighter, from French gabarre, storeship, lighter.

take, Irish gabhaim, Old Irish gabaim, gaib, capit, inf. gabáil, Welsh gafael, prehensio (English gavelkind), Cor gavel: *gabô, capio, do, *gabagli; Gothic giban, give, German geben, English give; Lithuanian gabénti, bring.
danger, peril, Irish gábha(dh), Early Irish gába, gábud: cf. Early Irish gád, danger, Greek @Gházw, retire, @Ghzíos, want, @Ghwrís, Latin hé-res. gabhagan, a titlark (Sh., O'R., H.S.D.):
fork; See best Gaelic form in gobhal.  page 185
flattery (Kirk, etc.; O'R.), gossip (Perth); from gabh: "take in"?
goat; See best Gaelic form in gobhar.
a craft trick; from Scottish gaud, a trick. Cf. Middle English gaude, specious trick (Chaucer), from Latin gaudium, English gaud.
a wandering, a man devoid of care (H.S.D., which makes it Dial.; M`E.):

each, every, Irish gach, Old Irish cach, cech, omnis, quivis, Welsh pob, Old Welsh, Cornish pop, Breton pep, pob: *qo-qa, *qe-qa, root qo, qe, of interrogative co; Latin quisque: Sanskrit kac@?-ca; etc.
a withe, switch, Irish gad, Early Irish gat: *gazdo-; Gothic gazds, goad, Old High German gart, sting, rod, Norse, gaddr, sting, English yard; Latin hasta, spear (from ghaz-dhâ?).
an iron bar; from Scottish gad, a bar of metal, English gad, wedge of steel, Middle English gad, spike, bar, Norse, gaddr, as under gad.
thief, Irish gaduigh, Early Irish gataige; See goid.
tie the fore feet of a horse, etc. (H.S.D., Dial.); from gad.

lurcher dog, Irish gadhar, mastiff, hunting dog, Middle Irish gadar, mastiff, Early Irish gagar; from Norse gagarr, dog (K.Meyer)? The Norse has gagg, the fox's cry, gagl, a wild-goose; this seems to prove that the Norse has a root gag, howl, and is likely the original source of gagar.
a slender, feeble fellow, a salmon after spawning (Sh.): *gad+?
hair insect, nit ( H.S.D., M`A.):
tumult, confusion (H.S.D., Dial.):
henbane ( Sh., O'Br., H.S.D.), Irish gafann, Cornish gahen:

a cleft, chink, Irish gág: *gâggâ, gâs-g, Indo-European root ghâ@g, further ghô, gha; English gap, gape; Greek @Gháskw, yawn, @Gháos, abyss, English chaos; Latin fauces, throat. Cf. Welsh gag. Skeat takes hence English jag.
stuttering ( Sh., O'R.), Breton gak; an onomatopoetic word. Cf. English gag, which Skeat queries if from Gaelic
a cluster:
a person in want, craver; from gabh.
stormy, prodigious, Early Irish gailbech, blustering; cf. English gale, Scandinavian origin, Danish gal, furious, Norse galinn (do.). Also gailbhinn, a storm at sea, a storm of snow.
a great rough hill ( Sh., "gailebhein", H.S.D.):
excitement (M`D.):
surly look, etc.; See goill.  page 186
the gum, a swelling of the gum (in cattle), seam of shoe uppers, or junction of inner and outer barks of trees, Irish gailleach (O'B):
a blow on the cheek, Irish gailleóg; from gaill. Cf. sgailleag.
a storm; cf. Norwegian galen, wind-storm, Norse galinn, furious, English gale.
an earwig, so Irish:
a mouth overcharged so that the cheeks swell out, a mouthful of flesh. See goill.

sand, so Irish, Early Irish ganem; root gâ of Greek @Ggai@na, earth? Stokes gives the stem as gasnimâ, root ghas, Latin hare@-na, sand. But gasn- should give Gaelic gann. Also gainmheach, Early Irish ganmech.
sedge, a small divinity in marshes and sedges by water, moaning for deaths to come (Carm.):
a dart, arrow ( Sh., O'Br., H.S.D., M`E.), gàinne, arrowhead (Arg.), Irish gainne: gasniâ; root gas of gad, q.v.
a prison, Irish gaintir (Fol.):
near; See gar.
call, crow; See goir.
a shout, outcry, Irish, Early Irish gáir, Welsh gawr, clamor: *gâri-; Greek @Ggc@nrus (Dor. @Gga@nrus), voice; root gar, ger, as in goir, q.v.
laugh, gàire, a laugh, Irish gáirim, gáire, Early Irish gáire (n.); from root gar, as in gàir. Stokes give the stem as *gâsriâ, and cfs. Sanskrit hasrá, laughing, has, laugh.
a greedy stomach, deer's paunch:
freestone, gravel, Irish gairbhéal, pron. grabheal; from English gravel.
a species of wild grass (H.S.D.):

rejoicing, Irish gáirdeachas, Middle Irish gáirdechad, delighting; from gáir, laugh. K.Meyer regards this as from older *gartiugud, shortening or whiling time, from goirid, Early Irish urgartiugud, while time, amuse; with a leaning on gàir, laugh. Cf. Welsh difyru, amuse, divert, from byr, short.
an arm; from Scottish gardy, arm, gardis, yards, same as yard.
from English garlic and Gaelic garg, bitter, by popular etymology.
stale wine, Irish gairgín, dung; from garg.
convenience; See goireas.
disgust, Irish gairseamhuil, obscene, wanton:
a call, office, Irish gairm, pl. garmanna, Old Irish gairm, Welsh, Breton garm, a shout: *garsmen-; root gar of goir, q.v.  page 187
a meal chest, Irish gairnéal, a meal magazine, garner; from Scottish garnell, girnell, English garner, from Old French gernier, from Latin granarium, granary.
a gardener; from the English.
a torrent (H.S.D. and Irish), surfeit; from English gush?
wisdom, lance, plenty (Carm.):
shrivel up; from gas, twig? For sense, cf. crannadh.
a trap ( Sh., O'Br., H.S.D.), Irish gaisde, Old Irish goiste, noose; from gaoisd, horse hair?
a wisp of straw (H.S.D.); cf. gaoisd.
a daunting (M`A.); cf gais, shrivel.
valour, Irish gaisge, bravery, Early Irish gaisced, gasced, bravery, feats of arms, armour, weapons; the idea seems to be "feats" and the root the same as in gasda, q.v.
weeping, Irish gul, Early Irish gol, Indo-European @gel, pain; German qual, pain, quälen, torment; Lit gélti, to smart. Cf. galar.

valour, war, Early Irish gal, Old Breton gal, puissance, *galâ, Welsh gallu, posse, Breton galloet (do.), Cornish gallos, might: *galno-; Lithuanian galiu, I can, Ch.Sl golemu@u, great. Hence the national name Galatae, Galatian, also gallus, a Gaul (but See Gall).
good girl, brave girl, fem. for laochan, used in encouraging address: a ghalad. Root is gal (*galnat), brave.
a gallon, Irish galun; from the English

a disease, Irish, Old Irish galar, Welsh galar, grief, Breton glar, glachar, (do.); *galro-n. Bez. suggests as allied Norse galli, flaw, Umbr. holtu, Church Slavonic zu@ulu@u, bad, sore. But cf. gal, weep.
thicken cloth, fulling; from the English walk, waulk.

a Lowlander, stranger, Irish Gall, a stranger, Englishman, Early Irish gall, foreigner; from Gallus, a Gaul, the Gauls being the first strangers to visit or be visited by the Irish in Pre-Roman and Roman times (Zimmer). for derivation See gal, valour. Stokes takes a different view; he gives as basis for gall, stranger, *gallo-s, Welsh gal, enemy, foe: *ghaslo-? root ghas, Latin hos-tis, English guest. Hence he derives Gallus, a Gaul, so named from some Celtic dialect.
a bitch; cf. Welsh gast, a bitch. Gaelic is possibly for *gas-liâ. Pott has adduced Spanish galgo, greyhound, which, however, is founded on canis Gallicus. See gasradh for root.
a branch, a youth (fig.): *gas-lo-, root gas of gas, q.v. Cf. Welsh gelin, a shoot.
wood angelica, so Irish: gal+flùran.
a band put upon the dugs of mares to prevent the foal sucking (H.S.D., Dial.):
a stride, Irish gámus, proud gait or carriage: *gang-mo-(?); Scottish gang, German gang, gait. Cf. gòmag.  page 188

a year-old calf, a stirk, Irish gamhuin, a calf, Early Irish gamuin, pl.g. gamna, year-old calf; from gam, winter: "winter-old". For root, see geamhradh. Confirmed by the proverb: "Oidhche Shamhna, theirear gamhna ris na laoigh" - On Hallowe'en the calves are called stirks. Similarly and from the same root are Norse gymbr, a year-old ewe lamb, Scottish gimmer, Greek @Ghímaros, a yearling goat (Dor.). Hence gamhnach, farrow cow.
malice, gannlas, ganndas (Dial.); from gann?
rail, fold ( Sh., O'Br., H.S.D.), Irish ganail: cf. gunwale.
deceit ( Sh., O'Br., etc.), bustle, light-headed creature (Sh.), Irish, Middle Irish gangaid, deceit, falsehood:
scarce, Irish gann, Old Irish gann, gand: *gando-s; Sanskrit gandháyate, hurt; Lithuanian gendù, be injured (Stokes).
a gander, Irish gandal; from the English
roaring noise as of billows or birds:
a lump as in yarn or cloth; cf. goigean.
a blemish, Irish gaoid, a stain; cf. Early Irish góet, a wound: *gaizdo-; Lithuanian z@?aizda, a wound.
a noise, a cry of pain or alarm, sensation or thrill of pain (Perth.); from gàir, shout?
horse hair, Middle Irish goisideach, crinitus, Old Irish goiste, suspendium, laqueus: *gaissinti-, *gait-tinti; Greek @Ghaítc, mane, flowing hair.
a crafty fellow (H.S.D. from MSS.), Irish gaistín; cf. gaisde, a trap.
a fop, empty-headed fellow; from gaoth, wind.

love, Irish gaol, kin, family, Early Irish gáel, relationship: *gailo-; Lithuanian gailùs, compassionate; Gothic gailjan, gladden, German geil, wanton; Greek @Gfílos, friendly. Stokes and Strachan agree.

fæces, ordure in the intestines, gore, Irish garr, probably from English gore, Anglo-Saxon gor, dirt. Hence gaorran, big belly, a glutton. In Arg. pronounced with Northern ao sound; in North, pronounced with ao broad as in Arg. Consider skar in sharn (Scottish); cf gaoirnean or gaoirnean.
a bawd, slut: "dirty wench"; from gaorr and the female termination -sach? Cf. siùrsach.
a saddle girth; from the English
