Old Irish slind, imbrex, tile, Irish slinn, slate, tile, also Early Irish slind-gér, smooth-sharp, slate-polished (?), slinnd-glanait, whetstone-cleaned: *slindi-, root slid, sleid, smooth, glide, English slide, Lithuanian slidùs, smooth. Stokes refers slind, imbrex, to the root splid, splind, split, English split, splint; See sliseag.

stroke, rub, lick, Irish sliobhaim, polish, Middle Irish slipthe, whettened, slibad, whetting, Welsh yslipan, burnish; from Norse or Anglo-Saxon - Norse slípa, whet, make sleek, Anglo-Saxon slípan, slip, glide, Middle L.German slípen, sharpen, Middle Dutch slijpen, polish, sharpen.
posterity, tribe, Irish sliochd, Middle Irish slicht, trace, track, Old Irish slict, vestigium: *slektu-, root sleg of slighe and slachd. For similar origin, cf. German geschlecht, race, lineage.
sly, Irish slíogach, sleek, fawning, slígthech, sly; from English, Scottish sleek, Norse slíkr, smooth; Indo-European slei@g, glide ( See sliabh).

sleek, slippery, slim, the buttercup (Carm.), Irish slíomaim flatter, smooth, gloss over; from English slim, sly, crafty, slender, now "slim", Scottish slim, naughty, slim o'er, gloss over, Old Dutch slim, awry, crafty, German schlimm, bad, cunning. Hence Gaelic slìomaire, weakling, craven.
a lip, blubber lip; from English lip.
the side of a man or beast, flank, Irish slios, Old Irish sliss, pl. slessa, Welsh ystlis: *stlisti-, root stel, extend, Latin stlâtus, lâtus, wide, Church Slavonic stelja, spread.

a chip, Irish slis, sliseóg, Early Irish sliss: *slissi-, from *splid-s-ti, root splid. English split, splice, splint, German spleissen, etc. English slice has been compared, English slit, root slid, which could also produce the Gadelic forms.
a plant like the slan-lus (Carm.):

a pit, slough, Irish sloc: *slukko-, for *slug-ko-, root slug, swallow, as in slug, q.v. Skeat derives hence Anglo-Saxon slóh, English slough. German schlucht, hollow, ravine, is referred by Kluge to the root slup, lubricus.  page 329
a puddle, Irish slod; See lod.
sloke; from the Scottish or English sloke.

surname, Irish sloinnim, I. name, Old Irish slondim, name, significo, slond, significatio, Old Welsh islinnit, profatur, Middle Welsh cy-stlwn, family and clan name, Welsh ystlyned, kindred, ystlen, sex: *stlondo-, *stlondiô, I speak, name.
dash, beat against sea-like, daub; from Scottish slaister, bedaub, a wet liquid mass, to move clumsily through a miry road, also slestir (Badenoch Dial. sleastair, bedaub).
people, Irish sluagh, Old Irish sluag, slóg, Welsh llu, Cornish lu, Gaulish slôgi, in Catu-slogi: *slougo-s, cf. Slavonic sluga, a servant, Lithuanian slauginti.
act of mixing (lime, etc.) with a shovel; See sluasaid. Cf. English slubber.
a shovel, Irish sluasad, a paddle, a shovel:

swallow, slugadh (inf.), Irish slugaim, Early Irish slucim, slocim: *sluggô, root slug, lug, swallow; German schlucken, to swallow, Middle High German slucken: Greek @Glúzw, @Gluggaínw, have the hiccup. Welsh llwnc, gullet, a gulp, llyncu, to swallow, Old Breton ro-luncas, guturicavit, m.Breton lloncaff are allied to Early Irish longad, now longadh, eating, which is a nasalised form of the root slug, lug.

authority, correction, Irish smachd, Old Irish smacht, Middle Irish smachtaigim, I enjoin, smacht, fine for breaking the law: *smaktu-, from s-mag, root mag, Indo-European magh, be strong; English may, Gothic magan, be able; Greek @Gmc@nhos, means (see mac).

a particle, jot: "spot, stain" (see smod). From Scottish smad, smot, a stain, English smut. Irish has smadán, soot, smut. Cf. also Middle Irish smot, a scrap, Irish smotán, a block, Welsh ysmot, patch, spot.
threaten, intimidate, boast:
a paw; See smòg.

dust, spot, blemish, Irish smál, smól; root smal, mal (smel, mel), Lithuanian smálkas, dust, sme@?lynas, sand field, smelalis, sand, Lettic smelis, water sand, Gothic málma, sand, Norse melr, sand hill, English mole.
snuff a candle, Irish smál, embers, snuff of candle; cf. smal.
the young saith or cuddie:
think; See smuain.

a lad, a growing youth (Badenoch); root smar, from mar, mer, Greek @Gmei@nraz, boy, Sanskrit maryakás, a mannie, máryas, young man, Lithuanian marti, bride; also Welsh morwyn, girl, merch,  page 330  daughter, Breton merc'h. Cf. Aran Irish marlach, child of two to five years, either sex.
an emerald, Irish smaragaid; from Latin smaragdus, whence through French comes English emerald.
the chin, Irish smeach, smeachan, Early Irish smech: *smekâ; Lithuanian smakrà, Lettic smakrs, chin, palate; Sanskrit c@.maçru, moustache.
a slumber, slight sleep:
remains, offals, dainties:

beckon, nod, Irish sméidim, beckon, nod, hiss: *smeiddi-, root smeid, smile, Greek @Gmeidáw, smile, Prussian smaida, a smile, English smile. Welsh amneidio, beckon, nod, Old Welsh enmeituou, nutus, Old Breton enmetiam, innuo, do not agree in vowel with Gadelic.
pale, ghastly, smeilean, a pale, puny person; cf. meileach.
the end of an arrow next the bowstring, smeorine, back end of arrow head ( Wh.), Irish smeirne, a spit, broach ( Sh., O'R.):

a thrush, Irish smólach, smól, Middle Irish smolach; Welsh mwyalch, blackbird, Cornish moelh, Breton moualch: *smugal-, *smugl-, from mug (see mùch)? Stokes derives Welsh mwyalch, blackbird, from *meisalko-, German meise, English tit-mouse.
anoint, smear, Irish sméaraim, grease, smear; from the English For root See smior.
a bramble berry, Irish smeur, Early Irish smér, Welsh mwyaren, Breton mouar (pl.):  -KPD: Irish <I>sméara dubha</I>, "black smears"?
smid
a syllable, opening of the mouth, a word, Irish smid: *smiddi-, root smid, smeid, smile, laugh, as in sméid?
the chin, Irish smig, Middle Irish smeice (O'C.): *smeggi-, for *smek-gi, root smek, as in smeachan?
a smile, smiling, Irish smig, smigeadh: *smi@uggi, root smi, smile, for which See smèid. Also mìog, q.v.
spirit; from Scottish smeddum.
refuse of a feast (M'A.); See smolamas.
marrow, Irish smior, Early Irish smir, g. smera, Welsh mer: *smeru-; Old High German smero, grease, Anglo-Saxon smeoru, lard, English smear, Norse smjo@urr, butter.
throw in the air with one hand and strike with the other; formed on English smite.
crop-eared, short-chinned (R.D.), Irish smiot, ear:
smear; from the Scottish smear, English smear. See smeur.
dirt, dust, also (according to M`A.) drizzling raid; from Scottish smot, English smut. See smad.  page 331
sweepings, crumbs, fragments, smattering, Middle Irish smot, a scrap; cf. smod.
a paw; cf. Norse smjùga, creep through a hole, Anglo-Saxon smúgan, creep, English smuggle. For smàg, See also màg.
trash, fragments of victuals; cf. strolamas, brolamas.

a thought, Irish smuaineadh, Middle Irish smuained: *smoudn-, root smoud, moud; Gothic gamaudjan, remind, cause to remember; Church Slavonic mysli@u-, thought (Strachan). Cf. Middle Irish muaidnig, thought.
grief, dejection: *smoudro-, root smoud of above?
marrow, juice of the bones, Irish smuais, marrow, Early Irish smuas:
smash, Irish smuais, in shivers, in pieces; from English smash.
a snivel, a nasal sound (smùch, M`A.); for root, See smug (s-mûc-c).
smoke, drizzle; from English smoke.
a particle of dust; See smod.
a small block of wood, Irish smotan, stock, block, log:
smoke; See smùid.

snot, spittle, smugaid, spittle, Irish smug, smugaid: *smuggo-, root smug, mug, mucus; Latin emungo, wipe the nose. The root mu@g is a by-form of muq, mucus, seen in Latin mucus, etc.; for which See muc.

smoke, Irish smúid, Early Irish smúit, smútgur, smútcheo: *smúddi-, root smud. Cf. English smut, German schmutz, dirt; which Zem. thinks the Gadelic borrowed from, though the meaning makes this unlikely. There are three allied roots on European ground denoting "smoke" -- smûgh (Greek @Gsmu@-/hw, smoulder), smúg, or smaug (English smoke) and smûd (Gaelic smùid).
a snout, the face (in ridicule): from the English mug, ugly face.
glumness, dejection; Middle Irish smuilcín, a small snout: "snoutyness".

dross, peat dross, smùir, dust, a particle of dust, smùirnean, a mote; cf. Scottish smurach, peat dross, smore, smurr, a drizzling rain, Middle English smóre, dense smoke, English smother (= smorther), Old Dutch smoor. O'R. has smur from Sh., and K.Meyer translates Middle Irish smur-chimilt as "grind to dust".
extracting the juice from (Suth.):
a bill, snout, Irish smut, a large flat nose, snout:

a little audible knock, a wood pecker (snagan-daraich), Irish snag, hiccup; cf. English snock, a knock, and snagaireachd. Irish snag, snagardarach, snaghairdara, a wood pecker, seems from snaidh.  page 332

cutting or hacking wood with a knife; from Dial.English snagger, a tool for snagging or cutting off snags, that is branches, knots, etc., Scottish snagger-snee, a large knife, snicker-snee, sneg, snag, cut off branches.
active; from the above roots; cf. snasmhor.

hew, chip, shape, Irish snoighim, snaidhim (O'D.), Early Irish snaidim, snaisi, peeled, Welsh naddu, hew, chip, cut. Old Cornish nedim, ascia (Welsh neddyf, neddai, adze, Breton eze, neze), Middle Breton ezeff: *snadô; German schnat, border, schnate, a young twig, Swiss schnätzen, cut, Swab. schnatte, an incision in wood or flesh (Bez. apud Stokes). Strachan suggests the root sknad, Greek @Gknadállw, scratch, @Gknwdw/nn, tooth (see cnàmh). Hence snas, regularity.
creep; from Scottish snaik, sneak in walking, etc., snaikin, sneaking, English sneak, snake. Cf. Irish snaighim, I creep.

a knot, Irish snaidhm, Early Irish snaidm, d. snaidmaimm, naidm, bond, nexus: *nadesmen, root ned, bind, Indo-European nedh; Sanskrit nah, tie, naddha-s, tied; German nestel, lace, Old High German nestila, a band; Latin nôdus, for noz-dos, a knot. See nasg.

swim, Irish snámhaim, Early Irish snám (inf.), ro snó, swam, Welsh nawf, natatio, nofio (vb.), Middle Breton neuff, Breton neunv: *snâmu, (n.), snâô, I swim; Latin no, nâre; Greek @náw, flow; Sanskrit snâti, bathe, float.
head, chief; ceann-snaodh, head chief (Carm.):
a slice, piece; cf. Early Irish snaisse, cut, caesus, from snaidh.
snuff, Irish snaoisín, snísín; from English sneezing in sneesing powder, the old name for snuff, Scottish sneeshin, sneezin.
a strong, robust fellow, Irish snaománach, stout, jolly fellow, hearty: "knotty", from *snadm- of snaim?
a bier, Irish snaoi:
the trigger of a gun; from the English snap.
regularity, elegance, Irish snas: "goot cut", from snad of snaidh; Early Irish snass, a cut.

thread, Irish snáth, Old Irish snáthe, Welsh ysnoden, lace, fillet, noden, thread, Cornish noden, snod, vitta, Breton neudenn: *snâtio-, *snâto-n, root snâ, snê, wind, spin; Sanskrit snâyu, sinew, bow-string; Greek @Geu@'/nnctos, well-spun; German schnur, lace, tie. See the allied snìomh and snàthad.

a needle, Irish snáthad, Old Irish snáthat, Welsh nodwydd, Old Cornish notuid, Breton nadoz, nadoez: *snatantâ, snâteijâ, from snât of snàth above; cf. English needle, Gothic nêþla, Old High German nâdala, German nadel.

snow, so Irish, Old Irish snechta, pl. snechti, nives, Welsh nyf: *sniqtaio-, *snibi- (Welsh), Indo-European sni@gh, snei@gh; Gothic snaiws,  page 333  English snow, German schnee; Latin nix, nivis; Greek @Gnífa (acc.), @Gnífei, it snows; Lithuanian sniñga (vb.), snë/gas, snow; Zend. çnizh.
a nit, Irish sneagh, Old Irish sned, Welsh nedd, nits, Cornish, nedhan, Breton nezenn: *sknidâ; Anglo-Saxon hnitu, English nit, German niss; Greek @Gkónides, nits.
a stitch of clothing (Arg.):

drop, fall in drops, ooze through in drops, Irish snidhim, Early Irish snigim, Welsh di-nëu, effundere, Breton di-nou, melt, thaw, Indo-European snei@gho-, wet; Sanskrit snih, snéhati, to be humid. Allied to sneachd.

spin, wind, twist, Irish sníomhaim, Middle Irish snímaire, a spindle. sním, spinning: *snêmu-, root, snê, nê; Greek @Gnc@nma, yarn. See snàth further. Welsh has nyddu, nere, Cornish nethe, Breton nezaff. In the sense of "sadness", there is Early Irish sním, distress, Breton niff, chagrin.
affix a fishing hook to the line, Manx snooid; from Scottish snood, the hair line to which the hook is attached, a fillet, Anglo-Saxon snód, fillet, English snood.
rapid motion of a boat.
a smile; See snuadh.
sap of a tree; root snu, flow, Irish snuadh, a stream, Greek @Gnéw, swim, English snot, Norse snúa, turn, Gothic sniwan, go.
testiness; from Scottish snog, snag, snarl, flout.
smell, snuff the wind, turn up the nose in smelling; founded on English snout.
hue, appearance, beauty, Irish snuadh, Middle Irish snúad; root snu, flow, as in Early Irish snuad, hair, head of hair, Irish snuadh, stream (see snodhach).
here, this, Irish so, Early Irish, P.Irish seo, so: *sjo- (beside *so, as in -sa, -se), Sanskrit syá, sá, the, this, German sie, she, they, Old High German siu, she (= Sanskrit sya@-/, Gaelic sì).
a prefix denoting good quality, Irish só-, Old Irish so-, su-, Welsh hy, Breton he-; Sanskrit su-, good, Zend. hu-.
turn, prevent, Old Irish sóim, inf. sood, root sov, discussed under iompaidh.
(M`L.), primrose, Irish sobhróg (Fol.), somharcin (O'Br.), sóbhrach (O'R.), Early Irish sobrach, g. sobarche:

forepart of anything, ploughshare, snout, Irish soc, Early Irish socc, Welsh swch (f.), Cornish soch, Breton soc'h, souc'h (m.): *succo-, snout, pig's snout, *sukku-, a pig, Welsh hwch, Cornish hoch, Breton houc'h (Anglo-Saxon sugu, English sow, Latin sûs, etc.). So Thurneysen (Rom., 112), who clinches his argument by Early Irish corr being both "crane" and "beak". French soc, ploughshare, English sock are from Celtic. Stokes suggests the possibility of Celtic being  page 334  from Medieval Latin soccus, vomer, or allied to Old High German seh, vomer, Latin secare.
ease, easy, Irish socair, easy, secure, Middle Irish soccair; opposite is deacair, Old Irish seccair: *di-acair, *so-acair, from *acar, convenience, root cor, place, as in cuir. Hence acarach.
a benefit, emolument, Irish sochar, emolument, wealth, ease, Middle Irish sochor, good contract (Sench. Mór); from so- and cor, q.v.

silliness, a yielding disposition, socharach, simple, compliant, Irish socharach, obliging, easy, Welsh hygar, amiable, Breton hegar, benignus; from so- and càr, dear. The Irish is also from sochar, ease.
silence, Irish sochd ( O'R., Sh.), Middle Irish socht: *sop-tu-, root svop of suain (Dr Cameron).

noise of boiling water, steam of water in which meat is boiled, boiled meat, Irish sod, boiled meat (O'Br.); from Norse soð, broth or water in which meat has been boiled, English sodden, seethe, sod, Scottish sotter, boil slowly, sottle, noise of boiling porridge, etc.
an awkward person, a stout person; from Scottish sod, a heavy person, sodick, soudie, a clumsy heavy woman.
a pillion, clout; from Scottish sodds, a saddle made of cloth.

pride, flattery, Irish sodal, sotal, sutal, Old Irish sotla, pride, insolence, sotli, animositates; this has been adduced as the source of English sot, French sot. According to Stokes *sput-tlo-, Welsh ffothyll, pustula, Latin pustula, Sanskrit phutkar, puff (Stokes).
caressing, joy, joyous reception:
trotting, a trotting horse (Sh., Lh., etc.), Irish sodar, trotting:
mirth, good humour, tipsiness; from *sugg, a short form of the root of sùgradh.
luxury, riot, Irish sógh, Middle Irish sodh, Early Irish suaig, prosperous: *su-ag-, root ag of aghaidh, àgh.
bashful, ignorant; See saidealta.
a jolly-looking or stout person; See sod.
pleasure, delight, Irish sóighneas: so-gne-, root gen.
officiousness, flattery, Irish soilíos; from Latin sollicitus?
wind, a fair wind:
clear, visible, Irish soilléir: from so- and léir. The ll is due to the analogy of soillse.
brightness, so Irish, Old Irish soillse, soilse: *svelnestio-; See solus for connections.

prosperous, easy, easy circumstanced, good-natured, seems to combine Old Irish somme, dives, and Old Irish soinmech,  page 335  lucky, good, Irish soinmheach, fortunate, happy. The former Stokes derives from so-imbi-s, for which See iomadh; the latter is so-nem-ech, root nem, under nèamh. Middle Irish somenmnach, good-spirited, is from meanmna.
esteem (n.), soineil, handsome; cf. sònraich for the root.
fair weather, Irish soinean, Middle Irish soinend, Early Irish sonend; the opposite of soinionn is doinionn, for su-sîn-enn, du-sîn-enn, from sín, now sian, weather, rain (Stokes).
the east, Irish soir, Early Irish sair; from s- (see suas) and air (= *are), on, q.v.
sack, vessel, bottle; cf. searrag.
easy, gentle, soirbheas, success, wind, flatulence (Arg.), Irish soirbh, Old Irish soirb, facilis, opposed to doirb, difficilis, root reb, or rib, manare (Ascoli). But compare Gaelic reabh.
snug, fond of ease (M`A.); from Scottish sosh, snug, social.
a ball of fire in the sky, a portent (M`A.):
gospel, Irish soisgéal, soisgeul, Old Irish soscéle; from so- and sgeul.
taste, decency, rest, stillness; from Scottish sonsy?
a vessel, Irish soitheach, Middle Irish soithech, saithech: *satiko-:
tame, docile, gentle: *so-seimh, from sèimh? So Munro, who writes soisheamh.
ere, before, Irish, Early Irish sul; root svel of seal.
highly delighted (M`A.; sollach, jolly, Arms.); founded on sòlas. Arms.'s word seems from English jolly.
a provision, purveying, preparing, Irish soláthar; from so- and làthair.
joy, comfort, solace, Irish sólas; from Latin sôlatium, English solace.
a welcome, rejoicing, Irish sollamhuin, a solemnity, feast, rejoicing, Early Irish sollamain; from Latin sollemne, English solemnity.

light, Irish, Middle Irish solus, Early Irish solus, bright: *svl@.nestu-, root svel; Anglo-Saxon svelan, glow, English sultry; Greek @Gsélas, light, @Gselc/nc, moon, @Ge@`lánc, torch; Sanskrit svar, sheen, sun.
bulky, large, placid; from Middle Irish soma, abundance, with adj. terminations -ail and ta. See soimeach further.
convert, upset (Carm.); cf. Irish sóm.
sake, cause, air son, on account of, Irish son, ar son, Middle Irish son, er son; from Early Irish son, word (root sven of seinn)?
happy, Irish, Early Irish sona, opposite of dona: *so-gná-vo-s, "well-doing"; root gna of gnìomh.

a stout man, hero; from sonn, club, staff, Middle Irish suinn catha, captains, "staves of battle". Cf. Norse stafn-buar, the stem men, or picked marines on the forecastle. Cf. Tàillear dubh na tuaighe was "ursainn chatha nan Camshronach". See sonn.  page 336

a staff, cudgel, beam, Irish, Early Irish sonn, Welsh ffon, Old Welsh fonn: *spondo-, Greek @Gsfendónc, a sling, @Gsfedanós, vehement; Sanskrit spand, draw, move; Latin pendo, hang (Rhys). Stokes gives the stem *spundo, allied to Norse spjót, a lance, Old High German spioz, spit, spear. Cf. Middle Latin spnda, trabecula, repagulum.

appoint, ordain, Irish sonraighim, sonrach, special, Early Irish sunnraid, Old Irish sainriud, especially, sainred, proprietas, sain, singularis, proprius, Old Welsh han, alium: *sani-, especially; Gothic sundrô, privately, English sunder; Latin sine, without; Sanskrit sanutár, without.

a wisp, Irish sop, Early Irish sopp, Welsh sob, sopen; from English sop, Norse soppa. Zimmer takes the Irish from Norse svöppr, sponge, ball; Stokes derives it from Norse sópr, besom. the Welsh sob, sopen favours and English source.
hesitate, grudge, shun:
a farewell, blessing, Irish soraidh, happy, successful, Middle Irish soraid, Early Irish soreid; from so- and réidh.
light, bright, Irish, Early Irish sorcha; opposite of dorch, q.v
rest or support, foot-stool, light stand, peer-man; from sorcha.
a flue, vent, Irish sórn, Early Irish sornn, Welsh ffwrn, Cornish forn; from Latin furnus, oven, whence English furnace.
a coarse mess or mixture; from Scottish soss.
kill, fell, Irish spaidim, benumb, spaid, spad, a clod (cf. spairt), a sluggard, eunuch; cf. Welsh ysbaddu, exhaust, geld, from Latin spado, eunuch. Hence spadanta, benumbed.
flat, Irish spad-; from *spad of spaid, spade?
a quarter or limb of an animal cut off; from Late Latin spatula, a shoulder blade, spatula prcina, leg of pork, also spadula, a shoulder, spadlaris, a quarter of a beast. Cf. Welsh yspaud, shoulder.
fop, braggart; cf. Norse spjátra, behave as a fop. See spaideil.
a paddle, plough-staff, so Irish; from Middle English spaddle, paddle, dim. of spade.

a strong and quick pull, the utmost extent of the outstretched arms, the grass cut by one scythe-stroke, spadh, a scyth's stroke (Bad.); from Latin spatium. Meyer objects. If Stokes' theory were right spadh could be from root spa, pull, span. Cf. English swath.

a claw or paw, limb of an animal, club-foot, spàgach, club-footed or awkward in the legs, Irish spág, claw, club-foot, clumsy leg, Welsh ysbach, a claw; spàga-da-ghlid, a buffoon, tomfool (Wh.):  page 337
uttering words indistinctly, spagadh, obliquity of the mouth, spaig, a wry mouth:
ostentation, conceit:
a spade, Irish spád; from the English
foppish, well-dressed: "strutting", from Latin spatior, as in spaisdear below? Cf., however, spadair.
pride, conceit, spailpean, fop, Irish spailp, spailpín, rascal, mean fellow, "spalpeen":
a spoon, Manx spain; from norse spánn, spónn, spoon, chip, Middle English sp@-n, Anglo-Saxon spón, chip. Irish spúnóg, spoon, is from the English

an effort, struggle, Irish spáirn, sbáirn, wrestling, struggling; from the Norse sporna, kick with the feet, struggle, sperna, kick, spurn, English spurn. Hennessey derived it from English sparring (Athen@oeum, 15/8/71).
foppish, spairis, having the hands in the trousers' pockets (M`A.); founded on Scottish spare, opening of the fore part of the breeches.
a turf, clod, a splash, Irish spairt; verb spairt, daub, plaster, splash, brain, Irish spairtim: cf. Norse sparða, pole-axe, whence Middle English spert or spart.

a saunterer, spaisdeireachd, sauntering, Irish spaisdeóireachd, promenading, walking; Norse spázera, walk, Danish spadsere, German spazieren, from Italian (13th Cent.), spaziare: all from Latin spatior, walk, promenade.
a shuttle, Irish spól; from Norse spóla, a weaver's shuttle, Middle English spo@-le, now spool, German spule, bobbin, spool. Hence spàlag, pea pod.
thin plate of metal, spangle; from Norse spo@'ng, g. spangar, a spangle, Middle English spang, now spangle, Anglo-Saxon spange, a clasp, German spange, buckle.
sever, divide, wean (a child); from Scottish spain, spane, wean, prevent, confused with Middle English spannen, stretch, span.
a hinge, hasp; from the English spang, a spangle, Anglo-Saxon spang, a hasp; or Anglo-Saxon spannan, to clasp, Norse spenna, spennir, grasper, Scottish spenn, to button.
wrap, swathe: *svil, *sveil, as in till, etc.
a roost, from spàrr.

a joist, beam, roost, Irish sparra, wedge, spear, Early Irish sparr, a beam, joist; from Norse sparri, a spar, Swed., Danish sparre, Old High German sparro, bar, balk, German sperren, a spar, English spar. Hence Gaelic spàrr, drive as a nail or sedge, thrust, Irish sparraim; Gaelic sparrag, a bridgle bit, "little bar".
a limb, a clumsy libm; cf. spoll.  page 338
the dew-lap of a beast, Irish sparsan (Lh., O'B); See spursan.

a wasp, connspeach, for conas-beach, "wrangling or dog bee", from beach, bee? The Irish for "wasp" is eircbheach. connspeach is referred by Stokes (Dict. 302) to *spekâ, Greek @Gsfc/x; for phonetics cf. padhadh, piuthar, also speir and speal.
a blow, thrust, stitch in the side, Irish speach, a kick:
door step (Carm.).

a very small foot or leg (M`A.), speadach, sheepshanked (M`A.), kicking (Badenoch, where spead means a cow's or sheep's kick); cf. Middle Irish spedudhud, a musical instrument (?), Kuno Meyer's "King and Hermit". Root sped-do-, spend-.
a scythe, Irish speal, scythe, reaping hook, Middle Irish spel: *spelâ, Greek @Gyalís, shears, root spal, clip, pull, further English psalm (so Stokes).
a splinter; from Scottish spelk, a splint attached to a fracture, Middle English spelke, a splinter, Norse spjalk, spelkur, splint, Dutch spalk.
a splinter; from Teutonic - Middle English spélde, now a spill, Middle High German spelte, a splinter, German spalten.
a cow-fetter, a fetter for wild goats; See speireach.
a spike, Irish spéice; from Norse spík, a spike, English spike, German speiche. Welsh has ysbig.
cattle, herd, Irish speil, herd of cattle or swine; *speli-, allied to Latin spolium (Stokes).
slide, skate; from Scottish speil, play, bonspel, curling game, German spielen, play.

hoof or ham of cattle, claw talon, ankle and thereabouts of the human leg, Irish speirr, hough, ham: *s-peri-; compare Welsh ffer, ankle, ber, leg, shank: Cornish fer, crus, Early Irish seir, heel, di pherid: *speret-, Greek @Gsfurón, ankle, heel; root sper, English spur, spurn, Latin sperno, etc.
cow-fetter, foot fetter; from speir and *rich, tie, for which last See buarach.
strength, force, courage; founded on Latin spîritus.
sparrow-hawk; from Middle English sper-hauk, Anglo-Saxon spear-hafoc, Norse sparrhaukr, from sparrow and hawk.
esteem, liking, Irish spéis, Middle Irish sbéis; seemingly from Middle Irish sbesailte, special, from Latin species, look (cf. English re-spect).
diverge, divaricate, tear asunder, branch; from Scottish spaik, a spoke (in a wheel), English spoke, Anglo-Saxon spáca.
spectacles, Irish speucláir, a glass, spectacles; from the Latin.  page 339

the heaven, firmament, Irish speur, spéir; from the Late Latin spera, a hemisphere, circle (of each planet), celestial region, Latin sphaera, a sphere (whence the English), from Greek @Gsfai@npra, globe. Cf. Scottish spere, sphere, circle, "the speir of the moon".
spite, Irish spíd; from the English Hence spìdeig or spideag, a taunt.
speed, haste; from English speed.
nightingale (spìdeag, Middle F.), Irish spideóg, robin:
a delicate or slender creature (Arms. spìdeag); from Scottish spit, a little, hot-tempered person, spitten, a puny, mischievous person, English spit.
a spital, hospital, Irish spideul, Middle Irish spidél; from Middle English spitel, from Old French ospital, from Latin hospitale.
pinnacle; "spidean an tempuill":
a seedling, dwarfish person:
meanness, dastardliness, spìocach, mean:
a spigot, Irish spiocaid (O'R.); from English sources - Middle English spigot, English spike.
wheezing, Irish spiochan; See pìochan.
nibble, peel, pluck, Irish spiolaim, spialaim, snatch, pluck. See piol.
unhusk, shell; from the Scottish spilk, pilk, shell pease, etc., spilkins, split pease. Cf. spealg.
pluck up, pull, tear, Irish spíonaim, teaze, probe, pluck, examine; cf. Middle Irish spín, a thorn, from Latin spîna, thorn.
strength, Irish spionnadh, spionnamhail, strong (Keat.): *sphen or *sven; See faod.
a currant, a particle in the throat, a maggot, a drop of rain or flake of snow, Irish spionán, a gooseberry, Middle Irish spínan; from Latin spîna.
a spirit, so Irish, Old Irish spiurt, spirut; from Latin spiritus, English spirit. Welsh has ysbryd, Cornish speris, Breton speret.
spice, Irish spiosra; from English spicery, Old French espicerie, spices, from Latin species.
a hen-roost, hammock; from Norse sperra, a spar, rafter, with a leaning on Gaelic iris, roost.
pillar, support (Carm.):

a chip, spelk, small bit of wood, bite, Irish spiothóg, a finger stone for throwing at an object ( Con., Sh.), spitheóg, a flake of snow; a borrowed word belonging to the English group spike, spigot, but likely taken from Norse spík, sprig, spike.
a sparkle, flash, Irish splanc:
a snot, mucus, Irish spleangaid (O'R.); a side-form of sglongaid?  page 340
a splay foot; from English splay.
ostentation, romance, false flattery, Irish spleadh; from Middle English spleien, display, from displeien, now display.
a sort of wooden paddle to dig up sand eels; See pleadhag.
stare, squint, spread out by trampling:
fluke of an anchor (M`A.); founded on English fluke.
tobacco pouch, Irish spliuchán, a pouch, bag, leather purse; hence Scottish spleuchan. Cf. Welsh blwch, a box.
a snot, icicle, anything hanging down: *s-cluig? Cf. cluigein.
splay-footed:
a discontented countenance:
a lame hand or foot, splay foot; See pliut.
a spoke; from the English
address one quickly and angrily, intimidate, affront, attack, Irish spochaim, provoke, affront, rob; cf. spoth.
a claw, paw, Manx spaag, Irish spâg, Welsh ysbach:

a quarter (as of a sheep, M`A.), spòld, a piece or joint of meat, Irish spódhla, spólla, a piece of meat; from Scottish spaul, limb, spald, shoulder, from old French espaule, espalle, Late Latin spatula, shoulder, whence English epaulet. Irish spolla is also hence. Cf. spadag, spathalt.

mangle, slaughter, hew down in battle, also (Dial. Badenoch) splutter; from the English. Cf. Middle English splatten, cut open, Scottish sploit, squirt, spout. spoltadh, drops flying out of a vessel when boiling or stirred carelessly.
sponge, tinder, Irish sponc, Early Irish sponge, Welsh ysbwng, sponge, Cornish spong, Breton spone, sponeñk; from Latin spongia, sponge, from Greek @Gspoggiá, allied to Latin fungus.

a spur, claw, talon, Irish spor, Middle Irish sbor, a spur for a horse; from Norse spori, a spur, spor, foot trace, Danish spore, Swed. sporre, English spur, Anglo-Saxon spora; root sper of speir, etc. Hence sporadh, inciting, scraping the earth (as a hen), Scottish spur.
tinder, flint, gun-flint; from English spar.
a purse, Irish sparán, sporán, sbarrán, Middle Irish sboran, Welsh ysbur: *s-burr- from *burs, from Late Latin bursa, a purse, whence English purse, bursary; originally from Greek @Gbursc, a hide.
crumbs (M`F.):
sport, Irish spórt (Fol.); from the English
a spot; from the English  page 341

geld, castrate, Irish spothaim, Middle Irish spochad (n.), Welsh dysbaddu, Breton spaza; from Latin spado, eunuch, whence English spay. The Middle Irish spochad is thought by Stokes to be from Breton spac'hein (inf.).
strength, sprightliness, Irish spracadh; from English sprack, lively, Norse spraekr, lively, Swed. spräker; from Norse also comes English spark - Norse sparkr.
a sever reprimand; See spreig.
a loud blast, report of a gun; cf. Scottish spraich, a cry, Norse spraki, a report.
burst, sound loudly while bursting, kill, Irish spréidhim, spread, burst (spreighim, O'Br.), Early Irish sprédaire, brush for sprinkling the holy water; from Middle English spraeden, now spread.
a cloven stick for closing the wound of bled cattle; from English springe, twig, rod, snare with flexible rod.
cattle, Irish spré(idh), Middle Irish spré, spreid, Welsh praidd, flock, booty; from Latin praeda, booty. Hence Scottish spreith, booty.
blame, reprove, incite, Irish spreagaim; founded on Middle English spraechen, now speak, German sprechen.
scatter, burst; See spreadh.
blubber lip: *s-breill, from ++breall?
the remains of a wreck:
weakness, weak person; from *s-breòch-, being the same in root as breòclaid?
(H.S.D.), a projecting beam, crann spreòid, a bow-sprit; from Middle English spre@-ot, a sprit, now sprit; Anglo-Saxon spréot, Middle Dutch spriet. Hence spreòd, incite.
dejection, sadness, Irish sprochd: *s-broc, Middle Irish broc, sorrow, anxiety (also sbrog). Cf. murcach for root; or bròn?
dewlap, bird's crop, Irish sprogaille, sbrogaill, also sgroban, sgrogul, neck: *s-broggo-. See bràghad.
a crumb; from pronn.
single stick (Lewis): Norse sproti, stick.
brushwood, firewood, Irish spruán: *s-bruan, from bruan. M`A. has sprudhan, fragments.
fingers, sprouts; from the English sprout.

crumbs, fragments, Irish spruille(ach), crumb, fragment, sprudhaille (Lh.), Middle Irish sbruileach. Cf. spruan. Middle Irish has also spuirech, fragmentum, Welsh ysbwrial, sweepings, ysborion, refuse of fodder.
spruce, neat, Irish sprúiseamhuil; from the English spruce.
claw (as of eagle):
crown of the head, a pinnacle, callosity, blister, Irish spuaic, a welt, callus, pinnacle:  page 342
baling ladle (N.H.): cf. English spudge.
spoil, plunder; from Scottish spulye, lay waste, plunder, English spoil, French spolier, Latin spoliare. Welsh has ysbail, a spoil.
spoil, plunder, Irish spúinim; another form of spùill, borrowed directly from Latin spoliare?
spurge, milkweed, Irish spuirse; from the English spurge, Middle English sporge.
nail of a cat, a clutch, spùllach, nailed, greedy (M`A.):
a gizzard, Irish spursán; cf. sparsan, dewlap.
a spout; from the Scottish spoot, English spout.
a straw; from the English:
falling water (Carm.):
strife ( Suth. R.D.):
tear, rend, rob, Irish sracaim; Gaelic has also racadh: *srakko-, for rap-ko-, root rap of Latin rapio?
a spark of fire, Irish srad: *sraddâ, from strad or str@.-d, root ster, as in English star, Greek @Ga@'stc/r. Middle Irish has srab-tine, lightning, from the same root.
a street, Irish sráid, Early Irish sráit; from Latin strâta@- (via), whence English street. K.Meyer derives it from Norse straeti, which itself comes from Latin
the plant shepherd's purse, Irish sraidín (sráidín, O'Br.); cf srad.
the cartilage of the nose, sneeze (M`A.); cf. root of sròn.
a jet of milk from the cow's udder, Irish sramh (srámh, O'R.); root ster, str@., strew.

a snore, buzz, Irish srann, Early Irish srand, Old Irish srennim, sterto: *stre-s-no-, root ster, pster of Latin sterto, snore, sternno, sneeze (see sreothart further). Stokes makes the Gadelic to be *strenvô, like Latin sternuo.

stumble, make a false step, rush forward violently; cf. Irish sraoinim, defeat, overthrow, scatter, Middle Irish sráined, dragging down, defeat, Early Irish sroenim, hurl, drag, defeat: *sroino-, root ster, strew, scatter (English strew, etc.).
a huff, snuffiness; M`A. has sròin, a huff: from sròn, nose?

a valey, strath, Irish, Middle Irish srath, meadow land or holm along banks of a river or loch, often swampy (Joyce), Old Irish israth, in gramine, Welsh ystrad, strath, Early Welsh strat, istrat, planities: *stratu-, root ster, spread, scatter; Latin strâtus, from sterno, I strew; Greek @Gstrwtós, spread, @Gstorénnumi, scatter; English strew, strand (?).
a pack-saddle, Irish, Old Irish srathar, Welsh ystrodyr; from Medieval Latin stratura, from stratum, sterno, spread.  page 343
rheum (M`A.), a wrinkle, sreamach, blear-eyed, Irish srám, eye rheum, srámach, blear-eyed, sremach (Four Masters). Stokes derives this from Anglo-Saxon streám, English stream.
curbing or checking by the nose:

a string, Irish srang, srang, Early Irish sreng: *srengo-, strengo-, Gadelic root streg; immediately allied either to English string, Norse strengr, German strang (Indo-European stre @Gh, Greek @Gstréfw, turn), or to Latin stringo, bind, German strick, string (Indo-European stre@g). The Indo-European roots stre@g and stre@gh are allied ultimately. sraing, lie, embroidery (Hend.).
a row, series, Irish sreath, Old Irish sreth: *srito-, *sr@.-to-, root ser, order, join; Latin series, row, sors, lot.
filmy skin covering unborn calf (H.S.D., etc.). When dried, it was used for covering vessels:

a sneeze, Irish sraoth, sraothfurtach, earlier sreod, Welsh trew, ystrew, a sneeze, ystrewi (vb.), Breton strefia, strevia (vb.), root streu, pstreu (Stokes), further ster, pster, Latin sternuo, sneeze, Greek @Gptárnumai (do.)
a bridle, Irish srian, Early Irish srían, Welsh ffrwyn; from Latin frênum (through Welsh).
a drop, spark, srideach, white streaked with dark: *sriddi, root sr@.d of srad.
the strangles; founded on the English.
a torrent of quick words; founded on sruth.
a push (Sh.), small quantity of liquor (A.M`D.); See sruab.
a whip, so Irish, Early Irish sraigell, Old Irish srogill (gen.), Welsh ffrowyll; from Latin flagellum.

a streamer, banner, silk, Irish sról, satin, byssus; from Latin stragulus, coverlet, pall, whence Cornish strail, tapestry, Welsh ystraill, a mat. Stokes (Lismore) has suggested a form *fról, *flór, French velours, velvet, Breton flour, velveted.

a nose, Irish, Old Irish srón, Welsh ffroen, Breton froan: *srognâ; *sroknâ (Stokes, Greek @Gréghw, snore, snort, @Grégkw), *sprognâ (Strachan), to which Latin spargo has been compared. Welsh has also trwyn (*trugno- or trogni-), Cornish trein.

drink up with noise of the lips, pull hastily out of the water: *sroubbo-, root sreub? Cf. srùb, and Lithuanian sriaubiu, sup, lap up, Church Slavonic sru@ubati, swallow, Latin sorbeo, English absorb.
shortbread cake having five corners (M`A. for Islay):
a spout; from the Scottish stroup, spout, Middle English stru@-pe, throat, Norse strjúpi, the spouting trunk when the head is cut off, Swed. strupe, throat. Hence srùban, a cockle.  page 344

a stream, Irish, Old Irish sruth, g. srotha, Welsh ffrwd, Cornish frot, alveus, Breton froud: *srutu-, root sreu, flow; Greek @Gr@`úsis, a flowing, @Gr@`eu@nma, a stream, @Gr@`éw, flow; English stream, Norse straumr; Lithuanian sravju, flow. Some have referred the Celtic words to the root spreut, spreu, to well, German sprudel, a well, sprühen, emit sparks, drizzle, further English spurt, spout.
rinsing, half-washing, Irish sruthlaighim; from sruth.
advantage, use; from the English - founded on stay?
wide, asunder, straddling, Irish stabhaighim, straddle:
a wry neck, a sullen attitude of the head (M`A.); See stùichd. Pronounced in Arg. staoi'c, staghaic.
a stable, Irish stabla; from Latin stabulum, through the English.

a precipice, steep hill, Middle Irish stacc, a stack (Four Masters), stacc, a pile, piece; from Norse stakkr, a stack (of hay), stakka, a stump, Swed. stack, a stack, Scottish (Shetland, etc.) stack, a columnar isolated rock, English stack.

a stop, Irish stad, Early Irish stad (Cormac); founded on Latin status, position, stat, stands (Hennessey, Stokes). Cf. Norse staða, a standing, a position. Ascoli compares Old Irish astaim, sisto (= ad-sad-to-, root sed of suidhe).
(better stagh), a stay, a certain rope in ship's rigging; from Norse stag (do.), English stay, Danish, German stag.
state, condition, Irish stáid, Middle Irish stait; from Latin statio (K.Meyer). Welsh has ystâd, from Latin status. Irish stáid may be from the English See stàideil.
stately, Irish stáideamhuil; from English state, stately.
a stair, Irish staighre, Middle Irish staigre; from the English, and Anglo-Saxon stáeger. The Gaelic is possibly from English stair, just as paidhir and faidhir are from pair and fair (Dr Cameron).
a bandage, strap:
stubbornness, stop, stump, Irish stailc; cf. tailce; cf. Norse stilkr, stalk.
steel; from Norse stál, steel, stálin weapons (pl.), German stahl, English steel.
a peg, small pointed rock; from Norse stöng, g. stangar, a pole, Scottish and English stang.
a well-built person or animal (M`A.), staingean, obstinate boorish person, Irish stainc, incivility; from staing.
a stopple, Irish stapal (O'R.); from the Scottish stappil, English stopple.
a staple, bar; from English staple.  page 345
a path over a bog, stepping stones in a river. Dr Cameron has suggested connection with Dutch steiger, waterside stairs, English stair. For s-tar, from *tar, cross (see thar)?
a rattling, a rumbling noise; also dairireach, q.v. For s-dairirich.
a particle, small quantity (Perth); from Scottish starn, particle, grain, star, from star.
noise (as the tread of horses), a violent push: *s-tairn; See tàirneanach for root. Cf. Irish stathruim, clatter, din.
(Suth.), conceited, ostentations; from stàirn, noise: "creating a furore". English stern?
a threshold, Irish tairseach, Early Irish tairsech: "cross beam or stone:; for root See tarsuinn, transverse.
a considerable distance, trip (M`A.); from English start?
a magistrate or great man, stàitean, great men; See stàt.
a stallion, Irish stail; from the English.

stiffen, stalcanta, firm, strong; for s-talc; See tailce. M`A. gives stalc as meaning "dash one's foot against (Islay), thread a hook, thump, stare." In the meaning of "stalk", the word is from the English

an overhanging rock, craggy steep, precipice, stall, a peat bank; from Norse stallr, any block or shelf on which another thing is placed, pedestal, step of a mast, stall, stalli, an altar, English stall, Lithuanian stalas, table.
stupidly deaf, heedless (Wh.):
dashing against, thumping (M`A.):
a stomach; from the English
sea tangle, staf (Lewis), Middle stafr, staff.
reduce to order, subject, break in, drub (M`A.), stannadh, subject (Heb.); from Norse stafr, a stick, staffa fyir, rule, fyrir stafni, aim at, stafn, stem?
stamp, trample, Irish stampáil, a stamping, prancing; from English stamp.
tin, Irish stán, Welsh ystaen, Cornish, Breton stean; from Latin stannum, tin (for *stagnum; cf. Italian stagno). See staoin.
below, down; Sutherland form of a bhàn, on analogy of a' s t-foghar, a' s t-samhradh, etc.:
a ditch, pool; from Scottish stank, Old French estang, now étang, from Latin stagnum.
sting, from Scottish stang, sting (as a bee), a sting, Norse stanga, prick, goad; further English sting.
the fish stickleback; from stang, sting.  page 346
a vat, tub, Irish stanna, vat, barrel; from English tun, ton, Middle English tonne. See tunna.
a standard, yard, limit; from the English It also means "affected coyness".
a collop, steak, Irish staoig, Middle Irish stáic; from Norse steik, English steak (Stokes, K.Meyer).
pewter, tin; See stàn.
juniper, caoran staoin:
laziness:
bent, awry, shallow (Hend.), Irish staon:
bending of the body to a side; for staon-um.
a mixture of meal and cold water; from Scottish stappack (do.), stap, mix, hash, Norse stappa, bray in a mortar.
loud noise, noise of the sea:
a bar, bolt, staple; See staipeal.
cunning, deceitful (Suth.):
romping, blustering (M`A.):
a strong, robust fellow:
firm; from Norse starkr, strong, English, German stark.
shove, dash, starradh, pushing violently, dashing against, a failing or freak, snap-starradh, a stumbling-block, obstruction, a ball on the end of a spear; cf. starr-(shuileach).
a tusk or gag-tooth, Irish stairfhiacail; from starr and fiacail.

having the eyes distorted, stard, a moon-eye (M`A.); cf. Norse starblindr, blind with a cataract, Old High German starablind, German starr, stiff, English stare, "fixed" look, Scottish stare, stiff, starr, sedge, star, a speck on the eye.
pride, haughtiness, Irish státamhuil, stately; from the English state, Middle English stát, from Latin status. Cf. stàideil, stàta.
the state or Government; from the English
(to) within, into, Irish steach, a steach, Middle Irish is tech, Early Irish isa tech: *in-san-tech, "into the house"; from teach. Cf. stigh.
firm, pointed or punctual in speech (M`A.); cf. English steady.
a little staff or stick, Irish steafóg; from English staff.
a blazing fire (Perth), "a drop in the e'e":
spout, cause to spout, pour out, Irish steallaim, squirt, sprinkle, steallaire, a tap; from Latin stillo, I drop, English distill.
a pole to kill birds with (Carm.):
a bittern, sea-bird, an inn-keeper's sign:
foundation; from Norse staeða, establish, Ork. steeth, foundation, steethe, to found.  page 347
a peg or pin for things hung; cf. Scottish stell, a prop.
(steilleach, M`F.), lusty, stout, ruddy; cf. stéidheil, steady, solid, from stéidh.
the itch, mange, Irish steinle (Lh., etc.); from teine, fire?
any person or thing standing (or sticking) upward, an attendant (steòcair also); from Scottish stog, stug, stook, stubble, stumpy horns, stok, English stick.
guide, direct, manage; from Norse stjórna (do.), stjórn, steering, rule, English stern, steer. See stiùir.
a horse, steed, Irish stead (O'R.), Middle Irish stéd; from Anglo-Saxon stéda, Anglo-Saxon stéda, Middle English stede, now steed.

a strip, stripe, streak, Irish stíall, Early Irish stíall, girdle, strap, board; cf. Welsh astell, Middle Welsh ystyll, shingle, plank, Cornish stil, rafter, Old French esteil, pole, Latin astella, splinter, or from Old High German stihhil, pole, post.
a fault, blemish, pain; from Scottish stick, a bungle or botch, English stick, stich (older sticke).
adhere, stick; from the English
ghostly person, "imp" (Carm.); Norse stygr, shy.
peep, Manx steetagh to peep; See dìd.
(stìdean, H.S.D.), a cat, the word by which a cat is called to one (also stididh and tididh, from Scottish cheet, cheety, puss, cat, English chit, cub, youngster; from cat, like kitten).
a skulking or abject look or attitude; from Norse stygr, shy.
inside, Irish 'stigh, Early Irish istig, istaig, isintig; for *in-san-tig, 'in the house", from tigh, house.
the hinge of a box, hasp:
a steeple; from the English
limping: "sticking"? From the English anyway.
a strip in cloth (M`A.); from Scottish steik, English stitch.
head-band, snood:
a stirrup, Irish stioróip; from Middle English stiro@-p, Anglo-Saxon stigráp.
stretch (at death, Arg.); from English stark?
a thin, worn-out rag, an emaciated woman, stiorlan, a thin person; stiorlach, thin gruel (M`D.); stirlean, thin gruel or watery stuff (Bad.):
sturgeon (M`A.), stirean; from Latin sturio(n), whence, through French, English sturgeon.
a stipend; from the English
a steward, Irish stìobhard; from the English
steeer, guide, Irish sdiuirim, Middle Irish stiurad or stiúrad; from Anglo-Saxon steóran, steer, now steer, Norse sty/ra, Gothic stiurjan.
a long tail or train, a foolish person. In the latter sense, the Gaelic is from Scottish stupe, from Latin stupidus.  page 348
gruel; from the Scottish stooram, stooradrink, stourreen, sturoch, a warm drink, meal and water mixed, from stoor, to stir, agitate.

thrust, stab, fix (as a stake), stob, a stake, stick, stob (Scottish), Irish stobaim, stab, thrust; from Scottish stob, a side-form of English stab. Cf. Norse stobbi, a stump, English stub, Middle English stob.
a stove; from the English
a stock, pillar, stump, Irish stoc; from English stock.

a trumpet, so Irish, Middle Irish stocc, Early Irish stoc; cf. Scottish stock-horne, stock-and-horn, a pipe formed of a sheep's thigh-bone inserted into the smaller end of a cut horn, with an oated reed, from English stock. Gadelic is borrowed.
a stocking, Irish stoca; from the English
a particle, whit, faintest glimpse of anything (Dial.); from Scottish styme.
a storm, Irish stoirm; from English, Middle English storm, Norse stormr, German sturm.
prominet; cf. stàt for origin.
a stool, settle, Irish stól, Welsh ystôl; from Anglo-Saxon stól, now stool, Norse stóll, German stuhl. Hence vb. stòl, settle.
a wooden vessel for liquor, a stoup, Irish stópa, a "stoup" or wooden pail; from Scottish stoup, Middle English stope, now stoup, Dutch stoop, a gallon, Norse staup, a stoup.
stop, close up, Irish stopaim; from the English
a steep cliff, broken teeth; cf. stùrr, starr. Norse stór.
store, wealth, Irish stór, stórus; from Middle English sto@-r.
lop off, cut corn high:
hot steam, vapour; See toth.
a strumpet, Irish strabóid; from an early form of English strumpet, that is *stropet, from Old French strupe, concubinage, stupre, from Latin stuprum.

a stroke, ship or boat plank; from Scottish strake, English stroke; from Scottish straik, strait-edge for measuring corn, comes Gaelic stràc (do.). Similarly Gaelic stràc, mower's whetstone, is from strake; all are from the root of English stroke, strike.
troublesome fellow, gossip, wanderer; from Norse strákr, a vagabond, etc.
pride, swelling with anger, Irish stráic:
rattling, great noise, sparkles; root sprag, sparg, crackle, English spark, sparkle, Lithuanian sprageti, crackle.
carpet; from Latin strâgulum, coverlet.
a lazy, quarrelsome fellow, Irish strangair; cf. dreangan.
film, carpet (Carm.):
climb, strive against obstacles, Irish dreapaim; cf. dreimire.
a little liquor (Skye):  page 349
a row, line (Suth.); from English street.
strife, quarrel; from Latin strepitus.
strife, contention; from Norse stríð, Anglo-Saxon stríð, German streit.
a badger:
a streak, line, Irish stríoc; from English streak.
yield, Irish stríocaim, strìocail, (inf.), fall, be humbled, submit:
prodigal (Rob.):
a prostitute, Irish stríopach; from Old French strupe, concubinage, from Latin stuprum, dishonour, violation.

prodigality, Irish stró, strógh; seemingly (because of preserved st in all cases) borrowed from, rather than allied to, Middle English strawen, strew, Anglo-Saxon stréowian, Gothic straujan, Indo-European strou, stru. Hence Gaelic struidheas, prodigality, squandering.
(stroic, Arms.), tear asunder, a long rag, strip torn off, Irish stroicim, stróicim, sroic, a piece: *srakki-, from srac, confused with stródh?
mess (Glenmoriston):
wrinkled (H.S.D.):
prodigality; See stròdh.
a baton, cudgel, Irish sroghall, whip, rod, Old Irish sraigell; See sroghall.
a strumpet; from the English
ostrich, Irish struth; from Latin struthio, whence, through Old French ostruche (= avis struthio), English ostrich.
cake made on St. Michael's eve and eaten on his day (Carm.):

a wave, gable, pinnacle, scroll, Irish stuadh, gable, pinnacle, scroll, stuaidh-nimhe, rainbow, Middle Irish stuag-nime (do.), stuaid-léim, leap of the waves, Early Irish stúag, arch: *s-tuag, from Old Irish tuag, bow, belonging to the same root as tuagh, axe.

( M`A., Arms.), stuaichd ( H.S.D.), a little hill, round promontory, Irish stuaic: *s-tuag-c, from stuadh above. M`A. has the meaning "wry-neck" and sullen countenance, extreme boorishness", which is usually represented by stùic. Stokes gives the Celtic as *stoukki-, Breton stuchyaff, to feather, Lithuanian stúgti, set on high, English steep.
modesty, Irish stuaim, device, mien, modesty: *s-tuamm-, *tous-men, root tus, teus of tosd, silence.

a little hill jutting out from a greater, a horn, Irish stucán,a small conical hill, stucach, horned; from Teutonic - Norse stúka, wing of a building; Scottish, English stook, Middle English stouke, a shock of corn (12 sheaves), stooks, small horns, Low German stu@-ke (properly a projection), a bundle, bunch. But cf. stuaic.  page 350
a projecting crag, an angry or threatening aspect; from stùc above.
studious, steady, glum, Irish stuideurach, stuideur, a study.
incite, spur on dogs; from English stick.
huffiness, pride, Irish stuirteamhlachd (Con.); from Middle English sturte, impetuosity, sturten, impetuous, quarrelsome, Scottish sturt, vexation, anger, a side form of start.

vertigo, a disease in sheep caused by water in the head, drunkenness; from Scottish sturdy, from Old F. estourdi, dizzy-headed, now êtourdi, giddy-headed; from Latin extorpidire. From French comes English sturdy.
dust; from Scottish stour, Middle English stour, tumult.
the rugged point of a rock or hill, sturrach, rugged: *s-tùrr, from turr = tòrr, q.v.? Cf. Norse staurr.
stuff, metal; founded on the English stuff.
dress with starch, starch (vb. and n.); from Scottish stiffing, starch, English stiff. Perthshire has stifinn.
a sweeping blow (Suth. R.D.):

a pot (M`F.), earthen furnace (Arms.), a basket hung in the chimney containing wood to dry (Dial.), anything wrought together awkwardly, as clay (M`A.), Irish suachgan (Lh.), an earthen pot; from suath?
a bundle of straw or hay twisted together, a deformed person; See sùgan.

ensign, escutcheon, Irish suaitheantas, a streamer, standard, escutcheon, su-aichintus, ensigns, colours (K.Meyer), Old Irish suaichnid, clear, demonstratio, for su-aithne, "easily known", from aithne, knowledge.
small, inconsiderable (M`F.), Irish suaill, Early Irish suail, a trifle:
genial, secure, Irish suaimhneach, peaceful, gentle, peaceable: *su-menmnach? See meamna.
sleep, Irish suan, Early Irish, Old Irish súan, Welsh hun, Breton hun: *supno-s, developing into *sofno-, *sovno, *souno-; Indo-European root svop, svep, sleep; Latin sopor, sleep; Sanskrit svápnas.

twisting, rope-twisting anything, a line for twisting round anything, Early Irish, Old Irish súanem, g. suaneman, funis: *sognemon-, root sug, soug, Breton sug, trace, Welsh syg, chain, trace; Romance soga, rope, Italian soga, rope, leather band, Sp. soga, a linear measure, Port. soga, rush rope, Churw@"lwsch saga. Stokes finally refers súanem to a stem-root *sogno- beside segno- (whence Early Irish sén, a net for catching birds, gin, root segh, hold, English sail), Lithuanian segù, fasten, saga, sledge.  page 351  This divorces suaineadh from Gaelic suaicean and sùgan, q.v. Cf. Welsh hwynyn, hoenyn, a hair from a horse's tail, gin.
a faint resemblance; from Scottish swaup, swap, cast or lineaments of the countenance, Norse svipr, likeness, look, a swoop or flash.
exchange, swop; from the Scottish swap, English swop.
civil, meek, so Irish, Early Irish suarc(c); opposed to duairc: *su-arci-:
wagging (tails) (Suth.); from suath?
a hide, skin, fleece, coarse garment, "plough rein" (Suth.); cf. Irish sunach, a kind of plaid:
insignificant, careless, Irish suarach: *svogro-, root sveg, sug, German schwach, weak, siech, sick, English sick. Cf. English sour, German sauer, *sûra.

up, upwards, Irish suas, Old Irish súas: *s-uas, from uas, as in uasal, and the prefix s-, allied to the final s of Latin abs, ex, Greek @Ge@'/x, @Gprós, etc., and the initial s of Latin sub, super; possibly for *ens, Greek @Gei@'s, from en, and meaning "into", "to" (Rhys' Middle Pray.@+2 156).

rub, mix, knead, Irish suathaim, knead, mix, Middle Irish súathaim (do.), Early Irish suata, polished down, root sout, sut, mix; cf. English seethe, Norse sjóða, cook, seethe, Gothic suaths, a burnt offering.
supple; from the English

(suibheag or sui'eag, Dial.) a raspberry, subh, fruit generally (Arg.), Irish suibh, a strawberry, sughog, raspberry (Fol.), Old Irish subi, fragae, Welsh syfi, strawberry, Breton sivi; a side form to root su@g as in sùgh. Cf. Greek @Gu@`/fear, a kind of mistletoe.
merry, so Irish, Early Irish subach, Old Irish sube, joy; opposite of dubhach: *so-bv-io-, "well-being", from root bu, be (see bu, etc.).
virtue, Irish subhailce (súbhailc, Con.), Old Irish sualig, virtus, sualchi (pl.): *su-alich (Asc., Zim.@+1 54), root al of altram (Dr Cameron).
sake, account (M`A.):
(Dial. sid), yon, Irish súd, Early Irish sút, siut, illud, illic, Welsh hwnt (h-wnt), other, yonder, Breton hont; from the root of so; sud = s-út (Rhys). Also ud.
a seam between the planks of a ship; from Norse súð, a suture (only used for the clinching of a ship's boards), from sy/ja, sow, English sew, suture.
mirth, Irish súgadh, súgradh, Early Irish sucach:
suck, imbibe; from Scottish souk, sook, English suck, Anglo-Saxon súcan. See sùgh.  page 352
the reflection of rays of light from any moving luminous body from the roof or wall of a house:
a rope of twisted straw, Irish súgán, suagan, straw or hay rope, suag, a rope (O'R.): *souggo-, root soug of suaineadh, q.v. Hence suigean, a cirle of straw ropes in which grain is kept in a barn.

juice, sap, also (as vb.) drain, suck up, Irish súgh, súghaim, Early Irish súgim: *sûgô, suck, *sûgo-, juice; Latin sûgô, suck; Anglo-Saxon sûcan, English suck, soak. Welsh has sug, juice, sugno, suck. súg, súch, Welsh sug, from Latin sucus (Stokes).
a wave (A.M`D.), motion of the waves (H.S.D.); root sup, swing, Lithuanian sùpti, swing, Latin dissipo, scatter?
a gag for a calf; founded on sùg, Scottish sook.

sit, suidhe, a seat, sitting, Irish suidhim, Early Irish suidim, sudim, Old Irish suidigur, suide, a seat: *sodeiô, *sodio-n, root sed, sod, Welsh seddu, sedd, Breton azeza, sit; Latin sedeo; Greek @Ge@`/zomai, @Ge@`/dos, a seat; English sit, seat; Lithuanian se@?de@?ti; Sanskrit sádati, sa@-/dati, sit, set.

eye, Irish, Old Irish súil: *sûli-s, allied to *sâvali-s, sun, Welsh haul, heul, sun, Cornish heuul, Breton heaul; Latin sôl, sun; Greek @Gc@`lios, (= sa@-vélios), sun; Gothic sauil, sun; Lithuanian sáule (do.).
cheer, hospitality, geniality: *su-lubi-, root lubh, please, love, Latin libet, English love. It influences the meaning of suilbhir, originally "eloquent".
cheerful, so Irish, Middle Irish suilbir, Old Irish sulbir, eloquence, Early Welsh helabar, now hylafar, eloquence: from su- or so- and labhair, speak: "easy-spoken".
a sum, Irish suim, Welsh sum, Middle English summe; from Latin summa, sum, chief.
attention, respect, Irish suim; a metaphoric use of suim, sum (Dr Cameron).
a supper, Irish suipéir; from the English

a maid, nymph, Irish súire ( O'Cl.), a siren (suire, O'Br., Lh., etc., mermaids); from Latin siren, with leaning on suirghe, courtship? Teh word is doubtful Gaelic; H.S.D. finds only an Ossian Ballad to quote.
a courting, suiridheach (better suirtheach or suireach, M`A.), a wooer, so Irish, also surighim, I woo, Middle Irish suirge, wooing, suirgech, procus: *su-reg-, root reg, direct, etc.?
a flail, Irish suist(e), Middle Irish sust, suiste, Welsh ffust, Norse thust, sust, flail; from Latin fustis, club.

soot, Irish súithche, Middle Irish suithe, Old Irish suidi, fuligine, Welsh huddugl (cf. hudd, dark), Breton huzel (French suie): *sodio-, root sed, sit, settle; English soot, Anglo-Saxon sót, Norse sót. Doubtful.  page 353
the gannet; from Norse súla, súlan, the gannet, whence English solan-goose.
cheerful, affable; side-form of suilbhir?
fat, fatness, joy, Irish sult, Early Irish sult: *sultu-, root svel; Anglo-Saxon swellan, English swell; Latin salum, sea; Greek @Gsálos, tossing.
cloth below a pack-saddle; ultimately from Late Latin sauma, pack-saddle, whence French sommier, mattress, English sumpter.
give the due number (as of cattle for pasture); from Scottish soum.
a billow, Irish sumaid ( O'R. and M`L., sùmaid); seemingly from English summit. The Gaelic also means "external senses" (H.S.D.).
summon, a summons; from the English
a surge, billow; See sumaid.
the drone of a bagpipe:
close-packed, tidy; opposite of dòmhail, q.v.
lovage - a plant, Irish sunais; also siunas:

good humour, cheerfulness, Irish sonntach, merry ( O'Cl., O'Br.), sonnda, bold, súntaidh, active, Early Irish suntich, ( O'Cl., O'Br.), sonnda, bold, súntaidh, active, Early Irish suntich, spirited: *sondeto-, English sound?
an easy-chair of twisted straw:
supple (M`A.); from the English

alacrity, cheerfulness; cf. Welsh chwardd, laughter, Cornish wherzin, ridere; root sver, sing, speak; English swear, Latin susurrus, whisper, etc. Middle Irish sord, bright (*surdo-), is referred by Stokes to the same origin as Latin serenus.
vent of a kiln; cf. sòrn.
a sound sleep; surram, snoring noise as of one asleep:
substance, Irish substaint; from Latin substantia.
a bustling, pother, affected shyness:

anything (Dial.), Irish, Early Irish suth, weather; root su, produce, Early Irish suth, milk; Greek @Gu@`/ei, it rains; as in sùgh, q.v. Further allied is root su, beget, Old Irish suth, offspring, English sun.
eternal, Irish suthain, Old Irish suthain, suthin; from su, so- and tan, time, q.v.; sú-tan-ìs (Stokes see). T

is, Irish tá, Early Irish tá, is, táim, I am, Old Irish táu, tó, sum, tá, táa, est, especially attáa (at the beginning of a sentence), est (= ad-tât, Latin adsto) and itá, itáa, "in which is": *tâjô, *tâjet, root stâ, stand; Latin stô, stat, stand, French été, having been; Church Slavonic stoja@?, I stand; further English stand, Greek @Gi@`/stcmi (for @Gsí-sta@-mi), set, Latin sisto. See seas further.  page 354
fight, brawl; Breton has tabut of like force; See sabaid. Cf. Scottish debate.
a tabor, Irish tabár; from the English
the sea, ocean; from Norse haf, Swed. haf, Danish hav, the open sea, Anglo-Saxon haef. From Norse also comes the Scottish (Shet.) haaf, open sea.
a spoon-net; from Norse háfr, a pock-net.
a sudden eruption, a forcing, a pull, Irish tabhach, sudden eruption, compulsion, tobhachaim, I compel, Early Irish tobach, levying, distraint, from dobongaim: for root See buain.
substantiality, effectiveness, Irish tábhachd, Middle Irish tabhuchta (Meyer):
give, so Irish, Early Irish tabraim, Old Irish tabur, do, post-particle form of dobiur, now Gaelic bheir, q.v.: inf. tabhairt, so Irish See thoir.
a sling, Irish tabhall, Early Irish taball, Welsh rafl, a cast, taflu, jacere, Cornish toula, Breton taol, a cast, blow: *taballo-, root tab, to fire, sling; cf. English stab.
an inn, tavern, Irish tabhairne; from Latin taberna, English tavern.
noisy (Suth.):
barking, Irish tathfan: *to-sven-, root sven, sound ( See seinn).
tedious nonsense:
a lease, tack; from Scottish tack.
a tack, tacket, Irish taca; from the English
a while, short time; from tac.
(tàcar, H.S.D.), provision, plenty, support, Irish tacar, a collection, gleaning, contrivance. Cf. Norse taka, income.
meet, happen, Manx taghyrt, to happen, an accident, Irish tachair, he arrived at; from to- and car, turn.
a ghost, yelling of a ghost, an orphan, Irish tacharán:
itching, scratching, Irish tochas:

choke, Irish tachdaim, Old Irish tachtad, angens. Stokes gives the root as tak and refers to it also Welsh tagu (and ystagu), choke, Cornish, Breton taga. Brugmann and Ascoli analyse tachd into to-acht, root angh, Latin ango, choke, Greek @Ga@'ghw, English anger. Root tak as in Latin tacere (Prellwitz).
winding yarn, Irish tocharais, tochardadh, Middle Irish tochartagh: *to-cert-, root qert, wind, as in ceirtle.
(Dial.), support, substance; cf. taic.
a ledge, layer; cf. spadh.

frequenting, visiting, Irish tadhall, Old Irish tadal, dat. tadíll, inf. of taidlim, doaidlibem, visitabimus, adall, diverticulum:  page 355  *to-ad-ell, form *elnô (Stokes), go, Middle Welsh elwyfi, iero, Cornish yllyf, eam, root ela, Latin ambulare, walk, Greek @Ge@'laúnw, drive, proceed; likely also French aller, go.
goal, hail; from English hail.
plead, Irish tagair (imper.), tagraim, Early Irish tacraim, Old Irish tacre, argumentum: *to-ad-gar-, root gar, as in goir, agair.
choose, Irish toghaim, Old Irish togu, eligo, electio: *to-gusô, root gus, choose, taste; Latin gusto, taste; Greek @Ggeúw, taste; English choose.
noise, echo, a mode of divination by listening to the noise of water cascades, Irish toghairm, summons, petition, Old Irish togairm, invocatio; from to- and gairm.
the marten:
ghost ( Suth. R.D.):

an apparition, ghost, Irish taibhse, vision, ghost, Middle Irish tadhbais, phantasma, Old Irish taidbse, demonstratio, tadbat, demonstrat, *tad-bat or *to-ad-bat, root bat, show, see, speak, Indo-European bhâ, bhan as in bàn, q.v. Greek @Gfántasma, English phantasm, and phantom are closely allied to the Gaelic
a taunt; See teabaid.
propriety of speech: "precision", Early Irish tepe, cutting; See teabaid.

support, proximity, Irish taca, prop, surety, fastening, toice, prop, wealth, tacamhuil, firm, aice, support, food, near, Middle Irish aicc, a bond, Early Irish aicce, relationship: *akki-, *pakki-, root pak, bind; Latin paciscor, agree, pax, peace; English fang, Gothic fahan, seize: Zend paç, bind. The root is a triplet -- pak, pag, pagh (Greek @Gpc/gnumi, make fast, Latin pango, English page, etc.). Zimmer refers Early Irish aicce to the root of agus, aig.

attention, heed, Irish uidh, Old Irish oid, óid, con-ói, servat: *audi-, root av, watch, Latin aveo, desire, audeo, dare, Sanskrit av, favour (see àill further). The t of Gaelic is due to the phrase "Thoir taidhe" (= thoir do aidhe) - Take thy heed: a phrase to which the word is practically restricted, and which accounts for the short vowel of the Gaelic and Irish, the sentence accent being on the verb.
meaning, import; See oidheam.
a bow-string:
attachment, custom; cf. aig, at.
haggis; from Scottish haggis, Old French hachis, English hash, from hack.
chattels (Heb.); a side form of teaghlach.

substance, wages, taileas, wages, Irish táille, wages, Middle Irish taile, salarium, Welsh tâl, payment, Cornish, Old Breton tal, solvit, root  page 356  tal, tel, take, hold; Greek @Gtálanton, a talent, English talent, @Gtelos, toll; Latin tollo, lift, English thole, etc.
strength, Irish talcánta, strong, Early Irish talce, tailce: *t-alkiâ, root alk, strong, Greek @Ga@'lkc/, strength, @Ga@'léxw, defend.
contempt; cf. tarcuis.

backgammon, chess, Irish táibhleis, backgammon table, back-gammon, Middle Irish taiflis, draught-board, tables, Welsh tawl-fwrdd, draught-board; from Middle English tables, backgammon, from table, Norse tafl, game, chess.
halberd; from the English The Irish, Middle Irish is halabard, which Stokes regards as derived from the French hallebard.
wages; See tail.
prophecy; for tairgneachd, q.v.
apprentice fee, premium (M`A., who has tàilleabh); See tail.
(M`A.), consequence, air tàille, on account of; cf. Middle Irish a haithle, after, as a haithle sin, thereafter, Old Gaelic as á áthle, thereafter (Book of Deer), aithle, remnant.
a tailor, Irish tailiur, Welsh teiliwr; from the English, Middle English tailor, taylor, from French tailleur.
a tool, sling, noose, Irish tailmh, a sling, Early Irish tailm (do.), Welsh telm, laqueus, Breton talm, sling: *talksmi (Stokes); Church Slavonic tlu@uka@?, strike.
bustle, noise; for *tairmrith, Early Irish tairmrith, transcursus, from tairm-, cross, trans (see thar), and ruith, run.
a bundle, bunch ( Sh., O'R.):
death, mortality, Irish táimh, Early Irish tám, plague: *tâmo-, death; cf. Sanskrit támyati, choke, Church Slavonic tomiti, vexare. Cf., however, tàmh, rest.
traduce (Carm.):
cattle, drove, Irish táin, cattle, spoil, Early Irish táin: *to-ag-ni, root ag, drive, Latin ago, etc.
thanks; from the English thank.
thaw (Arran), Manx tennue, Irish tionadh, Old Irish tinaid, evanescit, root ten as in tana. See aiteamh.
a mass, Irish taip; See tap.
contempt, Irish táir, Early Irish tár; for *to-shár; See sàr.
get, obtain, come, Irish tair, come thou, Early Irish tair (do.), tair, venies; from tairicim, I arrive at, come, catch, for *to-air-ic, root ic of thig, q.v.
an isthmus, peninsula: *tar-bertâ, from tar (see thar, cross) and ber of beir: "cross-bringing, portage".
profit, so Irish, Old Irish torbe: *to-for-be, where -be comes from *bv-iâ, root bu, be (see bu).  page 357
profitable, so Irish, Early Irish tairbert, yielding, giving up: *to-air-ber-, from the berb beir, bring.
surfeit, bloody flux (Carm.):

offer, tairgse, an offer, Irish tairgim, tairgsin, Early Irish tairgim, tharscin (dat.): *to-air-ges-, root ges, carry (Latin gero, as in agus? Ascoli compares Old Irish taircim, affero, tairciud, oblatio, tribuere, from to-ad-ro-ic, root ic of thig.
prophecy, Irish tairrgire, tairgire, prophecy, promise, Old Irish tairngire, promissio: *to-air-ind-gar-iâ, root gar as in goir.
a saw; See tuireasg.
the dairymaid's cry to calm a cow: cf. Old Irish tairissim, sto, *to-air-sess, from sess as in seas, q.v.
kind, loving, Irish tairis, loyal, Early Irish tairisse, true, loyal: "stable", from to-air-sess, from sess, stop, stand, as in seas, q.v.
peat-spade; See toirsgian.
cupboard or aumrie (Perth): Scottish tirless, lattice, wicket, French trellis.
necromancy (Sh., Old R.); See taghairm.
thunder, Irish tóirneach, tóirn; See torrunn for root, etc.
a nail, Irish, Early Irish tairnge; from tarruing?

soft, Irish tais, Early Irish taise, tasse, weakness: *taxi-, soft (Gaulish Taxi-magulus?), root tak, weak, melting, Greek @Gtakerós (do.), @Gtc/kw, melt; further Latin tabes, English thaw. Bezzenberger suggests Greek @Gtágcnon, a melting pot, saucepan.

reveal, Irish taisbeanaim, Early Irish taispenim, taissfenim, Old Irish asfenimm, testificor, doairfenus, exploravi; the old Gaelic root is fen, ben, which may be cognate to Greek @Gfaínw (see taibhse). Zeuss regarded the s as put before the b by metathesis, the word being of the same origin as taibhse.
a journey, taisdil (Cars.), journey (v.imp.) Irish taisdiol: *to-asdel, *ad-sod-, root sod-, as in astar.
(M`E.), saints' relics, Early Irish taisse:

deposit, store away, tasgaidh, depository, Irish taisgim, Early Irish taiscim, doroisecht-sa, id deposui: *to-ad-sec-, root seq, follow, beside, as in seach, past; the idea of the verb being "put past". (Ernault Zeit. Celt.@+2 384. segh).

finding of anything, taisgealach, a spy, Irish taiscealladh, spying, betraying, Middle Irish taiscelad, Old Irish taiscelaid, explorator, pl. taisceltai, do-scéulaim, experior; from to-scél-, from sgeul, story (Windisch). Hence taisgealadh, news.
a repartee, Irish taitheasg, aitheasg (O'Br., etc.), Old Irish taithesc, answer, aithesc, admonitio, Welsh ateb, a reply: *ati-seq, root seq, say, as in sgeul.  page 358

pleasing, Irish taithneamhach, Middle Irish taitnemach, bright, shining, Early Irish taitnim, I shine, taitnemach, shining, Old Irish taitnem, lucina, light: *taith-tennim, to-aith-tenn, root ten of teine, fire (Windisch). Stokes (Bez.Beit.@+18, 112), divides taitnem into tait- and nem, Pictish namet, albus.

adze, Irish, Old Irish tál: *to-aglo- (rather t-aglo-?), Gothic aqisi, axe, English axe (Strachan). Stokes gives a pre-Gaelic *tâkslo, root tek, Church Slavonic tesla, axe, Latin gelum (= tex-lum), weapon, Greek @Gtéktwn, carpenter; but tek does not appear to have a side form tâk, and tâkslo- would produce táll (tôkslo, Foy). But cf. Latin pâla, spade, for root, and for phonetics Gaelic torc and Latin porcus.
complaining, Irish talach, dispraise, reproach:
enticing, hushing, caressing; from Norse tál, allurement, bait, trap, Anglo-Saxon tál, calumny, root dâl, del, Latin dolus, guile, @Gdcléomai, hurt (Dor. da@-léomai).
a partition or dividing wall; from Scottish halland, hallon. Dial. Gaelic has also tallaid.

earth, so Irish, Old Irish talam, g. talman: *talmon-, for tl@.-mon, root tel; Latin tellus, earth (for te@-lo@-/s), *têl, flat; Greek @Gtclía, a board; Anglo-Saxon thelu, board (root te@-l); Sanskrit talas, level ground; Church Slavonic ti@ulo, pavement (root tl@.). Stokes joins here Celtic talo-s, brow, Gaulish Dubno-talos, Argio-talos (Pictish Talorgan), Welsh tâl, brow, Cornish tâl, Breton tal.
feats of arms, chivalry, Irish talan ( O'Br., Sh., etc.); See tàlann for origin.
a talent, Irish tallann, Old Irish talland; from Latin talentum, English talent.
a hoe; from tàl and fonn.
a hall, Irish alla, Middle Irish all; from Norse hall, höll, English hall: allied to Gaelic ceall, q.v.
honour (Carm.):

an insult, offence, Irish támailt, Breton tamall, reproach, root stemb, abuse, Indo-European sten@go, stamp, Greek @Gstémbw, shake, misuse, abuse, @Gstóbew, scold, English stamp (Stokes, Jubainville Rev.Celt. @+16, 365).
rest, Irish támh, Early Irish tám: *tâmo-, root stâm, sta, stand, English stand, station, stamina; See seas. Usually tàmh, rest, and tàimh, death, are referred to the same root.
blockhead, brownie; See amhas. For termination, cf. ùruisg, tannasg.
a gulping movement (M`D.):
a while, space of time, Irish tamall: *to-ad-melno-, from melno-, linger, Greek @Gméllw, linger (Stokes). See mall.  page 359
time, an tan, when, Irish tan, an tan, Old Irish tan, intain, intan, quum, quando: *tanâ, time; Sanskrit tan, duration, tanâ, continually. root tan, ten, extend, as in tana, q.v.

thin, Irish, Old Irish tana, Cornish tanow, Breton tanaw, but Welsh teneu: *tanavo-, thin; Latin tenuis, thin, tendo, stretch; Greek @Gtanaós @Gtanu-, long, stretched, @Gteínw, stretch; English thin, German dünn; Church Slavonic ti@unu@uku@u; Sanskrit tanú.

next heir, tanist, anything second, Irish tánaiste, lieutenant, second in command, heir apparent, Old Irish tánaise, secundus, imthanu, alternation, innimthána, talionem: *to-atn-, root at of ath, "re", Sanskrit at, also *at-s-men, of àm, time, q.v. (Strachan). Rhys (Celt.Breton@+2, 308) suggests connection with Welsh tan, till, Latin tenus, root ten (no root tân?).
a tankard, Irish tancárd; from English
an apparition, ghost; from the root of tana?

a side, Irish taobh, Early Irish tóeb, táib, Old Irish tóib, Welsh, Cornish, Breton tu: *toibos, root steibh, sti, stiff, standing; Latin tîbia, shin-bone (pl.); Lithuanian staibis, post, shin-bone (pl.), staibus, strong; Greek @Gstifós, strong; further English stiff, Latin stipes, log.
a halter, cable, hair-rope, Irish téad, a rope; See teud.
an apostate, Irish taodhaire ( Lh., O'Br.):
frequenting; See tadhal.
the grave:
a fit of passion ( Sh., O'R.):

dough, Irish taos, Early Irish toes, Old Irish táis, massam, Welsh toes, Breton taos: *taisto-, *stejesto-, root staj, concrescere; Greek @Gstaís (g. @Gstaitós), dough, @Gstéar (g. stéa@-tos for *sta@-jatos, *sta@-jn@.tos); Latin stîria, a drop.
oversman, tutor (Sutherland, etc.); from Latin tutor, English tutor. See saoitear.

pour out, empty (vb.), a jet, torrent (n.), taoim, bilge-water, Irish taomaim (taodhmaim), taodhm (n.), Early Irish tóem, a jet, taeim, sentina, Old Irish tuismiud, delivery, *to-fo-ess-sem: *to-ad-sm-men, root sem, let go, from sê, Lithuanian semiù, draw (as water), Latin simpulum, ladle (Stokes). Cf. Old Irish teissmim, I pour out (= to-ess-sem-im). Borrowing from Norse tómr, empty, English toom, is not to be thought of.
a fit of rage, Irish taom ( O'Br., etc.), Middle Irish taem:
a pour, rush, exact full of a liquid measure, Irish taosgaim, I drain, pour out, Early Irish tóesca, spilling, taescaire, a baler, pumper: *to-ad-sem-sko-, root sem as in taom?
horseplay (R.D.):
tow or wool on the distaff, forelock, "busk a hook", (Arg.), Irish tap, tapán; from Middle English top, tuft of hair or flax, top, Scottish tap.  page 360
clever, active, so Irish, Early Irish tapad, suddenness, alertness, top, sudden; from the same root as obann (Stokes).
tattooo (R.D.).
a wallet, repository, Irish taplaigh; for tap-lach, from tap, tow, etc.
augur, so Irish; for tarathar. See tora.
truncheon or staff of authority (Hend.):
the ghost of an unbaptised infant ( Sh., O'R.); for tacharan?

a bull, Irish tarbh, Early Irish tarbh, Welsh tarw, Cornish tarow, Breton taro, tarv, Gaulish tarvos: *tarvos; Latin taurus; Greek @Ggau@nros (= @Gtárfos); Prussian tauris, buffalo, Church Slavonic turu@u, auroch. Prellwitz thinks the Celtic not allied to Greek @Gtau@nros, etc., which he refers to the root tau, tu (stû gives English steer).
also talcuis, contempt. Irish, Middle Irish tarcuisne, Early Irish tarcusul:
ruling, governing, assembly (Lh., etc.), Irish targadh:
a target, Irish targáid; from English
foretell, Irish tairrghirim; See tairgneachd.
it happened; See thàrladh.
a slave, thrall; from English varlet?

producing, originating, source, dwelling, Irish tórmach, an increasing, a growing ripe for bearing, magnifying, Old Irish tórmach, an increase: *to-for-mach, root mag, power (English may, might, etc.).
a ptarmigan, Irish tarmochan; English ptarmigan is hence (Skeat). Also tarman, from tarm, murmur (Carm.):
white butterfly (Carm.):
dislike of food: *to-air-meas; See meas.
thunder-clap; See tàirneanach.
inn-keeper; from Late Latin tabernator, tavern-keeper, Latin taberna, English tabern.
a clod, lump (Sh., O'Br., etc.), Irish tarp, tarpán; from Norse torf, a turf, sod, English turf.

lower part of the belly, tail, breast, Irish tárr, belly, lower part of the belly, Early Irish tarr, Welsh tor, Breton tor, Old Breton tar: *tarsâ, tarmsâ; Scottish thairm, belly, gut, English tharm, German darm, bowels; Greek @Gtrámis, tail, entrail, hip joint. Stokes gives the Celtic *targsâ, allied to Latin terbus, back.
a nail; See tàirng.
pull, draw, so Irish, Early Irish tairrngim: *to-air-rengim, from Early Irish ringim, hang, tear, from reng, a nasalised form of reg, stretch (see ruighe).
also tèarraid, sheriff officer, tipstaff (Dial.); See earraid.  page 361
transverse, across, Irish tarsna, tarsa, trasna, Middle Irish, Early Irish tarsnu, across; from tar, across (see thar), and sainn of ursainn, q.v.

thirst, Irish, Old Irish tart: *tar(s)to-; English thurst, German durst, Greek @Gtérsomai, become dry; Latin torreo, burn, tostum (*torstum), English toast; Sanskrit tarsh, thirst, Zend taresh; Indo-European ters, dry.
tartan; from English, Scottish tartan, from French tiretain, linsie-wolsie.
noise; reduplication of root tar, tor in tòirneanach.
tedious discourse or scolding, Irish tasanach, tedious, slow (Lh. marks it obsolete and queries meaning):

a shilling; from Scottish testan, testoon, a silver coin of the 16th century with Mary's head (teste) on it, the "inglis testane" being worth 8 shillings Scots, English tester, worth 6d; originally so called from the coins of Louse XII. (1500) with his head (teste, French tête, head) on them.
depository, a treasure: "A thasgaidh" - Thou treasure; See taisg.
attract, attach one to oneself, tadadh (inf.), taiteadh (Perth), tame: *tad-dam, root dam of aidich.
cement, join (M`F., Lh.), Irish táthaim, táth, solder or glue, Welsh todi, construc, join: *táto-, *stâto-, constitute, root sta, stand?

visit, frequent, tendency to vomit (Hend.) Irish tathuighim, Middle Irish aithigim; formed form the prep. aith, back, rather than a compound of tiagaim as in imthich, our imich (that is, *ati-tig-, go back again). Stokes prefers root at, go, formerly discussed under tànaiste.
barking; See tabhann.

a woman, femal, she, Irish an tí, she who, an té, he who (O'Donovan says either means "he or she who" or "person who"), Old Irish intí is(qui), indí ea(quae), aní id(quod): the article and the enclitic particle -í, for which See nì, and cf. tì, he who.
insipid, slightly fermented; from root of teas; cf. tepid.

a taunt, repartee (Dial.), teab, a flippant person's mout (M`A.), teibidh, smart: "cutting", Early Irish tepe (to-aith-be, Stokes), a cutting, Old Irish taipe, concisio, brevitas: *tad-be (= to-ad-be), reduced root be, cut, imdibe, circumcisio, etc., root bi, bin, as in bean, touch, q.v.

a house, Irish teach, Old Irish tech, teg, g. tige, Welsh ty, Cornish ti, Old Breton teg, tig, ti, now ti: *tegos, g. teges-os; Greek @Gtégos, roof, @Gstégw, cover; Latin tego, cover, tectum, house; English thatch,  page 362  German dach; Lithuanian stë/giu, cover; Sanskrit sthagati, cover. See tigh for usual nom. case.

coming, arrival, Irish teachd, Old Irish techt, aditus, itio, Welsh taith, iter, Breton tiz, diligence, haste: *tiktâ, root stig, teig, as in tighinn, q.v. Some derive it from thig or tig, q.v. Hence teachdaire, messenger.

legal, lawful, Middle Irish teachta, téchta, Old Irish téchte, fitting, legalis, lex: *tenctio-, root, tenq, become, chance, produce, English thing, Lithuanian tenkù, chance, befaull, Latin tempus. Dial. form deic, cha deic, q.v.
silly boasting (Arg.).
slow, dilatory:
a tether; from Scottish, English tether, tedder, Norse tjóðr, tjor, Swedish tjuder.
collect, provide, shelter, Irish teagar, provision, shelter, teagarach, warm, snug, teagairim, store, provide; cf. eagar.
doubt, suspense; See theagamh.
teaching, so Irish, Early Irish tecosc: *to-aith-cosc-, for which See caisg.

family, household, so Irish, Old Irish teglach, Welsh teulu, Old Welsh telu, Cornish teilu, familia: *tego-slougo-, from the stems of tigh and sluagh. The terminations -lach from *slougo-s makes abstract collective nouns, which are used for single objects or persons; as òglach, young man, really "youth", or "young-people", just as "youth" is also used in English as a concrete noun - "a youth".
hearth, forge, Irish teallach, Early Irish tenlach, tellach: *tene-lach, from teine, fire, and terminal -lach (see teaghlach).
a lust or bunchu woman (M`F.):
pleasant, Irish teamhair, pleasant, Tara, Early Irish temair, delightful, omnis locus conspicuus: *stem-ri-?
time (Suth.): Latin?
slight swoon or stun, Irish teimheal, darkness, Old Irish temel (do.), Sanskrit támas, Lithuanian tamsa, Latin tenebrae, temere, rashly.
temple, church, Irish teampoll, Old Irish tempul, Welsh teml, Cornish tempel; from Latin templum.
deliverance, succour, teanacas, healing: *tind-ioc, from ìoc, heal.
pincers, smith's thongs, Irish teanchoir, tongs, pincers, Old Irish tenchor, forceps: *ten-cor, "fire-putter", from the stem of teine, fire, and cor, seen in cuir, put.

a tongue, Irish teanga, Old Irish tenge, gen. tengad: *tengot-, from sten@gh, sting (English sting, German stengal, stalk),  page 363  which is from zdn@.@gh, from dn@.@gh, whence Latin dingua, English tongue? Stokes (Academy, Oct 1891) has compared Latin tango (so Windisch, Scot.Celt.Rev., 34). Rhys has considered the probabilities of alliance with Welsh tafod, Cornish tavot, Breton toed, older teaut (*tebâto-) in Manx Pray.@+2, 136-7.

tight, tense, near to, Irish teann, Old Irish tend, Welsh tyn, tight, stretched: *tendo-; Latin tendo, I stretch, tentus, stretched (Stokes, Rev.Celt.@+13, 12f); in any case from root ten of tana. Foy gives sten; Norse stinnr, rough, hard. Cf. Greek @Gstenós.
separate, Irish tearbadh (O'Cl.), severance, Middle Irish terpúd, Early Irish terbaim, terbud: *ter-be-, Gadelic reduced root be, cut, for which See teabaid?
scarce, rare, Irish tearc, Early Irish terc: *ter(s)qo-s, rare, root ters, dry (as in tart); Latin tesqua (= tersquo-s), deserts.
