a sanctuary, protection, so Irish, Middle Irish termain, termonn, Welsh terfyn; from Latin termo(n), terminus, end, "end of race for life by reaching church lands" or Termon landes (Ducange).
tar, Irish tearr; from Middle English terve, Norse tjara.
save, escape, tèarnadh (inf.), Irish tearnaim, Early Irish térnaim, ternam, an escape, érnaim, I escape: *es-rn-, root r@.n, English run?

heat, Irish teas, Old Irish tess, g. tesa, Welsh, Cornish tes, Breton tez: *testu-, for *tepstu-, root tep, burn, heat; Latin tepeo, be warm, English tepid; Church Slavonic teplo, hotly; Sanskrit tap, be hot, Zend tap, burn. See, also from tep, teine, teth. Hence teasach, fever.
save, deliver, Irish teasargaim, Old Irish tessurc, servo, dumesurcsa, defendo me: *to-ess-arc, root ark, defend: Latin arceo, ward off; Greek @Ga@'rkéw (do.). See adharc.
die, Irish teasdaighim, die, fail, Middle Irish, Old Irish testa, deest, fails; *to-ess-tá, from tá, I am. Cf., for force, Latin desum.
I preserve, help (Carm.):
cut, cut off, Irish teasgaim, Early Irish tescaim: *to-ess-sc, root sec, cut, Latin seco, English saw.
irresolute: "halting, failing"; cf. Irish tebim, disappoint, fail, for which See theab.

flee, Irish teithim, Early Irish techim, Old Irish teichthech, vitabundus, Welsh techu, skulk, Middle Breton techet, flee: *tekô, *tekkô, flee, Indo-European root teq-, flow, run; Church Slavonic teku, a run, Lithuanian tekù, flow; Sanskrit taki, runs, Zend taka-, course.
wild, fierce ( H.S.D.), wild fire ( M`A.):
a fishing line: "a cast", from tilg, cast, Irish teilgean, casting?
msical instrument, teilig, a chord (Carm.), Welsh telu or telyn, harp. Cf. seillean.
a blub-cheeked fellow (Dial.); cf. meilleach.  page 364

fire, Irish teine, Old Irish tene, g. tened, pl. tenti, Welsh tân, Cornish, Breton tan (in proper names also tanet): *tenet-, *tenos, Celtic root te, from tep, hot, as in teas, q.v. Not for *te(p)ne-, as usually said, which would give téine now, nor *tepsne-, which would produce tenne now; teine-sionnachain, phosphorescence, teine-fionn, will o' the wisp (Suth.).
calamity, strait; an abstract nounn from teann.

fail, be spent, die, teireachduinn (inf.), Irish teiricim (O'Br.), Early Irish tarnic, it ended, from *tar-ic, transire (tar, across, and ic or nic of thig, thanig). Atkinson joins it with tairicim, arrive (= to-air-ic-), as in tàir, but the meanings scarcely suit.
hake, herring hake (Carm.):

descend, Irish tearnaim, túrnaim, Early Irish tairnim, Old Irish tairnnud, dejectio (= to-air-innud), from *endô, go, root end, ed, Indo-European ped, go (English foot, Latin pes, etc., Gaelic uidhe, q.v.).
the dairymaid's cry to calm a cow; See tairis.
a term, Irish tearma, earlier, térma (Four Masters); from Middle English terme, from Latin terminus through French
a mistake, mischance; cf. eirmis. Here te may be for de, on the analogy of to, do.
a musical air; See séist for derivation.
last will and testament; from Latin testamentum.
the exact or very middle; teis = to-ess, as in teasairg.
testimony, Irish teisd, teist, Old Irish teist, Welsh tyst, Breton test; from Latin testis, English test, etc.
make warm; from teò-, q.v. The Irish verb is teighim, inf. téaghadh.

warm, teò-chridheach, warm-hearted; *tepu-, Sanskrit tapus, hot, root tep as in teth. Cf. Keating's (Three Shafts, 282), teó-ghrádhuigheas, qui ardentius amat, where Atkinson considers teó a comparative.
a doel (Carm.):
skilful, expert, teòm, cunning (Carm.):

hot, Irish teith, comp. teotha (Gaelic and Irish), Middle Irish te, comp. teou: *teps (?), root tep, hot, as in teas. The Old Irish is tee, té, fervidus, pl. téit, from *tepents, g. *tepentos, Latin tepens.

congeal, be parched, Irish teuchdaim, curdle, coagulate, Middle Irish téchtaige, frozen, Old Irish coiteichtea, concretionis: *tenkto-, from Indo-European tenq, firm, fast; English tight, German dicht, close.
a string, Irish teud, téad, Old Irish tét, fidis, Welsh tant: tn@.tâ, chord; Sanskrit tântu, tánti, cord: root ten, stretch, thin, as in tana.
battle, contest, disease, Irish teagmháil, a meeting, retribution: *to-ex-com-dháil, See còmhdhail. In the sense of "disease", See eucail.  page 365

a bite, sudden snatch, wound, Early Irish temm, Welsh tam, a bite Cornish tam, pl. tymmyn, Breton tamm: *tendmen, root tend, cut; Latin tondeo, shear, tineo, a worm; Greek @Gténdw, gnaw; Church Slavonic te@?ti, caedere.
is; See tà. The aspiration is due to the use of tà in relative sentences, where the t is intervocalic.

came, Irish thánaic, tháinig, ve@-nit, Old Irish tánic, ránic, ve@-nit, tânac, ve@-ni: *ananka, I have come - a reduplicated perfect; Sanskrit ânamca, has reached; Greek @Gc@'/negke, brought: root enk, nak (nank), attain, bring, for which See thig. The aspiration is due to the analogy of other perfects which follow do.
over, across, Irish tairis, Early Irish tairis, over it, him; from tar ( thar) and sé or é, he, it. The aspiration is, due to a suppressed, or supposed suppressed, do or a.

over, beyond, Irish thall, Old Irish thall, tall: *t-all, Old Irish ol, quam, indoll, altarach, ultra, al, ultra; root ol, el, ol, Latin ille (= olle), alius. Also eile, other, which see. The form thallad stands for thall-ud.
come, come along, "age", thallaibh (pl.), Early Irish tallaim, take away, *talnô, root tel, bear (see tlàth, tail, etc.). Also interjection: thalla! thalla! well! well!
across, Irish tar, Old Irish tar, dar, Welsh tra-, over, trach, beyond, root ter, through, past, Latin trans, terminus; Sanskrit tar-, pass; Indo-European ter, pass through, bore. See tora, troimh.
accidit, Irish tarla, Early Irish dorala, dorla, Old Irish tarla: *to-ro-la, the la being the remains of root plu, as in dol (Ascoli).
nearly did (with inf.), Irish do theib sé, he failed (O'Br.): "grazed" it, from *tebb, graze, cut, as in teabaid?

mayhap, perhaps, Old Irish tecmaing, accidit, tecmang, eventus, do-é-cm-aingim, accido, for *to-ex-com-ang, root ang, near, as in cumhang, q.v. Meyer takes Old Irish ecmaing from ad-com-bangim, bang root of buain. It has also been referred to root mang, mag, English may, etc.
will go, Irish téid, goes, Old Irish téit, venit, it: *to-éit, *entô, *pentô, go, reach, root pet, pent, go, fly, fall; Latin pet, seek, "fall on"; Greek @Gpíptw, fall; Gothic finþan, English find.
will say; See deir.

will come, Irish tigim, come, Early Irish tic, ticc, venit, Old Irish ticfa, veniet: *tó-icc, from icc, *enkô, come, reach, root enk, nak, nank, attain, bring; Greek @Gc@'/negka, brought (= Gaelic thàinig), a reduplicated perf. from @Gegk; Sanskrit a@-namça, attained; further nank of adhlac and Latin nanciscor.  page 366
give, Gaelic, Irish tabhair, give thou, q.v. The Gaelic is for toir, a crushed form of tabhair, and this is aspirated on the analogy of bheir, gheibh, and especially of thug, its past tense.
an interjection of dislike or impatience: Scottish hoot, hoot-hoot, Swed. hut, whence English hoot. The Gaelic is borrowed.

bave, brought, Irish thug, thugas (1st pers.), Early Irish tuc, tucas, do-fuc, from uc, ucc, *ud-ge, from s- aorist *e-ges-s-t, *e-ges-s-m, root ges, carry, Latin gero, gessi (Zimmer, Zeit.@+30 156-7); whence also Welsh dug, he bore, Cornish duk, Breton dougas.
to thee, to you, to him; for chugad, etc., q.v. Similarly thun is for chun, gun, gu, q.v thun with gen. is for chum.
any one, person, Irish tí, person, an tí, an té; See té, nì.
intention, Irish, Early Irish tí; ar ti = intends (Glenmassan MS.):
perverse, ill-disposed, sick, a dwarf, Irish tiachair, perverse ( O'Cl., Lh., O'Br.), Middle Irish tiachair, troublesome, Early Irish tiachaire, affliction, peevishness:
a little hill, small stone, Irish tíadhan, a stone, testicle:
gloomy, lonesome, Irish tiamdha, dark (O'Cl.), Early Irish tiamda, dark, afraid:
prudent; cf. tìorail.
fountains (Uist; Hend.); See ++tiobart.
time; from Icel. tíð, Scottish, English tide, Anglo-Saxon tíd, German zeit.
(for taigh), a house, Irish tigh, Old Irish teg, tech; See teach.
lord, master, Irish tighearna, Old Irish tigerne, Welsh teyrn, Old Welsh -tigern, Cornish teern, Old British tigernus: *tegerno-s, tegernio-s, root teg of tigh, q.v.
call when passing (M`A.); the t being as in tigh, the word seems a variant of tadhal.

coming, Irish tighim, I come, Early Irish tiagaim, Old Irish tiagu, tíchtu (tíchtin), adventus: *tigô, *teigô, from root stei@gh, sti@gh, go; Greek @Gsteíhw, walk; Gothic steigan, ascend, German steigen, English stair: Sanskrit stighnute, stride.
cast, cast out, vomit, Irish teilgim, Old Irish teilcim: to-es-leic, "let out", from the original of Gaelic leig, let, q.v.
return, Irish tillim (Keating), fillim, pillim (O'Br.) (Ulster has till): *svelni-, turn round, Welsh chwylo, turn, revolve, chwyl, a turn, course, while (for which See Gaelic seal). Cf. fill.
time; from the English

around, a circuit, so Irish, Old Irish timchell: *to-imm-cell, from Indo-European qel, move, go; Latin colo, tend, celer, swift; Greek @Gpelomai, go, be, @Ga@'mfípolos, attendant; Sanskrit cárâmi, move, go. See buachaill.  page 367
sick, Irish tinn, Early Irish tind: *tenni-, root ten of tana, teann, teinn. Cf. Old Irish tinaim, evanesco, Latin attenuo, English attenuate.
a chain, link, piece of a column, Middle Irish tinne, flitch, Early Irish tinde, ring, link, bar, Old Irish tinne, chalybs; from the root ten of tana. Cf. Norse þind, diaphragm.
a heap (Arg.); from English heap or Gaelic iob?

a well, Old Gaelic tiprat (gen., Book of Deer), Irish tiobar, tiobrad, Early Irish tipra, d. tiprait, *to-aith-brevant-, Celtic verb *bervô, seethe, boil; Greek @Gfréar, @Gfréatos, a well; German brunnen, English burn. See tobar.

a gift, Irish tiodhlacadh, Early Irish tidnacul, Old Irish tindnacul, traditio, do-ind-naich, distribuit: to-ind-nank-, root nank, bring, get, Latin nanciscor, obtain; also root enk as in thig, q.v. Hence also tiodhlaic, bury, and adhlac, q.v.
a short space, a snatch:
snatch, grasp eagerly, Irish tiolpaim:

soft, timid, Gaelic tioma, tenderness, Irish time, fear, Early Irish tim, soft, timid, timme, fear: *temmi-, root tem, faint, Latin timeo, fear, English timid; Sanskrit tam, to faint, Zend tam, perish.

a will or testament, Irish tiomna, Old Irish timne: *to-imm-ne, the n of ne being the remains of -ân-, mandare, mittere (Ascoli); cf. Old Irish adroni, deposuit, immeráni, delegavit, Gaelic àithne, command, q.v.

a musical instrument - a cymbal, Irish tiompán, tabor, cymbal, drum, Early Irish tiompan, a small stringed instrument; from Latin tympanum, a timbrel, drum (Windisch). The difference of meaning between Early Irish and Latin has caused some to doubt the connection; and Stokes gives the Celtic root as temppu-, a chord or string, Lithuanian tempiù, stretch, Church Slavonic te@?etiva, chorda.
collecting, bringing together, Irish tiomsughadh, Early Irish timmsugud: *to-imm-sag-, root sag as in ionnsuidh, q.v.

gather, Irish tionólaim, Old Irish tinólaim, tinolaim, do-in-ola, applicat: *to-in-o@-la-im, where o@-la is referred by Stokes to *oklo-, *polko-, joining, uniting, Ger fügen, to fit, füge, joint; Latin paciscor, bargain, bind; Sanskrit pa@-/ças, a knot, Zend paç, bind. Ascoli regards it as *to-in-od-lu, root lu, plu of dol, but *od-lu- would rather mean "go out", "go off". Welsh cynull, gathering, Cornish cuntell, Old Breton contullet, are, according to Ernault, borrowed from Latin contuli.
likeness of any person or thing: *t-ionnail, from ionnan, like.
turning, Irish tiontodh, Old Irish tintuith, g. tintuda tintathigh, interpretes: *to-ind-sout-, root su of iompaidh, q.v.  page 368

a beginning, devising, tionnsgal, ingenuity, Irish tionnscnadh, a beginning, device, plotting, tionsgiodal, managing, industry, Old Irish tinscnaim (= to-ind-scannaim), I begin, tindscetal, a beginning, root sqend, start, spring, Latin scando, ascend, Sanskrit skandati, hurry, spring. The Welsh has cy-chwyn, ortus (*sqenô). The form -scetal is for sqen-t- (?).
pilfer (M`A.); cf. tiolp.
dry (as corn), kiln-dry, Irish tiortha, kiln-dried (Con.), Middle Irish tírad, kiln-drying, Early Irish tír, to dry; from the root of tioram (Old Irish tírim).

warm, cosy, sheltered, Irish tíoramhuil, cosy; Welsh tirion, pleasant, a familiar abject; cf. Irish tíoramhuil, tíorthamhuil, homely, national, from tír. Dr Cameron regarded it as taken from the root of tioram, which is ultimatley the same as that of tìr. Borrowing from English cheerful is unlikely.
dry, Irish tirim, Middle Irish tirimm, Old Irish tírim, tír (vb.): *tersmi-, root ters, dry, as in tart, q.v. See also tìr for phonetics.
save, deliver from peril: *t-erc-, *to-arki-, root ark of teasairg, q.v.
an accident:
water-gruel; from English ptisan, Latin ptisana, barley water, from Greek @Gptisánc.
tiotan, a moment, while; cf. Irish giota, something small, jot, appendage, from Latin iota, whence English jot. Gaelic is t-iot.

land, earth, Irish, Old Irish tír, Welsh, Cornish, Breton tir, tellus, la terre: *têros (*têres-); Latin terra (*tersâ), Oscan teerum, territorium. The further root is ters, be dry, as in tart; the idea of tír, terrâ, is "dry land" opposed to sea.
an interjection expressive of wet being perceived suddenly (H.S.D.): English chut?
come, let us go; from deaspirated thugainn, "to us", for chugainn, q.v.
thick, Irish tiugh, Early Irish tiug, Welsh tew, Old Welsh teu, obtuso, Cornish tew, Breton teu: *tegu-, thick; English thick, Norse þykkr, German dick; Greek @Gstegnós, fast, tight.
a beach out of reach of the sea; for an t-iurr, from Norse eyrr, a gravelly bank by a river or a promontory, Swed ör, Danish örr. tiur, mark of sea on shore, tear, stamp (Carm.).
pleasure, so Irish, Middle Irish tlacht: tl@.-ko-, "willing", from toil, will, q.v. Old Irish todlugud, petitio, tothlaigim, I desire, is from *tloq-, of altach.  page 369
teaze (wool), handful of wool. Strachan and Stokes give the stem as *tlagm (read tlâg-s-m-) allied to German flocke, flock of wool, English flock.

mild, smooth, Irish tlaith (tláith, O'Br.), tlath, Early Irish tlaith, Welsh tlawd: *tlâti-, "long-suffering", from tel, bear, endure; Greek @Gtlctós, tláw, endure; Latin tollo, raise, tuli, lâtus (for *tlâtus), borne; English, Scottish thole.
liquid, spume: t-lighe?
pity, tenderness, Middle Irish tlusach, wealthy, Welsh tlws, jewel (Stokes), Early Irish tlus (S.n.R.); from root tl@., tel of tlàth, q.v.
envy, Irish, Early Irish tnúth; from the root ten, stretch: "grasping"?
verbal prefix = to, ad, Irish, Old Irish to-, do-. Stokes compares Gothic du- to, from þu (?). Welsh has du-, dy-, y, Cornish dhi, Breton do, da.
flux, diarrh@oea spasms: to-fo-od-ber-t, root ber of beir.
wreath of wool or flax on a distaff; from Scottish tappin.

a well, Irish tobar, Old Irish topur, fons: *to-od-bur, root bhur, bhru, to well, boil; Greek @Gfúrw, mix; Latin ferveo, well, English fervid; Sanskrit bhur, move quickly: further See root bhru in bruith, and bhrev in tiobar. Some have referred tobar to the root ber of inbhir, abar ( obair).
a rope, from Scottish tow, rope, English tow, pull, Norse tog, rope, Latin duco.
turf, roofless walls, knoll; from Norse toft, topt, a clearing, a space enclosed by roofless walls, English toft, tuft, and top.
a rower's bend; from Norse þopta.
hough or thigh of an animal: *t-hoch, from the Scottish hough.
dig, Irish tochuilim, tochlaim: *to-cladh; See cladh.
dowry, Irish tochar, Middle Irish tocra, (acc.); cf. Old Irish tochur, placing, from cuir, put. The idea is "something assigned to one". Hence Scottish tocher.
an unpleasant smell, tòchar or tàchar, dense volume of smoke (Arg.); root stou, as in toth.
a disease of the eye in cattle; cf. Scottish hock (H.S.D.).
a wooing, so Irish, Old Irish tochmarc: *to-com-arc; See for root iomchorc.
a hogshead; from the English
small tuft of wool (Lewis); Norse toddi, a tod of wool. So Badenoch.
manure, a bleaching, seaweed for manure, Irish tuar, a bleach-green, tuarachan, a bleacher:
mastiff, better tobhlair:  page 370
raise, togail, liftin, Irish tógaim, tógbhail, Early Irish tócbaim: *to-od-gab-im-, from gab, gabh, take, q.v.
desire, Irish togairim, please, choose, Gaelic inf. togradh, Irish togra: *to-od-gar, root gar of goir.
attention, care (H.S.D.); a variant of taidhe.
exhalation (M`A.); cf. tòch.
reproach, blasphemy, Irish toibhéim, blemish, reproach, Early Irish toibeim: *to-béim, from béim, that is, beum, q.v.
wealth, riches, Irish toice; cf. taic.
a swelling, a puffed up state of the face:
purse-proud; from tòic.
arrogance (Sh., O'Br.); See tostal.

agreeable, cordi (mihi est), docha, preferable, is docha leam, I prefer, Old Irish toich, acceptus, tochu, acceptior: *to-gus-, root gus, choose, as inn tagh. It has also been analysed as *do- sech, or *do-fech, roots seq, veq? Stokes derives this from *togi-s, root tag, take, Latin tango, etc.
will, Irish toil, Old Irish tol: *tolâ, root tel, take, lift, endure; Latin tollo, tolero; English thole, tolerate, etc. See tlachd, tlàth.
deserve, Irish tuillim, Old Irish tuillim, atroilli, asroille, meruit, later do-sli, meruit, from sli (Thurneysen, Strachan).
a riddle, Irish toimseachán, a riddle, measure; from tomhas, q.v.
good sense, toimhseil, sensible (Suth.); from tomhas.
understanding:
twist; from Norse tvinna, twinne, twist thread, English twine.
the miller's share of meal for grinding (S. Argyle):

pursuit, Irish, Early Irish tóir, Irish tóruigheachd, tóireacht: *to-fo-racht, root reg of éirich. Rhys agrees. Cf. Old Irish toracht, successus, processus (= to-racht), tíarmóracht, pursuit (*to-iarm-fo-racht). From Irish tóruighe, pursuer, comes English Tory.
efficiency, bounty, Irish toirbheart, gift, munificence; See tairbheartach for the roots.
a mighty leap; cf. Early Irish tairlingim, jump out of, jump off, alight, turlaim (inf.): *to-air-ling-, for which See leum. Hence tòirlinn, alight (M`A.).
a noise, Irish toirm, tormán, Early Irish toirm, tairm: *tor-s-men, root tor of torrunn. Cf. Welsh twrf, tyrfan, tumult, Lithuanian tarme@?, declaration. Cf. seirm, foirm.
forbid, so Irish, Middle Irish tairmiscim, prohibit, hinder: *tarmi-sc, from tarmi, the composition form of tar, across, and sc or sec, say, as in caisg.
a great noise, sound, Irish tóirn; root tor of torrunn.  page 371
foetid, "high" (Wh.):
a sod (M`A.); from Norse torf, English turf.
conception (Bible):
a peat-cutting spade, toirpsgian (M`A.); a hybrid from Norse torf, turf, peat, and Gaelic sgian. Cf. Norse torf-skeri, peat-cutter.
respect, value, taste, Irish toirt, quantity, value:
giving; for tabhairt. See tabhair, thoir.
the beginning, front, Irish tosach, Old Irish tossach, initium. See tòiseach.

a beginning, a chief, Irish toiseach, a captain, Old Irish tóisech, praestans, leader, Welsh tywysog, dux, princeps, Welsh Ogmic tofisac and tovisaci (Latin): *to-vessiko-s, root ved, lead, bring; Lithuanian wedù, lead, Church Slavonic veda@?, duco; Zend vádhayeiti, bring, lead. Old Irish has also do-fedim, I lead.
an occasion, opportunity, Irish toisg, circumstances, state, journey, business, Middle Irish toisc, business, Old Irish toisc, necessity: *to-sech, root seq, follow, as in seach.
the left, unlucky:
reward for finding a lost thing; See taisgeal.
smoke, fume, Irish tóit, Middle Irish tutt, smoke: *tutto-, root tu, stu, English steam? See toth.

a little heap; from English tuft. In the sense of "piece of flesh", Irish tóiteán, this is from tóit, roast, smoke (see toit), scarcely to be derived from French tôt, hastily roasted, from Latin tostus.
a hollow in metal, dent, Irish tolc, hole, crevice, Early Irish tolc, Welsh tolc. Rhys says Welsh is borrowed.
a hole, Irish, Early Irish toll, Welsh twll, Breton toull: *tukslo-, root tuk, pierce, punch; Greek @Gtúkos, hammer; Ch.Slavonic root tuk, pierce, is-tu@uknati, effodere, tu@ukalo, cuspis.
tollbooth, a gaol; from the English
a hillock of round form; from Norse hólmr, a holm, islet, "inch", Scottish holm, English holm, Anglo-Saxon holm, mound, billow, German holm, hill.

a hillock, Irish tom, Middle Irish tomm, Welsh tom, Breton das-tum, to heap: *tumbo-, hillock; Greek @Gtúmbos, cairn, mound, English tomb; Sanskrit tunga, high, hight; further Latin tumulus. Welsh tom has been regarded as from the English tomb. But stom, Sanskrit stamba, "busch".
bulk; See somalta.
offer, threaten, Middle Irish tomaithim, Old Irish tomad, g. tomtho, minationes: *to-mat-, root mat, throw, Lithuanian metù, throw.  page 372
measure, so Irish, Old Irish tomus: *to-mus, where mus (*messu-) comes from root met, mê, measure; Latin mêtior, mensus, English measure; Greek @Gmétron, a measure. Allied is Gaelic meas, q.v.
bulk; also tomad. Cf. somalta, large, bulky:
anus, Irish, Early Irish tón, Welsh tin: *tuknâ, tûkno- (Welsh), root teuk, Anglo-Saxon þeóh, English thigh, Teutonic *theuha- (Strachan, ATokes); from root tu, swell.

a wave, Irish, Early Irish tond, Old Irish tonn, Welsh, Cornish ton, Breton tonn: *tunnâ, root tu, swell; Lithuanian tvanas, a flood, tvinti, swell; further Latin tumeo, swell, English thumb. Stokes gives the Celtic as *tundâ, Anglo-Saxon þeótan, howl, Norse þjóta, whistle (as the wind, etc.). Some have correlated it with Latin tundo, beat, root tund, tud, Sanskrit tud-, push.

++toinnte, skin, Irish tonn, hide, skin, Early Irish tonn, skin, surface, Welsh tonn, cutis, Breton tonnenn, rind, surface, hair of the head: tunnâ, skin, hide, whence possibly Low Latin (9th cent.) tunna, a cask, "wine-skin", now English ton.
a wonam's shawl or plaid; from Latin tunica. Cf. Middle Irish tonach, tunic.
augur, Irish tarachair, Early Irish tarathar, Old Cornish tarater, Welsh taradr, Breton tarazr, tarar: *taratro-; Greek @Gtéretron; Latin terebra: root ter, through, as in thar.
produce, fruit, so Irish, Old Irish torad: *to-rad, from *rato-, root rat, ra, give, as in rath, q.v.
grub-worm, Irish torain, corn maggots (O'Br.), torán (Con., etc.); from tor, bore, as in tora?

a boar, Irish, Old Irish torc, Welsh twrch, cor. torch, Breton tourc'h, Old Breton turch: *t-orko-s, from *orko-, in uircean, q.v.: Indo-European porko-s, swine, Latin porcus, Lithuanian parsza-s, English farrow. Stokes gives Celtic as *torko-s, Jubainvill as *turco-s.
a cleft, notch (Carm.):
species of bere, biforked corrot, Irish turcan? (Carm.):

a fall, killing, torchuir (vb.), Irish torchair, fell, Old Irish torchar, I fell, doro-chair, cecidit, ara-chrinim, difficiscor, root ker, Sanskrit çar, break to pieces, çr@.na@-/mi, break; See crìon.
a purling sound; from tor of torrunn.

a hill of conic form, heap, castle, Irish tor, tower, castle, crest, Early Irish tor, tuir, d. turid, a tower, Welsh twr, Cornish tur, Breton tour: *turi-, *turet-, Indo-European root tver, hold, enclose, Latin turris, Greek @Gtúrsis, tower. Some hold that the Celtic is borrowed from Latin Gaelic tòrr, with rr, is possibly for torth (cf. *turet-). It also means "crowd" in Gaelic and Early Irish, and "heap" also in Welsh  page 373
pregnant, Irish torrach, pregnant, fruitful, Early Irish torrach: *torth-aco-, from *torato-, toradh, fruit, q.v. Welsh torwy big-bellied, has been compared, from tor, belly, Gaelic tàrr.
(torradh, H.S.D.), burial, funeral solemnities, Irish tórradh, watching or waking of the dead, Early Irish torroma, attending, watching:

thunder, Irish toran, a great noise, Early Irish torand, thunder, Welsh tarann, Cornish taran, tonitruum: *toranno-s; Greek @Gtóros, sound; Lithuanian tàrti, say. Gaulish Taranis, the Gaulish Jove or Thor, and Gaelic tàirneanach show an a grade of the root.

silence, so Irish, Old Irish tost: *tusto-, root tus, teus, whence Early Irish tó, tua, silent; Old Prussian tussîse, silet, Ch.Slavonic tichu, silent; Sanskrit tush, silere, tushnîm, silently. tòs, calm = clos (Hend.).
a tusk; from the English
a hack, gash, dent (Wh.):
a peat-cutter (Dial.); from Scottish tusk in tusk-spawd (Banff), tuskar (Ork. and Sh.), tusk, cut peats. Cf. Shet. tushker, from Norse torfskeri, turf-cutter.
an ambassador or post, Irish toisg, a journey, business. See toisg.
arrogance, Irish tósdal, toichiosdal ( O'Br.), Old Irish tochossol, violation: *to-con-sal, from sal, leap (see tuisleadh)? Also toichiosdal.
rower's bench, turf; See tobhta.
a foul blast of vapour, also stoth, q.v.; See toit for root.
(tràbhach, M`F.), rubbish cast ashore, the grass fiorin; from tràigh? Cf., however, drabhas. tràibheanach, bedraggled fellow (R.D.). Cf. Scottish drab.
mill-hopper (M`A.); possibly from Latin trabula.
negotiation, proposal, so Irish; from Latin tracto, treat.
fatique; from Scottish trachle, draggle, fatiguing exertion.  -KPD: Related to Co. Clare Anglo-Irish <I>trálach</I>, pain in wrist from  -KPD: overwork?
a lance, fishing spear, Irish tradh, lance, treagh, spear; from the root tar, tra (see thar), through, Latin trâgula, a dart.
the shore, Irish tráigh, Early Irish tráig: *trâgi-; See traogh.
a slave, Irish traill (O'Br.), Middle Irish tráill (not well known to glossographers); from Norse þraell, English thrall.
the fish tusk:
a poultice, cataplasm, rag, Irish treata (tréata, Con.), plaster:
a whim (M`A.):
busy; from Scottish thrang, English throng.
one wasting away with sickness (Hend.); cf. Irish (Keat. traothaim, wear out, am weary.  page 374
ebb, Irish tráighim, traoghaim, Early Irish trágim, Welsh treio, ebb, trai, ebb-tide, traeth, shore: *trâgô, from trâg, Indo-European tragh, draw, Latin traho, etc.; See troidh for root.
the corncrake, Irish traona; See trèan-ri-trèan.
a cluster, Irish trapán:

across, trasdan, cross beam, crozier, Old Irish trost, trabs, from tar, tra of thar. Cf. Welsh trawst, rafter, which Stokes and Loth think to be borrowed from Latin transtrum, as also Old Irish trost mentioned above. Scottish has trast or trest, beam, from early French traste, Latin transtrum.
a fast, Irish trosgadh, Old Irish troscud: *truskô, *trud-skô, root trud, distress, burden, Latin trûdo, push, English threaten. See trod, trom.
time, season, Irish, Early Irish tráth: *trâtu-, root tra, tar, through (see thar). Cf. Welsh tro, turn, time, Breton tro, occasion, round; English turn.

through, Irish tré, tre, Early Irish tré, tria, tri, Old Irish tri, trí, tre, Old Welsh troi, now trwy, Cornish, Breton dre, Old Breton tre, dre: *trei, *tri, root ter, pass over, through; Latin trans, across; Sanskrit tirás, through, over, Zend tarô (do.). See the root in thar, tora, troimh; also in English through.

plough, till, Irish treabhaim, Early Irish trebaim, inhabit, cultivate, treb, a dwelling, Welsh tref, homestead, Old Welsh, Old Breton treb: *trebo-, a house; Latin tribus, trebus, a tribe, English tribe; English thorp; Lithuanian trobà, dwelling, building. Hence treabhair, houses, treibhireach, prudent.
a thrave; from Norse þrefi, English thrave.
dig, treachladh (1) digging (2) fatiguing: *tre-clad; for (1) See cladh and cf. tochail; from (2) cf. Scottish trachle.
a darting pain, stitch, Irish treagh(d)aim, I pierce through, Middle Irish treghat, pangs, smart, treaglad, transpiercing; Irish treagh, a spear: "piercing". See tradh.
lumber, trash, Irish trealamh, lumber, apparel, instruments, Early Irish trelam, weapons, furniture, apparel: *tre-lam; for lam, See ullamh.
the spleen (M`F.):
indisposition (M`F.):
adult, grown-up (M`A. for Islay):
a short space or time, Irish treall, Middle Irish trell, root ter, through, English thrill, pierce.
corn-crake, Irish traona:
cut (Carm.):
third, Irish treas, Old Irish tress: *tristo-, from tris, thrice, Greek @Gtrís, Sanskrit tris, root tri of tri, three. Welsh trydydd, third, is for *tritijo-s.  page 375
battle, skirmish, Irish treas, Early Irish tress. For root, cf. treasa. Welsh has trîn, battle, bustle, treis, violence.

stronger, Irish treas, strong, treise, stronger, Old Irish tressa, Welsh trech, fortior, Breton trec'h: *treksjôs, fortior, root treg, streg, sterg, strong, English stark, Lithuanian stre@?gti, stiffen, Persian suturg (*str@.g), strong. Stokes refers it to the root treg, trag, draw, leap, as in troigh, traogh. See treun further; treasa is its comparative really.
thorough-paced (of a horse); cf. Irish trosdán, a pace, jump; root treg, draw, walk, as in troigh.
refuse of brewed malt, groats, Irish treasúmha, dross, copper dross, treascach, draffy, Middle Irish tresc, refuse, offal: *tre-sco?

gla: treibhireach ( treibhdhireach, Dictionaries), prudent, upright, Old Irish trebar, prudent, Middle Irish trebaire, prudence; from treb of treabh, q.v.
eng: tréig
forsake, Irish tréigim, Early Irish trécim, Welsh trancu, perish: *trankjô, abandon, root trak, push, press, as in dùrachd (Stokes).
a while, space, also greis, Irish treibhse, dreibhse (O'Br.), treimhse (Con.); See greis.
a while, space, also greis, Irish treibhse, dreibhse (O'Br.), treimhse (Con.); See greis.
weaver's paste, trash (M`A., Arg.), Irish treisgin (con., etc.), dreislinn (Monaghan); cf. Scottish dressing.
a smith's nail mould, Irish treóir, treoir; from tre, trem, through?
strength, Irish treóir, conduct, strength, Middle Irish treorach, strong, Early Irish treóir, vigour: *treg-ri-, root treg of treasa.
guide, Irish treóruighim, Middle Irish treoraigim: *trag-ri-, root trag of troigh?
a tribe; from Latin tri@ubus, a tribe. See treabh.
valorous, strenuous, treubhantas, bravery; for *treuntas, from which treubhach is deduced. M`Kinnon (Gael.Soc.Tr.@+13, 341) refers it to treubh, tribe.

flock, herd, Irish tréad, treud, Early Irish trét: *trento-, root trem, Latin turma, troop, Anglo-Saxon þruma, heap, company (Strachan, Stokes). Windisch has compared Greek @Gstratós (*strn@.tos) to treud.
brave, Irish treun, Old Irish trén, fortis, Welsh tren, strenuous, force: *tregno-, root treg of treasa, q.v. Stokes gives the Celtic as *treksno-, which would produce *tresno-, modern treann.
three, Irish, Old Irish treí, Welsh tri, Cornish try, Breton tri: *treis; Latin três (*trei-es); Greek @Gtrei@ns; Gothic þreis, English three; Lithuanian try/s; Sanskrit tráyas.
going, journey, Irish tríall, Early Irish triall: *tri-all, "go-through", root ell of tadhal?  page 376
third part, a third, Irish, Early Irish trían, Welsh traian: *treisano-; See treas, tri.
lord, chief, Early Irish tríath: *treito-s. Stokes compares Latin trîtavus, strîtavus, ancestor in the 6th degree.
frequent, often, Irish tric, Early Irish trice: *trekki-, root treg of troigh (Stokes, Strachan).

through, by, Irish tríd, Early Irish trít, per eum, id: *trei-t, from root trei of tre, through; the final -t is the demonstrative pron. to (English that, Greek @Gto); a pron. *em-ti, *en-ti (Stokes).
rag, clout, stitch; "Cha'n 'eil trìd air":

thrilling, quavering; cf. Early Irish trílech, song, Old Irish trírech, song of birds. Cf. English trill, Italian trillare, Sp. trinar: an initiative word, English thrill is from the root tre, ter ( See tora), "piercing", which may also be the ultimate origin of the Gaelic words.
locks of hair, Irish trilis (obs.), Early Irish triliss; cf. English tress, from Latin tricia, trica, plait, Greek @Gtríha, in three parts, root tri, three.
sand plover (Heb., Miss Freer):
(drilleachan, M`A.), the pied oyster-catcher, sea-piet:
(drillsean, M`A.), lantern, rush-light, a glimmer, Irish triliseán, torch, lantern, earlier trilsen, facula, trillsech, sparkling: "piercing", from tre, ter, as in trileanta?
a plate, trencher, Irish trinsiur; from English trencher.
trouble, tribulation, Irish trioblóid, Early Irish tréblait; from Latin tribulatio, English tribulation.
vibrate, quiver; from English tremble?
a trinity, Irish tríonóid, tríonoid, Early Irish trínóit, Old Irish trindóit; from Latin trinitât-, trinitas, a trinity, from tres, three. The Gadelic is developed from *trin(i)tâti-.

trews, trousers, Irish triús, Middle Irish tribus, Old Irish trebus, breeches, Late Latin tubrucus (Isidor), tribuces (Du Cange), "thigh breeches" (D' Arbois); from Scottish trews, English trooze, trouses, now trousers, trunkhose.
a rascal; from Scottish truker, trukier, a deceitful person, from Old French tricher, to trick, allied to English trick.
a stripe of distinguishing colours in tartan:
( M`F.), hooping cough, triogh ( M`A.), a fit of laughing or coughing, Irish triuch, trioch: root pster of sreothart?
come thou hither to me; opposite of thugad: *to-ro'-ad, *to-romh-t, "to before you"?  page 377

mercy, Irish, Old Irish trócaire, Welsh trugaredd, Cornish tregereth, Middle Breton trugarez, Old Welsh trucarauc, merciful: *trougo-karja, "loving of the wretched", from the roots of truagh and car, love.

a quarrel, scolding, Irish troid, Middle Irish trot, quarrel, combat, trottach, quarrelsome: *truddo-, root trud, distress, bother; English threat, Norse þrjóta, fail, lack; Latin trûdo, push, English obtrude; Church Slavonic trudu@u, difficulty.

raise, trogail, raising, Manx troggal, earlier trogell: to-ro-od-gab, that is to say, tog with the prep. ro inserted. See tog. Rhys (Manx Pray.@+2, 138) compares Early Irish turcbál, a rising (as of the sun): *to-for-gab-.
trash (Dial.), busy dealing, tròg, busy dealing, from Scottish troke, to bargain, barter, trog, old clothes, troggin, pedlar's wares, English truck, from French troquer, barter, truck.
grumbling ( M`A.), trògbhail, quarrel ( Nich., trogbhail, Arms., Sh., O'R.):
a dwarf; See droich.
cataplasm, rags, shapeless worn shoe (Skye); See trait.

misspelt troidh, a foot, Irish troigh, Old Irish traig, g. traiged, Welsh traed, Old Cornish truit, pes, Middle Breton troat: *traget- (*troget-?), foot, root trag, leap, draw, Gaulish vertragos, greyhound; Indo-European tragh; Gothic @Gþragjan, run, Anglo-Saxon þrah, course; Latin traho, draw.
any trifling thing; founded on English trifles?
through, Old Irish tremi-, trans-, super-: *trimo-, from tri of tre. For the mi or mh, cf. roimh, comh-.

heavy, Irish trom, Old Irish tromm, Welsh trwm, Cornish trom, Breton troum: trud-s-mo-s, "oppressive", from trud, oppress, distress; Gothic us-þriutan, oppress, English threat; Latin trûdo, push. See trod further. For other views, See Rhys' Lect.@+2, 114, Zimmer Zeit.@+24, 208.
dwarf, elder, Irish tromán, Old Irish tromm, g. truimm; also Gaelic droman (M`A.):
the Jew's harp; from Scottish trump (do.), English trump, from French trompe.
a trumpet, Irish trompa, L.Middle Irish trompadh; from the English
a spire, steeple (M`F.); founded on English turret.
dull, seriously inclined, Irish trosdamhuil, serious, confident.
a crutch, support, Irish trostán, crutch, pilgrim's staff, Welsh trostan, long slender pole. See trasd for root.  page 378
a codfish, Irish trosg; from Norse þroskr, Danish torsk, German dorsch.
trot, trotan, trotting; from the English
compassion, Irish truacánta (O'Br.): *troug-can-, "expressing pity", from truagh and can, say.

wretched, pitiful, so Irish, Early Irish trúag, Old Irish tróg, Welsh tru, Cornish troc, miser, Breton tru, Gaulish Trôgos: *trougo-, miser, root streug, rub, wear; Greek @Gstreúgomai, am worn out, distressed; Church Slavonic strugati, scratch, distress, Lithuanian strugas, carving instrument; Norse strjúka, to stroke, German straucheln, stumble (Windisch, Prellwitz). Stokes refers it to the root of Norse þrúga, press, þrúgan, compulsion, Old High German drûh, compes. From Celtic comes English truant.
a sheath, so Irish, Early Irish trúaill: *troud-s-li-, root treud, trud, push; English thrust, Latin trûdo. See further trod, trom.

pollute, violate, Irish trúaillim, Early Irish trúalnim, Old Irish druáilnithe, corruptus, @oellned, inquinatio, illuvies, élnithid, violator, from éln-, Old Irish as-lenaimm, pollue, Gaelic root len (le@-n, Ascoli), f@oedare (Latin lino, smear, as in lean?). Ascoli analyses truaill into der-uad-le@-n (der- intensive), while Thurneysen refers the tru-, dru- to the root of Latin trux, trucis. dru-es-lén (Stokes). Early Irish trú, wretched, English throe (Stokes).

a stammerer, a dirty or obscene person, Irish trudaire, a stammerer (Lh., O'Br., Con.). In the first sense, the word is Irish; in the second sense, it is Gaelic only, and likely of the same origin as trusdar. Norse þrjótr, knave, bad debtor, has been adduced as its origin.
a dirty or base person, filthy food: *trus-lic-, root trus as in trusdar? Or from Scottish trolie, a person of slovenly habits, trollop?

tear, snatch, truss; from Scottish truss, to eat in a slovenly, scattering fashion (Ork.), Icel. tros, English trash. In the sense of "truss", the Gaelic is from English truss. Hence the cry to dogs to get out - truis!
a troop; from the English
truss or bundle, collect, Irish trusdalaim, truss up, girdle, Welsh trwsa, a truss; from English truss, Old French trusser, from Late Latin tortiare, tortus, twisted. See also triubhas.
a filthy fellow, filth; cf. Irish, Early Irish trist, curse, profligacy, Late Latin tristus, improbus.
clothes, apparel, Irish truscán, trosgán, clothes, furniture; founded on trus. Cf. English trousseau from the same origin.
a traitor, villain; from Scottish trucker, deceiver, trickster? Or from English traitor? Cf. trudair.  page 379
thou, Irish, Old Irish tú, Welsh ti, Cornish ty, te, Breton te: *tû; Latin tû; Greek sú; English thou; Prussian tou; Zend tû.

axe, so Irish, Middle Irish tuag, Early Irish túagach, hitting: *tougâ root teu@gh, tuq, hit, strie; Greek @Gteúhw, fashion, @Gtúkos, hammer, @Gtukánc, flail; Church Slavonic tu@ualo, cuspis. Stokes prefers comparison with Sanskrit tuj, hit (*tug).

dizziness, tuachioll (Sh.), winding, eddying, moving against the sun, left-about: *to-fo-cell (for cell, See timchioll, Irish tuachail, going, confused with *tuath-cell, "left (north) going"? Cf. tuaineal.
reproach, scandal, so Irish ( Lh., O'Br., etc.): *to-fo-less; from *lisso-, blame, discussed under leas-?
a towel; Irish tudhoille; from the English
unloose (Dial.); See tualaig.
dizziness, stupor, Irish toinéall, swoon, trance (Dineen): *to-fo-in-el, root ell of tadhal? Or *to-fo-neul?
a guess, aim, vicinity, Irish tuairim; also tuairmse: *to-for-med-, root med of meas.
turbulence:
confusion, sedition, Irish tuargán, noise, discontent:
description, report, Irish tuarasgbháil, Middle Irish túarascbal, description, Old Irish tuárascbaim, for to-for-as-gab-, root gab of gabh.
hit on, discover: *do-fo-air-mess; See eirmis.
anything round, a boss, tidy female, tuairnean, a mallet, beetle, Irish tuairnín, mallet; cf. tuairnear.
a turner, Irish túrnóir; from the English
a dolt, sloven, tuaisdeach, unseemly:
wrong, left-wise, Irish tuaithbhil, Early Irish tuathbil; from tuath and seal: See deiseil for latter root and form. Irish has tuathal, the left hand, awkward.
loose (Arms.), have flux, tuanlaig (n elided, Perth), tuanaig, tuama, a tomb, Irish tuama; from Latin tumba, English tomb.
food, Old Irish tuare: *taurio-, root staur, place, store, English store, Sanskrit sthávara, fixed: root sta.
hue, appearance; cf. Irish, Middle Irish tuar, an omen, presage: *to-vor-, root ver, vor, of fhuair?

wages, so Irish, Middle Irish tuarustul, tuarastal: *to-fo-ar-as-tal, root tal, tel, take, lift, Middle Irish taile, salarium, Welsh tâl, payment, Cornish, Breton tal, solvit; Indo-European tel; Greek @Gtélos, tax, @Gtálanton, talent; Latin tollo; English thole. See tail, tlàth.

a quarrel, fight, Irish fuasaoid, animosity, spite, Early Irish fúasait, "entwickelung", development: to-fo-ad-sedd-, Gaelic  page 380  root sedd from sizd, si-sed, set, "set-to" being the idea? Root sed of suidhe. But cf. faosaid.
loose, untie, Irish tuaslagadh, releasing, Early Irish tuaslaicim: *to-fo-as-léc-im, from le@-c of leig, let, q.v.

people, tenantry, so Irish, Old Irish túath, populus, Welsh tud, country, nation, Cornish tus, Breton tud, Gaulish Tout-, Teuto-: *toutâ, people; Latin Umbr. toto, state, Oscan túvtú, populus, Latin tôtus, all; Gothic þiuda, people, Teutonic, Deutsch, German, Dutch; Lettic táuta, people, Old Prussian tauto, land.

north, Irish tuath, tuaith, Old Irish túath, left, north: *toutâ, *touto-s (adj.), left hand, left, "good", Gothic þiuþ, good; cf. Greek @Geu@'w/numos, left hand, "good-omened". Rhys (Manx Pray. @+2, 62) suggests that the root is su, turn (see iompaidh): *do-hu@-th (*to-su-), "turning to"; Welsh aswy or aseu, left hand, being also hence - *ad-sou-i-.
a tub; from the English
mischance, Middle Gaelic tubbiste (Dean of Lismore), Arran Gaelic tiompaiste, Irish tubaiste:  -KPD: also Irish <I>timpiste</I>.
tuft of wool on the distaff; See toban.
smother, become hoarse, tùchan, hoarseness: *t-úch; cf. Welsh ig, sob, hiccup.
a small heap or stack (dud, M`A.):
brought; See thug.
witticisms (Dial., H.S.D.):

thatch, covering, tugh (vb.), Irish tuighe (n.), tuighim (vb.), Early Irish tuga, tugim, Welsh to, a cover, thatch, toi, tegere, cor. to, tectum, Breton to, tenn: *togio-, *togo-, root to@g, ste@g, as in tigh, teach.
a patch:

understand, Irish tuigim, Old Irish tuiccim, tuiccim, tuccim: *to-od-ges- root ges of tug. some have given the stem as *to-od-cesi, root qes of chì; but this would give Gaelic tuic. Old Irish tuicse, electus: *to-od-gus-, root gus, taste, English gusto.

a flood, Irish, Old Irish tuile: *tuliâ, root tu, swell; Greek @Gtúlos, knob, weal; Sanskrit tûla, tuft, English thumb, tumid, etc. ( See tulach). So Stokes Zeit.@+31, 235. The Old Irish root o@-l, to flood, abound, gives tólam, a flood, imról, foróil, abundance, etc. The root pol, pel has also been suggested, as in iol-.
overloading stomach (Carm.):

more (n.), Irish tuille, tuilleadh, addition, tuilleamh, wages, addition, Early Irish tuilled, tuillem, addition, inf. to tuillim, enhance, deserve, as in Gaelic toill. Two words are mixed: to-eln-, deserve, and to-oln, much, more, Early Irish oll, great, huilliu, plus, *olniôs, root pol, pel, many, Greek @Gpolús, Latin plus  page 381  etc. (see iol-). Stokes equates the Old Irish uilliu, oll, with Latin pollere, which is from *pol-no-, root pol as above (Wharton). The Gaelic syntax of tuille shows its comparative force in tuille na (more than) as well as tuille agus, Irish tuilleadh agus (addition and).
beating, thumping, tuinnse, a blow (Gael.Soc.Tr.@+15, 260), Middle Irish tuinsim, calco, tuinsem, bruising, *to-ud-nessim (Str.); founded on Latin tundo, beat. Stokes queries if cognate.
an abode, possession, Irish tuinidhe, possession (O'Cl.), Early Irish tunide; also tuineadh (Irish and Gaelic): *to-nes-, root nes as in còmhnuidh, q.v.
deathful, Irish tuinneamh, tuineamh, death:
firm hard, Irish tuinnidhe ( O'Br., Sh.), immovable, clocha tuinnidhe; from tuineadh, the idea being "settled, fixed".

relate, tuireadh, relating, Irish tuirtheachda, relation, rehearsal, Early Irish turthiud, pl. tuirtheta, tale, from ret, run (as in ruith). Cf. aithris, Early Irish tuirem, reciting, is from *to-rím, root ri@-m, number (as in àireamh).
a dirge, lamentation, Irish tuireamh, dirge, elegy; for root See tuirse.
a spark of fire from an anvil, Irish tuireann (O'Br., etc.), Early Irish turend (?): *to-rind? For rind, See reannag.
a saw, Irish tuiriosg, Early Irish turesc: *tar-thesc, from teasg, cut, q.v.
descend, Irish tuirlingim, Early Irish tairlingim, Old Irish doarblaing, desilit *to-air-ling-; for ling, jump, See leum.
sadness, Irish tuirse, Middle Irish tor, sad, Early Irish toirsi, torsi, Old Irish toris, toirsech, tristis; root tor, ter, tre, Latin tristis, sad.
incense, Irish, Middle Irish, Early Irish túis; from Latin tu@-s, Greek @Gqúos.

a stumbling, fall, so Irish, Old Irish tuisled, prolapsio, tuisel, casus, dofuislim, labo: *to-fo-ess-sal-im, root sal, spring; Latin salio, leap, dance, English insult; Greek @Ga@`/llomai, leap; cf. Lithuanian sele@?/ti, glide, creep. Ascoli analyses it into *to-fo-isl-, where isl is what remains of ísel or ìosal, low.

fall, Irish tuitim, Old Irish tuitim, inf. tutimm, acc.pl. totman, also tothimm, *tod-tim, Gadelic root -tim-, Welsh codwm, a fall (cf. Irish cudaim), codymu, cadere, Cornish codha; cf. English tumble, Greek tomber, fall. Usually explained as *to-fo-thét-, from théid, which would naturally be tuid in Gaelic, even granting that the crasis of -ofothé- simply landed in -ui-, not to mention the inf. in preserved m (tuiteam). Root tud (Thurneysen); to-ud = think.
entirely, Irish tul (i.e. tuile, O'Cl.), increase, flood: an adverbial use of the root form of tuil, flood? Cf. Irish tola, superfluity.
fire, hearth, heap (Carm.):  page 382
a hillock, Irish, Early Irish tulach; root tu, swell; Greek @Gtúlos, knob, @Gtùlc (u long), swelling, weal; Latin tumor, tu@-ber, a swelling; English thumb.
the fish whiting, Irish tullóg, the pollock; cf. pollag.
a gable, posterior, Irish tulchán, hillock; from tulach?
plucky (Hend.):
dip, tumadh, dipping, so Irish, Early Irish tummim: *tumbô; Latin tinguo, tingo, wet, English tinge, tincture; Old High German duncôn, dip, ger. tunken, dip, steep.

a tun, ton, Irish, Early Irish tunna; Anglo-Saxon tunne, Middle English tonne, Norse tunna, German tonne; all from Latin tunna, a cask. Stokes (Bez.Beit.@+18), suggests borrowing from the Norse; Kluge regards the words as of Celtic origin. On this See ++tonn.
beating, dashing; See tuimhseadh.
a duck, Irish tonnóg?
upheaval (R.D.):
entirely, Irish tura, plenty (tura namhad, plenty of enemies), Early Irish tor, a crowd (dat. tur); See tòrr.
a tower, Irish túr; from Middle English tour, tu@-r, from Old French tur, Latin turris.
understanding; cf. Middle Irish túr, research, examination, Old Irish túirim, rotuirset, scrutati sunt, for to-fo-shirim, from sir, search.
dry weather, tur, dry (without condiment), so Irish, Early Irish turud, terad, adj. tur, dry, tair: root tor, ter of tioram?
a trifling illness (as of a child) - Arg.:
rocking, nodding; See turraban.
tweezers (M`A.), pincers; See durcaisd.

destruction (H.S.D. from MSS.), Middle Irish tuarcain, smiting, Early Irish tuarcaim (dat.), hitting: *to-fo-argim, root org, Old Irish orgun, orcun, occisio, Old Breton orgiat, Cæsar's Gaulish Orgeto-rix: *urg-, root vr@.g, verg, press, Latin urgeo. Stokes suggests connection with Greek @Ge@'réhqw, tear; Bezzenberger gives Zend areza, battle, fight; Brugmann compares Sanskrit r@.gha@-yati, raves, rages, Old High German arg, what is vile or bad.
a large fire: *t-ur-lach, from Irish ur, úr, fire, Greek @Gpu@nr, English fire.
a bulky, squat person; See tòrr, turadh. Cf. Welsh twrllach, a rounnd lump.
small cupboard (Perth); See tairleas.
a lake that dries in summer, Irish turloch; from tur and loch.
a turn, job; from the English  page 383
rocking of the body, nodding, grief (turadan, Sh.). Hence turra-chadal, a slumbering drowsiness, "nodding sleep":
an accident:
a surprise, taking unnawares (Skye):
at stool (M`A.):
a soft sound, murmur; onnomatopoetic. But cf. toirm, torrunn.
a turtle, so Irish, Welsh turtur; from Latin turtur.
a journey, Irish, Early Irish turus, Old Irish tururas, incursus, aururas, properatio: *to-reth-s-tu, root ret, run (see ruith).
the beginning, Irish tús, Old Irish túus, tús, Welsh tywys, leading; See tòiseach.
interjection of cold or impatience; from English tut. See thud.
a quiet breaking of wind, stench, Irish tút, Middle Irish tútt, stench: allied to toit, q.v. Cf. Keating's tútmhar, smoky.
a slut (Arms., M`L.), Irish túthan; from the root of the above word. U
from, Irish ua, ó, Old Irish ua, hua, ó: *ava, ab; Sanskrit áva, ab, off; Latin au- (au-fero), away; Church Slavonic u-, ab, away. See o.
expulsion: *od-bert-, prefixed by ua? from the root ber (in beir).

pride, so Irish, Old Irish úabar, vainglory, Welsh ofer, waste, vain (Ascoli): *oubro-, root eu@g, rise, Greek @Gu@`/bris, insolence (See uasal). It has also been analysed into *ua-ber like uabairt = "e-latio", elation.
surface, summit, so Irish, Old Irish uachtar, ochtar: *ouktero-, root eu@g, ve@g, rise, be vigorous, as in uasal, q.v. Cf. Welsh uthr, admirandus.
in uadh-bheist, monster, uadh-chrith, terror; See ++uath below.
a grave, Irish uaigh, Middle Irish uag, Early Irish uag, *augâ, allied to Gothic augo, eye, English eye. See for force dearc. So Stokes, and rightly.
secret, lonesome, so Irish, Middle Irish uagnech: *uath-gen-, "lonesome-kind", from uath, lonesome, single; Norse auðr, empty, Gothic auþs, waste, desert; Latin ôtium, rest.
pride, Irish uaill, Early Irish úaill, Old Irish uall: *oukslâ, root eu@g, ve@g of uasal.

a cave, den, Irish uaimh, g. uamha, Middle Irish uaim, g. uama, Old Irish huam, specus (also huád, specu): *oumâ. Bezzenberger suggests *poumâ, allied to Greek @Gpw@nma, a lid ( @G*pwuma); Strachan  page 384  compares Greek @Geu@'nc/, bed (German wohnen, dwell). Welsh ogof, cave, den is correlated by Ascoli.
green, Irish uainne, uaithne, Early Irish úane. Strachan suggets the possibility of a Gadelic *ugnio-, root ve@g, be wet, Greek u@`grós, wet (see feur).
bustle, wallowing, Irish únfuirt, wallowing, tumbling; also Gaelic aonairt, aonagail:

an hour, Irish uair, Old Irish huar, uar, g. hóre, Welsh awr, Cornish our, Old Breton aor, Breton eur, heur; from Latin hora, English hour. Hence uaireadair, a watch, time-piece, Irish uaireadóir (*horatorium?).
pride, nobility, so Irish; from uasal, q.v.
a burden, Irish ualach: *podl-; Old High German fazza, a bundle, German fassen, hold (Strachan). Also Gaelic eallach, q.v.
gay, proud, so Irish; from uaill.
sheep-louse:
dreadful, Irish uathmhar, Early Irish úathmar; from ++uath, fear, q.v. Used adverbially, like English awfully, to denote excess. Dial. uarraidh.
dread, horror, uathbhas, Irish uathbhás, Early Irish úathbhás: *uath-bás, "dread death"; See ++uath and bàs.

horror, Irish uamhan, awe, horror, Early Irish uamun, hóman, Old Irish omun, homon, rarely, ómun, fear, Welsh ofn, fear, awe, Cornish own, Breton aoun, Gaulish -obnos, Ex-obnus, Fearless: *obno-s, fear. Bez. cfs. Gothic bi-abrjan, be astounded (but abrs means "powerful"), and Greek @Ga@'/fnw, suddenly.

a lamb, Irish, Middle Irish uan, Welsh oen, pl. wyn, Cornish oin, Breton oan: *ogno-s; Latin agnus; Greek @Gámnós (for @Ga@'bnós); Church Slavonic jagne; Also Anglo-Saxon éanian, to yean or lamb (*auno@-n).
waterfall, heavy shower, confluence (Sutherland Dial.), Irish, Early Irish úarán, fresh spring; See fuaran. Arms. has uaran, fresh water.
hourly, temporary (H.S.D.), homely (M`L.); from uair.

noble, proud, Irish, Old Irish uasal, Welsh uchel, Breton uhel, huel, Gaulish uxello-: *oukselo-, high, root eu@g, ve@g, rise, increase; Greek @Gu@`yclós, high, @Gau@'xw, increase; Latin augeo, increase, vigeo, be strong; English up, German auf; Lithuanian áuksztas, high.
dread, Irish uath, Old Irish úath, Cornish uth, Breton eus, heuz, horror; *pouto-, root pu, foul; Latin putris, English putrid, foul?
ubub! interjection of contempt or aversion, Old Irish upp.
a charm, Irish uptha, upadh, sorcerer, Old Irish upta, fascinatio, uptha, Manx obbee, sorcery: *od-ba-t-, from ba, speak (see ob, refuse). Zimmer refers it to root ben of bean, hurt, touch.
rummaging amoung heavy articles, bustle (Dial.); See ùbraid.  page 385
interjection of disgust or amazement; cf. English phew.

an egg, Irish ubh, ugh, Old Irish og, ub (?), Welsh wy, pl. wyan, Cornish uy, oy, Breton u, vi: *ogos; Greek w@'/beon, egg, further w@'ón, Latin ovum, English egg. The phonetics as between Celtic and the other languages is somewhat difficult; but the connection is indisputable.

apple, Irish ubhall, Early Irish uball, ubull, Old Irish aball, Welsh afal, Cornish auallen, Breton avallen: *aballo-, *aballôn; English apple, German apfel; Lithuanian obu@olys. Stokes now queries German obst, fruit, Old High German obaz, Anglo-Saxon ofet, fruit.
a fine, penalty:
confusion, dispute, also ùprait: *ud-bert-, from ber of beir.
coal-fish, stenlock:

the breast, so Irish, Old Irish ucht: *poktu-; Let. pectus? Stokes and Bezzenberger give *puptu-, Lettic pups, woman's breast, Lithuanian pápas, breast (English pap from Latin pappa). St. now gives poktus, allied to pectus. See iochd.
yon, yonder, Irish úd, Early Irish út; for sud (sút), q.v. For loss of s, cf. the article.
outhouse, porch, back-house (ùdabac, Uist); from Norse úti-bak, "out-back"?
cause to shake, waver, remove, Irish udmhall, quick, stirring (O'Cl.), Old Irish utmall, unsteady, utmaille, instability: út of sud + tamall (Rhys).
inhospitable, churlish, ùdlaidh, gloomy; cf. Norse útlagi, an outlaw, útlagð, outlawry.
a swivel, Irish udalán (Fol., O'R.); from udail. Cf. ludnan.
a boil, ulcer; also othar, q.v.
a stag, old hart (Arms.):
free egress and regress to common pasture; from the Norse - cf. útreið, an expedition, "out-road".
the upper part of the breast, Irish ugán, craw of a fowl, ugann, fish gill (Heb.):
author, Irish úghdar, Early Irish ugtar, Old Irish augtor; from Latin auctor.
coal-fish; See ucas.
a mass, lump (as of dough), iob; cf. faob: *ud-bio-, "out-being". But cf. Latin offa, ball.
a number, quantity, Irish uibhir, uimhir, Early Irish numir, number; from Latin numerus, English number.
(uidh), care, heed, Irish uidh (obs.), Old Irish oid; See taidhe.

a ford, that part of a stream leaving a lake before breaking into a current; also an isthmus (M`Kinnon), uidh, aoi); from  page 386  Norse eið, an isthmus, neck of land. Hence Eye or Ui near Stornoway, older Ey, Huy, Eie.
a journey, distance, Irish uidhe, Early Irish ude, Old Irish huide, profectio: *odio-n, root pod, ped, go; Latin pes, pedis, foot; Greek @Gpoús, @Gpodós, foot; English foot; Sanskrit padyâ, footstep.

accoutrements, apparatus, Irish ughaim, harness, trappings, Old Irish aidmi, armamenta, Welsh iau, jugum, Old Cornish iou, Breton geo, ieo, *yougo-, yoke; English yoke, German joch; Greek @Gzugón; Latin jugum; Lithuanian jungas. The Gadelic requires a form *ad-jung-mi. Cf. Old Irish adim, instrumentum, pl.n. admi.
a nook, cove; from Norse vík, bay, creek, English wick, -wich. Hence the place name Uig (Skye, Lewis). Hence ùigean, a fugitive, wanderer.
pleasant, careful; from aoigh in the first meaning and from ùidh in the second.

all, the whole, Irish uile, Old Irish uile, huile: *polio-s, root pol, pel, full, many, Greek @Gpollós (= @Gpolios), much, many; See iol-. Stokes and most philologists refer it to *oljo-s, English all, German all, Gothic alls (*olnó-s, Mayhew). Some have derived it from *soli-, Latin sollus, whole, Greek @Go@`los, whence Stokes deduces the Brittonic words - Welsh oll, all, Cornish hol, Breton holl, oll (see slàn).

elbow, Irish uille, g. uilleann, Middle Irish uille, pl.acc. uillinn, Old Irish uilin (acc.), Welsh, Cornish elin, Breton ilin, elin: *olên-; Greek @Gw@'lc/n, @Gw@'lénc; Latin ulna; Anglo-Saxon eln, English ell, elbow.
enough, etc.; See fuilear.
(ùill, H.S.D.), oil thou, uilleadh, oil (n.); See ola.
honeysuckle, so Irish (O'Br.), Middle Irish feithlend, woodbine; See under feith.
coffer (Carm.):
circum, Irish uim-, Old Irish imm-; a composition form of mu, q.v. Hence uime, about him, it, Irish uime, Old Irish uimbi; uimpe, about her (= imb-sì or imb-shi).

time, Irish uain, time, opportunity, Early Irish úine, Old Irish úain, leisure, time: *ut-nio-, root ut, vet of feith, wait. Strachan gives *ucn- as a reduced form, from euq, Sanskrit ókas, comfort, @Geu@'/kclos, free from care, at ease.
bustle, tumultus; See uainneart.
lambskin (Carm.); for uainicionn.
a window, Middle Gaelic fuinneóg, Middle Irish fuindeog, fuindeoc; from Norse windauga, Scottish winnock, English window (= wind-eye). From Anglo-Saxon windaége (Stokes, Lis.).
an onion, Irish uinniun, Middle Irish uinneamain, uindiun, Welsh wynwynyn; from Latin union-em, Old French oignon, English onion, from unus, one.  page 387
ankle:

ash, Irish uinseann, Middle Irish fuindseog, ash-tree, Old Irish ind-huinnius, Welsh on, onen, earlier onn, onnen, Breton ounnenn. Cornish onnen: *osnâ, *osnestu-; Latin ornus (*osinos); Lithuanian u@osis, ahs, Russ. jaseni@u. Cf. English ash.
unhandy craftsman, bungler:
a treasure, hoard; cf. uibe.
mould, dust, earth, Irish, Middle Irish úir, Early Irish úr, g. úire: *ûrâ; Norse aurr, loam, wet clay, mud, Anglo-Saxon eár, humus. Stokes hesitates between *ûrâ and *ugrâ, Greek u@`grós, wet.
a young pig, Irish uircín, Middle Irish orcán, porcellus, oircnín (do.), orc, porcus; *porko-s; Latin porcus; English farrow, pork; Lithuanian pàrszas, boar.
as much, amount, Irish oiread, Old Irish erat, airet, length of time, distance, cia eret, quamdiu: *are-vet-to-, root vet of feith.
below, down; See ioras.
need, poverty, so Irish, Middle Irish auresbadh; from air and easbhuidh, q.v.
faculty of speech, speech, Irish uirghíol, a command (O'Br.), uraghall, uradhall, speech (Keat.), Early Irish uirgill, for ur-fhuigell, Middle Irish urfhoighill:
last year, Irish annuraidh, Early Irish inn uraid, Old Irish urid: *peruti; Sanskrit parut, last year; Greek @Gpérusi, Dor. @Gpéruti; root vet of feith.
a couch, bed: *air-sed-, root sed of suidhe?
a precipice (H.S.D. from MSS.): *air-ailech, from ++ail, rock, q.v.
offspring of fairy and mortal (M`F.); See ùruisg.
a walled garden, Irish uirlios (O'Br., etc.); from air and lios.
a furnace, Irish uirnéis, fúirnéis (O'Br.), Middle Irish forneis; from English and Old French fornaise, Latin fornacem, fornax, oven.
tools, implements, Irish úirnéis ( Fol., O'R.), úirlis (Con.); See airneis.
a spreading (as of dung or hay to dry); from air and sgoil.
a fable, romance, so Irish; from air and sgeul.
use, utility; from the English use, Latin ûsus.
a lark, Irish uiseóg, fuiseóg, Welsh uchedydd, Breton ec'houedez, also Welsh ucheda, to soar; from *ux, up, as in uas, uasal?

water, Irish uisge, Old Irish uisce, usce: *ud-s-kio, root ud, ved; Greek @Gu@`/dwr, @Gu@`dos; English water, etc.; Sanskrit udán; further Latin unda, wave. Stokes suggests the possibility of uisge being for *uskio-, and allied to English wash.  page 388
disturbance, fury:
sport, diversion, Irish uslainn (Lh., etc.):
hist! whist! Latin st! English hist!

(pl.), beard, Irish, Early Irish ulcha, g. ulchain: *ulukon-; *pulu-, beard; Sanskrit pula, pulaka, horripilation; Greek @Gpúligges, hair of chairs (Hes.). Hence Ulaid, Ulster. It may be root ul, vel, cover (see olann).
block, pulley, "sonwball" (Wh.); from English pulley, Late Latin polanus?
oatmeal and water mixed:
a treasure, Irish uladh, charnel-house, Early Irish ulud, stone tomb; root ul, vel, cover? A Gadelic *alvet0, allied to Latin alvus, a belly, alveus, channel, has been suggested.
you brute! (Sutherland); from Norse úlfr, wolf.
(ul'ach), ashes, Welsh ulw, pl. ulwyn: *polviko-, *pôlven-; Latin pulvis, dust, pollen, pollen.
howling; from *ul, bark (Greek @Gu@`láw, bark, Latin ulula, owl, etc.), and art of comhart, q.v.
preparation, preparing, Irish ullmhuighim, I prepare; from ullamh, ready.
a mouthful of meal (Sh.); cf. ulag.

ready, Irish ullamh, for urlamh, Early Irish erlam, paratus; from air and lam, the latter being from làmh, hand: "to hand, handy". Usually referred to root las, desire, Latin lascivus, English lascivious.
a lapful, armful, Irish ullthach (O'Br.), Middle Irish utlach, lapful, urtlach, lap: *ar-tl@.-ac-; root tol, tel, lift (see toil, tlàth). Gaelic ulathach, burden in one's arms = ultach (Wh.).
dolt, blockhead; See umpaidh.
copper, brass, Irish umha, Old Irish humæ, ume, copper, brass, umaide, humide, aeneus, Welsh efydd, Old Welsh emid, aere; *umâjo- (Stokes), *omja (Ascoli), *um-ajo-, -ajo- = aes (Bez.).
heed, attention, Irish umhail, úmhail ( O'Br., Con.); cf. ùmhal.
obedient (umhailt, Dial.), Irish umhal, Early Irish, Old Irish umal, Welsh ufyll, Cornish huvel, Breton vuel; from Latin humilis, English humble.
a fine, unlagh (Arg.); from Scottish unlaw, unlach, a fine, transgression, un-law.
a boor, clown, idiot ( Sh., O'R.); See ùmaidh.
anoint, Irish ungaim, Old Irish ongim; from Latin ungue. Welsh has enenio from *o@+inj-.
an ounce, Irish únsa, Welsh wns; from English The Old Irish is unga, from Latin uncia.  page 389
adversity (Campbell's Tales, II. Mac-a-rusgaich); a form of an-rath?
push, ùpag, a push; cf. Welsh hwp, a push, effort. Cf. pùc. Onomatopoetic.

fresh, new, Irish, Early Irish úr, Old Irish húrde, vividarium, Welsh ir, fresh, green: *ûro-s, *pûro-s; Latin pûros, English pure. Usually referred to *ugro-s, Greek u@`grós, wet, Latin uvidus, moist, root ve@g.
thole pin (N.Lochaber). Cf. àrcan, a cork.
a shot, cast, Irish urchur, Early Irish urchur, aurchor, erchor, Welsh ergyr, Old B. ercor, ictum: *are-koru-, a cast; from cuir, send, q.v.
fetters, shackles, so Irish (Lh., etc.): *are-col-, root col, cel of timchioll?
physic, antidote, Irish urchosg, preservative, antidote: *air-chosg, from cosg, caisg, stop, q.v.
hurt, mischief, Irish urchóid, Old Irish erchoit: *are-kkonti-, Greek @Gkentéw, stick, prick, @Gkaínw, kill. Stokes prefers *skonti-, as stem, allied to English scathe.
face, hair, breast, Irish urla, lock of hair, long hair of the head, Early Irish urla, irla: *air-la-, where la is for vla, root vel of falt?
eloquence, Irish urlabhair, elocution, Early Irish erlabra: *air-labhair; See labhair.
stag (R.D.):
turn from in disgust (Arg.):
readiness (M`F.), Irish úrlamh, ready; See ullamh. Hence also ùrlaimh, expert, Old Irish erlam, irlam.
possession, Irish úrlámhus, forlamhus; from for-, super, and làmh, hand: "upper-handed-ness".
a staff, Irish úrlann, a staff, spear staff, Middle Irish urlann, staff of a spear: *air-lann, from lann: also Early Irish irlond, hinder end of a spear or ship.

a floor, lowest part, Irish urlár: *air-lár, from làr, floor, q.v. irnigde, irnichte: *are-nakô, I strive for, root nak, enk, as in thig? Zimmer gives the root i@gh, desire, Greek @Gi@'hana@nn, desire, Lithuanian igiju, strive after, Sanskrit îh, long for, dividing it into *air-con-ig (*air-in-ig?). Old ?Irish arnigim: ig = Greek @Gi@'har; arn = *paran, Greek pará ( St. Zeit. 36).
a person, infant; cf. urradh.

authority, guarantee, author, Irish urra(dh), surety, author, defendant, urrain, stay, prop, Middle Irish errudus, responsibility; from ràth, ràthan, surety. Urradha were a chief's "gentlemen" paying rent or servic (Sil.Gad.).  page 390
power, is urrainn, can; Irish urra, power, urrain, stay. See urradh.
forward, bold, urranta, Irish urránta, bold, confident in one's might; from urradh.
honour, respect, Irish urram, urraim, honour, deference, submission, Middle Irish urraim, homage: *air-réim?
surety, guarantee, Irish urrúdhas, urrús; from urradh.
a door-post, Irish ursa, g. ursann, Early Irish ursa, aursa, irsa, d. ursaind, Welsh gorsin: *are-stan-, root sta, stand.
a Brownie; from uisge, air+ uisg.
impudence (M`A.):
easier, Irish usa, Old Irish assu, facilius, asse, facilis; cf. Welsh haws, from hawdd, easy; further French aisé, English easy, Gothic azets, easy.
querulousness ( M`A. and Wh.):
a jewel, bell on liquor:
holy, sacred (Carm.):
a push, pang, Irish uspóg; cf. ospag.
an ugly or lumpish fellow, Irish uspán, a shapeless lump, chaos, clumsy fellow. See uspan.
strife, Irish uspairneachd: *ud-spairn, from spàirn.
a shapeless mass, Irish uspán: also usp (ùsp); cf. uibe, *uibs-?
interjection of disapprobation, English tut, hoot, Welsh hwt, etc.
(Arg.), strife, confusion; also "push, jostle", ut, push. Cf. put, putag.
a knuckle (Sh., O'R.), better utan:

an udder, Early Irish uth. Stokes gives the stem as *(p)utu-, Lithuanian suputimas, a swelling, putlùs, swollen. Latin ûber, Greek @Gou@'@nqar, English udder have been compared, but the Gadelic lacks the terminal -er, and the consonant is t rather than d or dh. Cf. Latin uter, skin-bag.
above, on high, Irish ós, árd. Gaelic is for *for-ard, "on high"; See air and àrd.
district road (Carm.); See ùdrathad.
a confused mass of anything, a fidgeting.
